2435 '"except" clause\n'
2436 '---------------\n'
2437 '\n'
2438 'The "except" clause(s) specify one or more exception handlers. '
2439 'When no\n'
2440 'exception occurs in the "try" clause, no exception handler is\n'
2441 'executed. When an exception occurs in the "try" suite, a search '
2442 'for an\n'
2443 'exception handler is started. This search inspects the "except"\n'
2444 'clauses in turn until one is found that matches the exception. '
2445 'An\n'
2446 'expression-less "except" clause, if present, must be last; it '
2447 'matches\n'
2448 'any exception. For an "except" clause with an expression, that\n'
2449 'expression is evaluated, and the clause matches the exception if '
2450 'the\n'
2451 'resulting object is “compatible” with the exception. An object '
2452 'is\n'
2453 'compatible with an exception if the object is the class or a '
2454 '*non-\n'
2455 'virtual base class* of the exception object, or a tuple '
2456 'containing an\n'
2457 'item that is the class or a non-virtual base class of the '
2458 'exception\n'
2459 'object.\n'
2460 '\n'
2461 'If no "except" clause matches the exception, the search for an\n'
2462 'exception handler continues in the surrounding code and on the\n'
2463 'invocation stack. [1]\n'
2464 '\n'
2465 'If the evaluation of an expression in the header of an "except" '
2466 'clause\n'
2467 'raises an exception, the original search for a handler is '
2468 'canceled and\n'
2469 'a search starts for the new exception in the surrounding code '
2470 'and on\n'
2471 'the call stack (it is treated as if the entire "try" statement '
2472 'raised\n'
2473 'the exception).\n'
2474 '\n'
2475 'When a matching "except" clause is found, the exception is '
2476 'assigned to\n'
2477 'the target specified after the "as" keyword in that "except" '
2478 'clause,\n'
2479 'if present, and the "except" clause’s suite is executed. All '
2480 '"except"\n'
2481 'clauses must have an executable block. When the end of this '
2482 'block is\n'
2483 'reached, execution continues normally after the entire "try"\n'
2484 'statement. (This means that if two nested handlers exist for the '
2485 'same\n'
2486 'exception, and the exception occurs in the "try" clause of the '
2487 'inner\n'
2488 'handler, the outer handler will not handle the exception.)\n'
2489 '\n'
2490 'When an exception has been assigned using "as target", it is '
2491 'cleared\n'
2492 'at the end of the "except" clause. This is as if\n'
2493 '\n'
2494 ' except E as N:\n'
2495 ' foo\n'
2496 '\n'
2497 'was translated to\n'
2498 '\n'
2499 ' except E as N:\n'
2500 ' try:\n'
2501 ' foo\n'
2502 ' finally:\n'
2503 ' del N\n'
2504 '\n'
2505 'This means the exception must be assigned to a different name to '
2506 'be\n'
2507 'able to refer to it after the "except" clause. Exceptions are '
2508 'cleared\n'
2509 'because with the traceback attached to them, they form a '
2510 'reference\n'
2511 'cycle with the stack frame, keeping all locals in that frame '
2512 'alive\n'
2513 'until the next garbage collection occurs.\n'
2514 '\n'
2515 'Before an "except" clause’s suite is executed, the exception is '
2516 'stored\n'
2517 'in the "sys" module, where it can be accessed from within the '
2518 'body of\n'
2519 'the "except" clause by calling "sys.exception()". When leaving '
2520 'an\n'
2521 'exception handler, the exception stored in the "sys" module is '
2522 'reset\n'
2523 'to its previous value:\n'
2524 '\n'
2525 ' >>> print(sys.exception())\n'
2526 ' None\n'
2527 ' >>> try:\n'
2528 ' ... raise TypeError\n'
2529 ' ... except:\n'
2530 ' ... print(repr(sys.exception()))\n'
2531 ' ... try:\n'
2532 ' ... raise ValueError\n'
2533 ' ... except:\n'
2534 ' ... print(repr(sys.exception()))\n'
2535 ' ... print(repr(sys.exception()))\n'
2536 ' ...\n'
2537 ' TypeError()\n'
2538 ' ValueError()\n'
2539 ' TypeError()\n'
2540 ' >>> print(sys.exception())\n'
2541 ' None\n'
2542 '\n'
2543 '\n'
2544 '"except*" clause\n'
2545 '----------------\n'
2546 '\n'
2547 'The "except*" clause(s) are used for handling "ExceptionGroup"s. '
2548 'The\n'
2549 'exception type for matching is interpreted as in the case of '
2550 '"except",\n'
2551 'but in the case of exception groups we can have partial matches '
2552 'when\n'
2553 'the type matches some of the exceptions in the group. This means '
2554 'that\n'
2555 'multiple "except*" clauses can execute, each handling part of '
2556 'the\n'
2557 'exception group. Each clause executes at most once and handles '
2558 'an\n'
2559 'exception group of all matching exceptions. Each exception in '
2560 'the\n'
2561 'group is handled by at most one "except*" clause, the first '
2562 'that\n'
2563 'matches it.\n'
2564 '\n'
2565 ' >>> try:\n'
2566 ' ... raise ExceptionGroup("eg",\n'
2567 ' ... [ValueError(1), TypeError(2), OSError(3), '
2568 'OSError(4)])\n'
2569 ' ... except* TypeError as e:\n'
2570 " ... print(f'caught {type(e)} with nested "
2571 "{e.exceptions}')\n"
2572 ' ... except* OSError as e:\n'
2573 " ... print(f'caught {type(e)} with nested "
2574 "{e.exceptions}')\n"
2575 ' ...\n'
2576 " caught <class 'ExceptionGroup'> with nested (TypeError(2),)\n"
2577 " caught <class 'ExceptionGroup'> with nested (OSError(3), "
2578 'OSError(4))\n'
2579 ' + Exception Group Traceback (most recent call last):\n'
2580 ' | File "<stdin>", line 2, in <module>\n'
2581 ' | ExceptionGroup: eg\n'
2582 ' +-+---------------- 1 ----------------\n'
2583 ' | ValueError: 1\n'
2584 ' +------------------------------------\n'
2585 '\n'
2586 'Any remaining exceptions that were not handled by any "except*" '
2587 'clause\n'
2588 'are re-raised at the end, combined into an exception group along '
2589 'with\n'
2590 'all exceptions that were raised from within "except*" clauses.\n'
2591 '\n'
2592 'From version 3.11.4, when the entire "ExceptionGroup" is handled '
2593 'and\n'
2594 'only one exception is raised from an "except*" clause, this '
2595 'exception\n'
2596 'is no longer wrapped to form a new "ExceptionGroup".\n'
2597 '\n'
2598 'If the raised exception is not an exception group and its type '
2599 'matches\n'
2600 'one of the "except*" clauses, it is caught and wrapped by an '
2601 'exception\n'
2602 'group with an empty message string.\n'
2603 '\n'
2604 ' >>> try:\n'
2605 ' ... raise BlockingIOError\n'
2606 ' ... except* BlockingIOError as e:\n'
2607 ' ... print(repr(e))\n'
2608 ' ...\n'
2609 " ExceptionGroup('', (BlockingIOError()))\n"
2610 '\n'
2611 'An "except*" clause must have a matching type, and this type '
2612 'cannot be\n'
2613 'a subclass of "BaseExceptionGroup". It is not possible to mix '
2614 '"except"\n'
2615 'and "except*" in the same "try". "break", "continue" and '
2616 '"return"\n'
2617 'cannot appear in an "except*" clause.\n'
2618 '\n'
2619 '\n'
2620 '"else" clause\n'
2621 '-------------\n'
2622 '\n'
2623 'The optional "else" clause is executed if the control flow '
2624 'leaves the\n'
2625 '"try" suite, no exception was raised, and no "return", '
2626 '"continue", or\n'
2627 '"break" statement was executed. Exceptions in the "else" clause '
2628 'are\n'
2629 'not handled by the preceding "except" clauses.\n'
2630 '\n'
2631 '\n'
2632 '"finally" clause\n'
2633 '----------------\n'
2634 '\n'
2635 'If "finally" is present, it specifies a ‘cleanup’ handler. The '
2636 '"try"\n'
2637 'clause is executed, including any "except" and "else" clauses. '
2638 'If an\n'
2639 'exception occurs in any of the clauses and is not handled, the\n'
2640 'exception is temporarily saved. The "finally" clause is '
2641 'executed. If\n'
2642 'there is a saved exception it is re-raised at the end of the '
2643 '"finally"\n'
2644 'clause. If the "finally" clause raises another exception, the '
2645 'saved\n'
2646 'exception is set as the context of the new exception. If the '
2647 '"finally"\n'
2648 'clause executes a "return", "break" or "continue" statement, the '
2649 'saved\n'
2650 'exception is discarded:\n'
2651 '\n'
2652 ' >>> def f():\n'
2653 ' ... try:\n'
2654 ' ... 1/0\n'
2655 ' ... finally:\n'
2656 ' ... return 42\n'
2657 ' ...\n'
2658 ' >>> f()\n'
2659 ' 42\n'
2660 '\n'
2661 'The exception information is not available to the program '
2662 'during\n'
2663 'execution of the "finally" clause.\n'
2664 '\n'
2665 'When a "return", "break" or "continue" statement is executed in '
2666 'the\n'
2667 '"try" suite of a "try"…"finally" statement, the "finally" clause '
2668 'is\n'
2669 'also executed ‘on the way out.’\n'
2670 '\n'
2671 'The return value of a function is determined by the last '
2672 '"return"\n'
2673 'statement executed. Since the "finally" clause always executes, '
2674 'a\n'
2675 '"return" statement executed in the "finally" clause will always '
2676 'be the\n'
2677 'last one executed:\n'
2678 '\n'
2679 ' >>> def foo():\n'
2680 ' ... try:\n'
2681 " ... return 'try'\n"
2682 ' ... finally:\n'
2683 " ... return 'finally'\n"
2684 ' ...\n'
2685 ' >>> foo()\n'
2686 " 'finally'\n"
2687 '\n'
2688 'Changed in version 3.8: Prior to Python 3.8, a "continue" '
2689 'statement\n'
2690 'was illegal in the "finally" clause due to a problem with the\n'
2691 'implementation.\n'
2692 '\n'
2693 '\n'
2694 'The "with" statement\n'
2695 '====================\n'
2696 '\n'
2697 'The "with" statement is used to wrap the execution of a block '
2698 'with\n'
2699 'methods defined by a context manager (see section With '
2700 'Statement\n'
2701 'Context Managers). This allows common "try"…"except"…"finally" '
2702 'usage\n'
2703 'patterns to be encapsulated for convenient reuse.\n'
2704 '\n'
2705 ' with_stmt ::= "with" ( "(" with_stmt_contents ","? '
2706 '")" | with_stmt_contents ) ":" suite\n'
2707 ' with_stmt_contents ::= with_item ("," with_item)*\n'
2708 ' with_item ::= expression ["as" target]\n'
2709 '\n'
2710 'The execution of the "with" statement with one “item” proceeds '
2711 'as\n'
2712 'follows:\n'
2713 '\n'
2714 '1. The context expression (the expression given in the '
2715 '"with_item") is\n'
2716 ' evaluated to obtain a context manager.\n'
2717 '\n'
2718 '2. The context manager’s "__enter__()" is loaded for later use.\n'
2719 '\n'
2720 '3. The context manager’s "__exit__()" is loaded for later use.\n'
2721 '\n'
2722 '4. The context manager’s "__enter__()" method is invoked.\n'
2723 '\n'
2724 '5. If a target was included in the "with" statement, the return '
2725 'value\n'
2726 ' from "__enter__()" is assigned to it.\n'
2727 '\n'
2728 ' Note:\n'
2729 '\n'
2730 ' The "with" statement guarantees that if the "__enter__()" '
2731 'method\n'
2732 ' returns without an error, then "__exit__()" will always be\n'
2733 ' called. Thus, if an error occurs during the assignment to '
2734 'the\n'
2735 ' target list, it will be treated the same as an error '
2736 'occurring\n'
2737 ' within the suite would be. See step 7 below.\n'
2738 '\n'
2739 '6. The suite is executed.\n'
2740 '\n'
2741 '7. The context manager’s "__exit__()" method is invoked. If an\n'
2742 ' exception caused the suite to be exited, its type, value, '
2743 'and\n'
2744 ' traceback are passed as arguments to "__exit__()". Otherwise, '
2745 'three\n'
2746 ' "None" arguments are supplied.\n'
2747 '\n'
2748 ' If the suite was exited due to an exception, and the return '
2749 'value\n'
2750 ' from the "__exit__()" method was false, the exception is '
2751 'reraised.\n'
2752 ' If the return value was true, the exception is suppressed, '
2753 'and\n'
2754 ' execution continues with the statement following the "with"\n'
2755 ' statement.\n'
2756 '\n'
2757 ' If the suite was exited for any reason other than an '
2758 'exception, the\n'
2759 ' return value from "__exit__()" is ignored, and execution '
2760 'proceeds\n'
2761 ' at the normal location for the kind of exit that was taken.\n'
2762 '\n'
2763 'The following code:\n'
2764 '\n'
2765 ' with EXPRESSION as TARGET:\n'
2766 ' SUITE\n'
2767 '\n'
2768 'is semantically equivalent to:\n'
2769 '\n'
2770 ' manager = (EXPRESSION)\n'
2771 ' enter = type(manager).__enter__\n'
2772 ' exit = type(manager).__exit__\n'
2773 ' value = enter(manager)\n'
2774 ' hit_except = False\n'
2775 '\n'
2776 ' try:\n'
2777 ' TARGET = value\n'
2778 ' SUITE\n'
2779 ' except:\n'
2780 ' hit_except = True\n'
2781 ' if not exit(manager, *sys.exc_info()):\n'
2782 ' raise\n'
2783 ' finally:\n'
2784 ' if not hit_except:\n'
2785 ' exit(manager, None, None, None)\n'
2786 '\n'
2787 'With more than one item, the context managers are processed as '
2788 'if\n'
2789 'multiple "with" statements were nested:\n'
2790 '\n'
2791 ' with A() as a, B() as b:\n'
2792 ' SUITE\n'
2793 '\n'
2794 'is semantically equivalent to:\n'
2795 '\n'
2796 ' with A() as a:\n'
2797 ' with B() as b:\n'
2798 ' SUITE\n'
2799 '\n'
2800 'You can also write multi-item context managers in multiple lines '
2801 'if\n'
2802 'the items are surrounded by parentheses. For example:\n'
2803 '\n'
2804 ' with (\n'
2805 ' A() as a,\n'
2806 ' B() as b,\n'
2807 ' ):\n'
2808 ' SUITE\n'
2809 '\n'
2810 'Changed in version 3.1: Support for multiple context '
2811 'expressions.\n'
2812 '\n'
2813 'Changed in version 3.10: Support for using grouping parentheses '
2814 'to\n'
2815 'break the statement in multiple lines.\n'
2816 '\n'
2817 'See also:\n'
2818 '\n'
2819 ' **PEP 343** - The “with” statement\n'
2820 ' The specification, background, and examples for the Python '
2821 '"with"\n'
2822 ' statement.\n'
2823 '\n'
2824 '\n'
2825 'The "match" statement\n'
2826 '=====================\n'
2827 '\n'
2828 'New in version 3.10.\n'
2829 '\n'
2830 'The match statement is used for pattern matching. Syntax:\n'
2831 '\n'
2832 ' match_stmt ::= \'match\' subject_expr ":" NEWLINE INDENT '
2833 'case_block+ DEDENT\n'
2834 ' subject_expr ::= star_named_expression "," '
2835 'star_named_expressions?\n'
2836 ' | named_expression\n'
2837 ' case_block ::= \'case\' patterns [guard] ":" block\n'
2838 '\n'
2839 'Note:\n'
2840 '\n'
2841 ' This section uses single quotes to denote soft keywords.\n'
2842 '\n'
2843 'Pattern matching takes a pattern as input (following "case") and '
2844 'a\n'
2845 'subject value (following "match"). The pattern (which may '
2846 'contain\n'
2847 'subpatterns) is matched against the subject value. The outcomes '
2848 'are:\n'
2849 '\n'
2850 '* A match success or failure (also termed a pattern success or\n'
2851 ' failure).\n'
2852 '\n'
2853 '* Possible binding of matched values to a name. The '
2854 'prerequisites for\n'
2855 ' this are further discussed below.\n'
2856 '\n'
2857 'The "match" and "case" keywords are soft keywords.\n'
2858 '\n'
2859 'See also:\n'
2860 '\n'
2861 ' * **PEP 634** – Structural Pattern Matching: Specification\n'
2862 '\n'
2863 ' * **PEP 636** – Structural Pattern Matching: Tutorial\n'
2864 '\n'
2865 '\n'
2866 'Overview\n'
2867 '--------\n'
2868 '\n'
2869 'Here’s an overview of the logical flow of a match statement:\n'
2870 '\n'
2871 '1. The subject expression "subject_expr" is evaluated and a '
2872 'resulting\n'
2873 ' subject value obtained. If the subject expression contains a '
2874 'comma,\n'
2875 ' a tuple is constructed using the standard rules.\n'
2876 '\n'
2877 '2. Each pattern in a "case_block" is attempted to match with '
2878 'the\n'
2879 ' subject value. The specific rules for success or failure are\n'
2880 ' described below. The match attempt can also bind some or all '
2881 'of the\n'
2882 ' standalone names within the pattern. The precise pattern '
2883 'binding\n'
2884 ' rules vary per pattern type and are specified below. **Name\n'
2885 ' bindings made during a successful pattern match outlive the\n'
2886 ' executed block and can be used after the match statement**.\n'
2887 '\n'
2888 ' Note:\n'
2889 '\n'
2890 ' During failed pattern matches, some subpatterns may '
2891 'succeed. Do\n'
2892 ' not rely on bindings being made for a failed match. '
2893 'Conversely,\n'
2894 ' do not rely on variables remaining unchanged after a '
2895 'failed\n'
2896 ' match. The exact behavior is dependent on implementation '
2897 'and may\n'
2898 ' vary. This is an intentional decision made to allow '
2899 'different\n'
2900 ' implementations to add optimizations.\n'
2901 '\n'
2902 '3. If the pattern succeeds, the corresponding guard (if present) '
2903 'is\n'
2904 ' evaluated. In this case all name bindings are guaranteed to '
2905 'have\n'
2906 ' happened.\n'
2907 '\n'
2908 ' * If the guard evaluates as true or is missing, the "block" '
2909 'inside\n'
2910 ' "case_block" is executed.\n'
2911 '\n'
2912 ' * Otherwise, the next "case_block" is attempted as described '
2913 'above.\n'
2914 '\n'
2915 ' * If there are no further case blocks, the match statement '
2916 'is\n'
2917 ' completed.\n'
2918 '\n'
2919 'Note:\n'
2920 '\n'
2921 ' Users should generally never rely on a pattern being '
2922 'evaluated.\n'
2923 ' Depending on implementation, the interpreter may cache values '
2924 'or use\n'
2925 ' other optimizations which skip repeated evaluations.\n'
2926 '\n'
2927 'A sample match statement:\n'
2928 '\n'
2929 ' >>> flag = False\n'
2930 ' >>> match (100, 200):\n'
2931 ' ... case (100, 300): # Mismatch: 200 != 300\n'
2932 " ... print('Case 1')\n"
2933 ' ... case (100, 200) if flag: # Successful match, but '
2934 'guard fails\n'
2935 " ... print('Case 2')\n"
2936 ' ... case (100, y): # Matches and binds y to 200\n'
2937 " ... print(f'Case 3, y: {y}')\n"
2938 ' ... case _: # Pattern not attempted\n'
2939 " ... print('Case 4, I match anything!')\n"
2940 ' ...\n'
2941 ' Case 3, y: 200\n'
2942 '\n'
2943 'In this case, "if flag" is a guard. Read more about that in the '
2944 'next\n'
2945 'section.\n'
2946 '\n'
2947 '\n'
2948 'Guards\n'
2949 '------\n'
2950 '\n'
2951 ' guard ::= "if" named_expression\n'
2952 '\n'
2953 'A "guard" (which is part of the "case") must succeed for code '
2954 'inside\n'
2955 'the "case" block to execute. It takes the form: "if" followed '
2956 'by an\n'
2957 'expression.\n'
2958 '\n'
2959 'The logical flow of a "case" block with a "guard" follows:\n'
2960 '\n'
2961 '1. Check that the pattern in the "case" block succeeded. If '
2962 'the\n'
2963 ' pattern failed, the "guard" is not evaluated and the next '
2964 '"case"\n'
2965 ' block is checked.\n'
2966 '\n'
2967 '2. If the pattern succeeded, evaluate the "guard".\n'
2968 '\n'
2969 ' * If the "guard" condition evaluates as true, the case block '
2970 'is\n'
2971 ' selected.\n'
2972 '\n'
2973 ' * If the "guard" condition evaluates as false, the case block '
2974 'is\n'
2975 ' not selected.\n'
2976 '\n'
2977 ' * If the "guard" raises an exception during evaluation, the\n'
2978 ' exception bubbles up.\n'
2979 '\n'
2980 'Guards are allowed to have side effects as they are '
2981 'expressions.\n'
2982 'Guard evaluation must proceed from the first to the last case '
2983 'block,\n'
2984 'one at a time, skipping case blocks whose pattern(s) don’t all\n'
2985 'succeed. (I.e., guard evaluation must happen in order.) Guard\n'
2986 'evaluation must stop once a case block is selected.\n'
2987 '\n'
2988 '\n'
2989 'Irrefutable Case Blocks\n'
2990 '-----------------------\n'
2991 '\n'
2992 'An irrefutable case block is a match-all case block. A match\n'
2993 'statement may have at most one irrefutable case block, and it '
2994 'must be\n'
2995 'last.\n'
2996 '\n'
2997 'A case block is considered irrefutable if it has no guard and '
2998 'its\n'
2999 'pattern is irrefutable. A pattern is considered irrefutable if '
3000 'we can\n'
3001 'prove from its syntax alone that it will always succeed. Only '
3002 'the\n'
3003 'following patterns are irrefutable:\n'
3004 '\n'
3005 '* AS Patterns whose left-hand side is irrefutable\n'
3006 '\n'
3007 '* OR Patterns containing at least one irrefutable pattern\n'
3008 '\n'
3009 '* Capture Patterns\n'
3010 '\n'
3011 '* Wildcard Patterns\n'
3012 '\n'
3013 '* parenthesized irrefutable patterns\n'
3014 '\n'
3015 '\n'
3016 'Patterns\n'
3017 '--------\n'
3018 '\n'
3019 'Note:\n'
3020 '\n'
3021 ' This section uses grammar notations beyond standard EBNF:\n'
3022 '\n'
3023 ' * the notation "SEP.RULE+" is shorthand for "RULE (SEP '
3024 'RULE)*"\n'
3025 '\n'
3026 ' * the notation "!RULE" is shorthand for a negative lookahead\n'
3027 ' assertion\n'
3028 '\n'
3029 'The top-level syntax for "patterns" is:\n'
3030 '\n'
3031 ' patterns ::= open_sequence_pattern | pattern\n'
3032 ' pattern ::= as_pattern | or_pattern\n'
3033 ' closed_pattern ::= | literal_pattern\n'
3034 ' | capture_pattern\n'
3035 ' | wildcard_pattern\n'
3036 ' | value_pattern\n'
3037 ' | group_pattern\n'
3038 ' | sequence_pattern\n'
3039 ' | mapping_pattern\n'
3040 ' | class_pattern\n'
3041 '\n'
3042 'The descriptions below will include a description “in simple '
3043 'terms” of\n'
3044 'what a pattern does for illustration purposes (credits to '
3045 'Raymond\n'
3046 'Hettinger for a document that inspired most of the '
3047 'descriptions). Note\n'
3048 'that these descriptions are purely for illustration purposes and '
3049 '**may\n'
3050 'not** reflect the underlying implementation. Furthermore, they '
3051 'do not\n'
3052 'cover all valid forms.\n'
3053 '\n'
3054 '\n'
3055 'OR Patterns\n'
3056 '~~~~~~~~~~~\n'
3057 '\n'
3058 'An OR pattern is two or more patterns separated by vertical bars '
3059 '"|".\n'
3060 'Syntax:\n'
3061 '\n'
3062 ' or_pattern ::= "|".closed_pattern+\n'
3063 '\n'
3064 'Only the final subpattern may be irrefutable, and each '
3065 'subpattern must\n'
3066 'bind the same set of names to avoid ambiguity.\n'
3067 '\n'
3068 'An OR pattern matches each of its subpatterns in turn to the '
3069 'subject\n'
3070 'value, until one succeeds. The OR pattern is then considered\n'
3071 'successful. Otherwise, if none of the subpatterns succeed, the '
3072 'OR\n'
3073 'pattern fails.\n'
3074 '\n'
3075 'In simple terms, "P1 | P2 | ..." will try to match "P1", if it '
3076 'fails\n'
3077 'it will try to match "P2", succeeding immediately if any '
3078 'succeeds,\n'
3079 'failing otherwise.\n'
3080 '\n'
3081 '\n'
3082 'AS Patterns\n'
3083 '~~~~~~~~~~~\n'
3084 '\n'
3085 'An AS pattern matches an OR pattern on the left of the "as" '
3086 'keyword\n'
3087 'against a subject. Syntax:\n'
3088 '\n'
3089 ' as_pattern ::= or_pattern "as" capture_pattern\n'
3090 '\n'
3091 'If the OR pattern fails, the AS pattern fails. Otherwise, the '
3092 'AS\n'
3093 'pattern binds the subject to the name on the right of the as '
3094 'keyword\n'
3095 'and succeeds. "capture_pattern" cannot be a "_".\n'
3096 '\n'
3097 'In simple terms "P as NAME" will match with "P", and on success '
3098 'it\n'
3099 'will set "NAME = <subject>".\n'
3100 '\n'
3101 '\n'
3102 'Literal Patterns\n'
3103 '~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n'
3104 '\n'
3105 'A literal pattern corresponds to most literals in Python. '
3106 'Syntax:\n'
3107 '\n'
3108 ' literal_pattern ::= signed_number\n'
3109 ' | signed_number "+" NUMBER\n'
3110 ' | signed_number "-" NUMBER\n'
3111 ' | strings\n'
3112 ' | "None"\n'
3113 ' | "True"\n'
3114 ' | "False"\n'
3115 ' | signed_number: NUMBER | "-" NUMBER\n'
3116 '\n'
3117 'The rule "strings" and the token "NUMBER" are defined in the '
3118 'standard\n'
3119 'Python grammar. Triple-quoted strings are supported. Raw '
3120 'strings and\n'
3121 'byte strings are supported. f-strings are not supported.\n'
3122 '\n'
3123 'The forms "signed_number \'+\' NUMBER" and "signed_number \'-\' '
3124 'NUMBER"\n'
3125 'are for expressing complex numbers; they require a real number '
3126 'on the\n'
3127 'left and an imaginary number on the right. E.g. "3 + 4j".\n'
3128 '\n'
3129 'In simple terms, "LITERAL" will succeed only if "<subject> ==\n'
3130 'LITERAL". For the singletons "None", "True" and "False", the '
3131 '"is"\n'
3132 'operator is used.\n'
3133 '\n'
3134 '\n'
3135 'Capture Patterns\n'
3136 '~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n'
3137 '\n'
3138 'A capture pattern binds the subject value to a name. Syntax:\n'
3139 '\n'
3140 " capture_pattern ::= !'_' NAME\n"
3141 '\n'
3142 'A single underscore "_" is not a capture pattern (this is what '
3143 '"!\'_\'"\n'
3144 'expresses). It is instead treated as a "wildcard_pattern".\n'
3145 '\n'
3146 'In a given pattern, a given name can only be bound once. E.g. '
3147 '"case\n'
3148 'x, x: ..." is invalid while "case [x] | x: ..." is allowed.\n'
3149 '\n'
3150 'Capture patterns always succeed. The binding follows scoping '
3151 'rules\n'
3152 'established by the assignment expression operator in **PEP '
3153 '572**; the\n'
3154 'name becomes a local variable in the closest containing function '
3155 'scope\n'
3156 'unless there’s an applicable "global" or "nonlocal" statement.\n'
3157 '\n'
3158 'In simple terms "NAME" will always succeed and it will set "NAME '
3159 '=\n'
3160 '<subject>".\n'
3161 '\n'
3162 '\n'
3163 'Wildcard Patterns\n'
3164 '~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n'
3165 '\n'
3166 'A wildcard pattern always succeeds (matches anything) and binds '
3167 'no\n'
3168 'name. Syntax:\n'
3169 '\n'
3170 " wildcard_pattern ::= '_'\n"
3171 '\n'
3172 '"_" is a soft keyword within any pattern, but only within '
3173 'patterns.\n'
3174 'It is an identifier, as usual, even within "match" subject\n'
3175 'expressions, "guard"s, and "case" blocks.\n'
3176 '\n'
3177 'In simple terms, "_" will always succeed.\n'
3178 '\n'
3179 '\n'
3180 'Value Patterns\n'
3181 '~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n'
3182 '\n'
3183 'A value pattern represents a named value in Python. Syntax:\n'
3184 '\n'
3185 ' value_pattern ::= attr\n'
3186 ' attr ::= name_or_attr "." NAME\n'
3187 ' name_or_attr ::= attr | NAME\n'
3188 '\n'
3189 'The dotted name in the pattern is looked up using standard '
3190 'Python name\n'
3191 'resolution rules. The pattern succeeds if the value found '
3192 'compares\n'
3193 'equal to the subject value (using the "==" equality operator).\n'
3194 '\n'
3195 'In simple terms "NAME1.NAME2" will succeed only if "<subject> '
3196 '==\n'
3197 'NAME1.NAME2"\n'
3198 '\n'
3199 'Note:\n'
3200 '\n'
3201 ' If the same value occurs multiple times in the same match '
3202 'statement,\n'
3203 ' the interpreter may cache the first value found and reuse it '
3204 'rather\n'
3205 ' than repeat the same lookup. This cache is strictly tied to a '
3206 'given\n'
3207 ' execution of a given match statement.\n'
3208 '\n'
3209 '\n'
3210 'Group Patterns\n'
3211 '~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n'
3212 '\n'
3213 'A group pattern allows users to add parentheses around patterns '
3214 'to\n'
3215 'emphasize the intended grouping. Otherwise, it has no '
3216 'additional\n'
3217 'syntax. Syntax:\n'
3218 '\n'
3219 ' group_pattern ::= "(" pattern ")"\n'
3220 '\n'
3221 'In simple terms "(P)" has the same effect as "P".\n'
3222 '\n'
3223 '\n'
3224 'Sequence Patterns\n'
3225 '~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n'
3226 '\n'
3227 'A sequence pattern contains several subpatterns to be matched '
3228 'against\n'
3229 'sequence elements. The syntax is similar to the unpacking of a '
3230 'list or\n'
3231 'tuple.\n'
3232 '\n'
3233 ' sequence_pattern ::= "[" [maybe_sequence_pattern] "]"\n'
3234 ' | "(" [open_sequence_pattern] ")"\n'
3235 ' open_sequence_pattern ::= maybe_star_pattern "," '
3236 '[maybe_sequence_pattern]\n'
3237 ' maybe_sequence_pattern ::= ",".maybe_star_pattern+ ","?\n'
3238 ' maybe_star_pattern ::= star_pattern | pattern\n'
3239 ' star_pattern ::= "*" (capture_pattern | '
3240 'wildcard_pattern)\n'
3241 '\n'
3242 'There is no difference if parentheses or square brackets are '
3243 'used for\n'
3244 'sequence patterns (i.e. "(...)" vs "[...]" ).\n'
3245 '\n'
3246 'Note:\n'
3247 '\n'
3248 ' A single pattern enclosed in parentheses without a trailing '
3249 'comma\n'
3250 ' (e.g. "(3 | 4)") is a group pattern. While a single pattern '
3251 'enclosed\n'
3252 ' in square brackets (e.g. "[3 | 4]") is still a sequence '
3253 'pattern.\n'
3254 '\n'
3255 'At most one star subpattern may be in a sequence pattern. The '
3256 'star\n'
3257 'subpattern may occur in any position. If no star subpattern is\n'
3258 'present, the sequence pattern is a fixed-length sequence '
3259 'pattern;\n'
3260 'otherwise it is a variable-length sequence pattern.\n'
3261 '\n'
3262 'The following is the logical flow for matching a sequence '
3263 'pattern\n'
3264 'against a subject value:\n'
3265 '\n'
3266 '1. If the subject value is not a sequence [2], the sequence '
3267 'pattern\n'
3268 ' fails.\n'
3269 '\n'
3270 '2. If the subject value is an instance of "str", "bytes" or\n'
3271 ' "bytearray" the sequence pattern fails.\n'
3272 '\n'
3273 '3. The subsequent steps depend on whether the sequence pattern '
3274 'is\n'
3275 ' fixed or variable-length.\n'
3276 '\n'
3277 ' If the sequence pattern is fixed-length:\n'
3278 '\n'
3279 ' 1. If the length of the subject sequence is not equal to the '
3280 'number\n'
3281 ' of subpatterns, the sequence pattern fails\n'
3282 '\n'
3283 ' 2. Subpatterns in the sequence pattern are matched to their\n'
3284 ' corresponding items in the subject sequence from left to '
3285 'right.\n'
3286 ' Matching stops as soon as a subpattern fails. If all\n'
3287 ' subpatterns succeed in matching their corresponding item, '
3288 'the\n'
3289 ' sequence pattern succeeds.\n'
3290 '\n'
3291 ' Otherwise, if the sequence pattern is variable-length:\n'
3292 '\n'
3293 ' 1. If the length of the subject sequence is less than the '
3294 'number of\n'
3295 ' non-star subpatterns, the sequence pattern fails.\n'
3296 '\n'
3297 ' 2. The leading non-star subpatterns are matched to their\n'
3298 ' corresponding items as for fixed-length sequences.\n'
3299 '\n'
3300 ' 3. If the previous step succeeds, the star subpattern matches '
3301 'a\n'
3302 ' list formed of the remaining subject items, excluding the\n'
3303 ' remaining items corresponding to non-star subpatterns '
3304 'following\n'
3305 ' the star subpattern.\n'
3306 '\n'
3307 ' 4. Remaining non-star subpatterns are matched to their\n'
3308 ' corresponding subject items, as for a fixed-length '
3309 'sequence.\n'
3310 '\n'
3311 ' Note:\n'
3312 '\n'
3313 ' The length of the subject sequence is obtained via "len()" '
3314 '(i.e.\n'
3315 ' via the "__len__()" protocol). This length may be cached '
3316 'by the\n'
3317 ' interpreter in a similar manner as value patterns.\n'
3318 '\n'
3319 'In simple terms "[P1, P2, P3," … ", P<N>]" matches only if all '
3320 'the\n'
3321 'following happens:\n'
3322 '\n'
3323 '* check "<subject>" is a sequence\n'
3324 '\n'
3325 '* "len(subject) == <N>"\n'
3326 '\n'
3327 '* "P1" matches "<subject>[0]" (note that this match can also '
3328 'bind\n'
3329 ' names)\n'
3330 '\n'
3331 '* "P2" matches "<subject>[1]" (note that this match can also '
3332 'bind\n'
3333 ' names)\n'
3334 '\n'
3335 '* … and so on for the corresponding pattern/element.\n'
3336 '\n'
3337 '\n'
3338 'Mapping Patterns\n'
3339 '~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n'
3340 '\n'
3341 'A mapping pattern contains one or more key-value patterns. The '
3342 'syntax\n'
3343 'is similar to the construction of a dictionary. Syntax:\n'
3344 '\n'
3345 ' mapping_pattern ::= "{" [items_pattern] "}"\n'
3346 ' items_pattern ::= ",".key_value_pattern+ ","?\n'
3347 ' key_value_pattern ::= (literal_pattern | value_pattern) ":" '
3348 'pattern\n'
3349 ' | double_star_pattern\n'
3350 ' double_star_pattern ::= "**" capture_pattern\n'
3351 '\n'
3352 'At most one double star pattern may be in a mapping pattern. '
3353 'The\n'
3354 'double star pattern must be the last subpattern in the mapping\n'
3355 'pattern.\n'
3356 '\n'
3357 'Duplicate keys in mapping patterns are disallowed. Duplicate '
3358 'literal\n'
3359 'keys will raise a "SyntaxError". Two keys that otherwise have '
3360 'the same\n'
3361 'value will raise a "ValueError" at runtime.\n'
3362 '\n'
3363 'The following is the logical flow for matching a mapping '
3364 'pattern\n'
3365 'against a subject value:\n'
3366 '\n'
3367 '1. If the subject value is not a mapping [3],the mapping '
3368 'pattern\n'
3369 ' fails.\n'
3370 '\n'
3371 '2. If every key given in the mapping pattern is present in the '
3372 'subject\n'
3373 ' mapping, and the pattern for each key matches the '
3374 'corresponding\n'
3375 ' item of the subject mapping, the mapping pattern succeeds.\n'
3376 '\n'
3377 '3. If duplicate keys are detected in the mapping pattern, the '
3378 'pattern\n'
3379 ' is considered invalid. A "SyntaxError" is raised for '
3380 'duplicate\n'
3381 ' literal values; or a "ValueError" for named keys of the same '
3382 'value.\n'
3383 '\n'
3384 'Note:\n'
3385 '\n'
3386 ' Key-value pairs are matched using the two-argument form of '
3387 'the\n'
3388 ' mapping subject’s "get()" method. Matched key-value pairs '
3389 'must\n'
3390 ' already be present in the mapping, and not created on-the-fly '
3391 'via\n'
3392 ' "__missing__()" or "__getitem__()".\n'
3393 '\n'
3394 'In simple terms "{KEY1: P1, KEY2: P2, ... }" matches only if all '
3395 'the\n'
3396 'following happens:\n'
3397 '\n'
3398 '* check "<subject>" is a mapping\n'
3399 '\n'
3400 '* "KEY1 in <subject>"\n'
3401 '\n'
3402 '* "P1" matches "<subject>[KEY1]"\n'
3403 '\n'
3404 '* … and so on for the corresponding KEY/pattern pair.\n'
3405 '\n'
3406 '\n'
3407 'Class Patterns\n'
3408 '~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n'
3409 '\n'
3410 'A class pattern represents a class and its positional and '
3411 'keyword\n'
3412 'arguments (if any). Syntax:\n'
3413 '\n'
3414 ' class_pattern ::= name_or_attr "(" [pattern_arguments '
3415 '","?] ")"\n'
3416 ' pattern_arguments ::= positional_patterns ["," '
3417 'keyword_patterns]\n'
3418 ' | keyword_patterns\n'
3419 ' positional_patterns ::= ",".pattern+\n'
3420 ' keyword_patterns ::= ",".keyword_pattern+\n'
3421 ' keyword_pattern ::= NAME "=" pattern\n'
3422 '\n'
3423 'The same keyword should not be repeated in class patterns.\n'
3424 '\n'
3425 'The following is the logical flow for matching a class pattern '
3426 'against\n'
3427 'a subject value:\n'
3428 '\n'
3429 '1. If "name_or_attr" is not an instance of the builtin "type" , '
3430 'raise\n'
3431 ' "TypeError".\n'
3432 '\n'
3433 '2. If the subject value is not an instance of "name_or_attr" '
3434 '(tested\n'
3435 ' via "isinstance()"), the class pattern fails.\n'
3436 '\n'
3437 '3. If no pattern arguments are present, the pattern succeeds.\n'
3438 ' Otherwise, the subsequent steps depend on whether keyword or\n'
3439 ' positional argument patterns are present.\n'
3440 '\n'
3441 ' For a number of built-in types (specified below), a single\n'
3442 ' positional subpattern is accepted which will match the '
3443 'entire\n'
3444 ' subject; for these types keyword patterns also work as for '
3445 'other\n'
3446 ' types.\n'
3447 '\n'
3448 ' If only keyword patterns are present, they are processed as\n'
3449 ' follows, one by one:\n'
3450 '\n'
3451 ' I. The keyword is looked up as an attribute on the subject.\n'
3452 '\n'
3453 ' * If this raises an exception other than "AttributeError", '
3454 'the\n'
3455 ' exception bubbles up.\n'
3456 '\n'
3457 ' * If this raises "AttributeError", the class pattern has '
3458 'failed.\n'
3459 '\n'
3460 ' * Else, the subpattern associated with the keyword pattern '
3461 'is\n'
3462 ' matched against the subject’s attribute value. If this '
3463 'fails,\n'
3464 ' the class pattern fails; if this succeeds, the match '
3465 'proceeds\n'
3466 ' to the next keyword.\n'
3467 '\n'
3468 ' II. If all keyword patterns succeed, the class pattern '
3469 'succeeds.\n'
3470 '\n'
3471 ' If any positional patterns are present, they are converted '
3472 'to\n'
3473 ' keyword patterns using the "__match_args__" attribute on the '
3474 'class\n'
3475 ' "name_or_attr" before matching:\n'
3476 '\n'
3477 ' I. The equivalent of "getattr(cls, "__match_args__", ())" is\n'
3478 ' called.\n'
3479 '\n'
3480 ' * If this raises an exception, the exception bubbles up.\n'
3481 '\n'
3482 ' * If the returned value is not a tuple, the conversion '
3483 'fails and\n'
3484 ' "TypeError" is raised.\n'
3485 '\n'
3486 ' * If there are more positional patterns than\n'
3487 ' "len(cls.__match_args__)", "TypeError" is raised.\n'
3488 '\n'
3489 ' * Otherwise, positional pattern "i" is converted to a '
3490 'keyword\n'
3491 ' pattern using "__match_args__[i]" as the keyword.\n'
3492 ' "__match_args__[i]" must be a string; if not "TypeError" '
3493 'is\n'
3494 ' raised.\n'
3495 '\n'
3496 ' * If there are duplicate keywords, "TypeError" is raised.\n'
3497 '\n'
3498 ' See also:\n'
3499 '\n'
3500 ' Customizing positional arguments in class pattern '
3501 'matching\n'
3502 '\n'
3503 ' II. Once all positional patterns have been converted to '
3504 'keyword\n'
3505 ' patterns,\n'
3506 ' the match proceeds as if there were only keyword '
3507 'patterns.\n'
3508 '\n'
3509 ' For the following built-in types the handling of positional\n'
3510 ' subpatterns is different:\n'
3511 '\n'
3512 ' * "bool"\n'
3513 '\n'
3514 ' * "bytearray"\n'
3515 '\n'
3516 ' * "bytes"\n'
3517 '\n'
3518 ' * "dict"\n'
3519 '\n'
3520 ' * "float"\n'
3521 '\n'
3522 ' * "frozenset"\n'
3523 '\n'
3524 ' * "int"\n'
3525 '\n'
3526 ' * "list"\n'
3527 '\n'
3528 ' * "set"\n'
3529 '\n'
3530 ' * "str"\n'
3531 '\n'
3532 ' * "tuple"\n'
3533 '\n'
3534 ' These classes accept a single positional argument, and the '
3535 'pattern\n'
3536 ' there is matched against the whole object rather than an '
3537 'attribute.\n'
3538 ' For example "int(0|1)" matches the value "0", but not the '
3539 'value\n'
3540 ' "0.0".\n'
3541 '\n'
3542 'In simple terms "CLS(P1, attr=P2)" matches only if the '
3543 'following\n'
3544 'happens:\n'
3545 '\n'
3546 '* "isinstance(<subject>, CLS)"\n'
3547 '\n'
3548 '* convert "P1" to a keyword pattern using "CLS.__match_args__"\n'
3549 '\n'
3550 '* For each keyword argument "attr=P2":\n'
3551 '\n'
3552 ' * "hasattr(<subject>, "attr")"\n'
3553 '\n'
3554 ' * "P2" matches "<subject>.attr"\n'
3555 '\n'
3556 '* … and so on for the corresponding keyword argument/pattern '
3557 'pair.\n'
3558 '\n'
3559 'See also:\n'
3560 '\n'
3561 ' * **PEP 634** – Structural Pattern Matching: Specification\n'
3562 '\n'
3563 ' * **PEP 636** – Structural Pattern Matching: Tutorial\n'
3564 '\n'
3565 '\n'
3566 'Function definitions\n'
3567 '====================\n'
3568 '\n'
3569 'A function definition defines a user-defined function object '
3570 '(see\n'
3571 'section The standard type hierarchy):\n'
3572 '\n'
3573 ' funcdef ::= [decorators] "def" funcname "(" '
3574 '[parameter_list] ")"\n'
3575 ' ["->" expression] ":" suite\n'
3576 ' decorators ::= decorator+\n'
3577 ' decorator ::= "@" assignment_expression '
3578 'NEWLINE\n'
3579 ' parameter_list ::= defparameter ("," '
3580 'defparameter)* "," "/" ["," [parameter_list_no_posonly]]\n'
3581 ' | parameter_list_no_posonly\n'
3582 ' parameter_list_no_posonly ::= defparameter ("," '
3583 'defparameter)* ["," [parameter_list_starargs]]\n'
3584 ' | parameter_list_starargs\n'
3585 ' parameter_list_starargs ::= "*" [parameter] ("," '
3586 'defparameter)* ["," ["**" parameter [","]]]\n'
3587 ' | "**" parameter [","]\n'
3588 ' parameter ::= identifier [":" expression]\n'
3589 ' defparameter ::= parameter ["=" expression]\n'
3590 ' funcname ::= identifier\n'
3591 '\n'
3592 'A function definition is an executable statement. Its execution '
3593 'binds\n'
3594 'the function name in the current local namespace to a function '
3595 'object\n'
3596 '(a wrapper around the executable code for the function). This\n'
3597 'function object contains a reference to the current global '
3598 'namespace\n'
3599 'as the global namespace to be used when the function is called.\n'
3600 '\n'
3601 'The function definition does not execute the function body; this '
3602 'gets\n'
3603 'executed only when the function is called. [4]\n'
3604 '\n'
3605 'A function definition may be wrapped by one or more *decorator*\n'
3606 'expressions. Decorator expressions are evaluated when the '
3607 'function is\n'
3608 'defined, in the scope that contains the function definition. '
3609 'The\n'
3610 'result must be a callable, which is invoked with the function '
3611 'object\n'
3612 'as the only argument. The returned value is bound to the '
3613 'function name\n'
3614 'instead of the function object. Multiple decorators are applied '
3615 'in\n'
3616 'nested fashion. For example, the following code\n'
3617 '\n'
3618 ' @f1(arg)\n'
3619 ' @f2\n'
3620 ' def func(): pass\n'
3621 '\n'
3622 'is roughly equivalent to\n'
3623 '\n'
3624 ' def func(): pass\n'
3625 ' func = f1(arg)(f2(func))\n'
3626 '\n'
3627 'except that the original function is not temporarily bound to '
3628 'the name\n'
3629 '"func".\n'
3630 '\n'
3631 'Changed in version 3.9: Functions may be decorated with any '
3632 'valid\n'
3633 '"assignment_expression". Previously, the grammar was much more\n'
3634 'restrictive; see **PEP 614** for details.\n'
3635 '\n'
3636 'When one or more *parameters* have the form *parameter* "="\n'
3637 '*expression*, the function is said to have “default parameter '
3638 'values.”\n'
3639 'For a parameter with a default value, the corresponding '
3640 '*argument* may\n'
3641 'be omitted from a call, in which case the parameter’s default '
3642 'value is\n'
3643 'substituted. If a parameter has a default value, all following\n'
3644 'parameters up until the “"*"” must also have a default value — '
3645 'this is\n'
3646 'a syntactic restriction that is not expressed by the grammar.\n'
3647 '\n'
3648 '**Default parameter values are evaluated from left to right when '
3649 'the\n'
3650 'function definition is executed.** This means that the '
3651 'expression is\n'
3652 'evaluated once, when the function is defined, and that the same '
3653 '“pre-\n'
3654 'computed” value is used for each call. This is especially '
3655 'important\n'
3656 'to understand when a default parameter value is a mutable '
3657 'object, such\n'
3658 'as a list or a dictionary: if the function modifies the object '
3659 '(e.g.\n'
3660 'by appending an item to a list), the default parameter value is '
3661 'in\n'
3662 'effect modified. This is generally not what was intended. A '
3663 'way\n'
3664 'around this is to use "None" as the default, and explicitly test '
3665 'for\n'
3666 'it in the body of the function, e.g.:\n'
3667 '\n'
3668 ' def whats_on_the_telly(penguin=None):\n'
3669 ' if penguin is None:\n'
3670 ' penguin = []\n'
3671 ' penguin.append("property of the zoo")\n'
3672 ' return penguin\n'
3673 '\n'
3674 'Function call semantics are described in more detail in section '
3675 'Calls.\n'
3676 'A function call always assigns values to all parameters '
3677 'mentioned in\n'
3678 'the parameter list, either from positional arguments, from '
3679 'keyword\n'
3680 'arguments, or from default values. If the form “"*identifier"” '
3681 'is\n'
3682 'present, it is initialized to a tuple receiving any excess '
3683 'positional\n'
3684 'parameters, defaulting to the empty tuple. If the form\n'
3685 '“"**identifier"” is present, it is initialized to a new ordered\n'
3686 'mapping receiving any excess keyword arguments, defaulting to a '
3687 'new\n'
3688 'empty mapping of the same type. Parameters after “"*"” or\n'
3689 '“"*identifier"” are keyword-only parameters and may only be '
3690 'passed by\n'
3691 'keyword arguments. Parameters before “"/"” are positional-only\n'
3692 'parameters and may only be passed by positional arguments.\n'
3693 '\n'
3694 'Changed in version 3.8: The "/" function parameter syntax may be '
3695 'used\n'
3696 'to indicate positional-only parameters. See **PEP 570** for '
3697 'details.\n'
3698 '\n'
3699 'Parameters may have an *annotation* of the form “": '
3700 'expression"”\n'
3701 'following the parameter name. Any parameter may have an '
3702 'annotation,\n'
3703 'even those of the form "*identifier" or "**identifier". '
3704 'Functions may\n'
3705 'have “return” annotation of the form “"-> expression"” after '
3706 'the\n'
3707 'parameter list. These annotations can be any valid Python '
3708 'expression.\n'
3709 'The presence of annotations does not change the semantics of a\n'
3710 'function. The annotation values are available as values of a\n'
3711 'dictionary keyed by the parameters’ names in the '
3712 '"__annotations__"\n'
3713 'attribute of the function object. If the "annotations" import '
3714 'from\n'
3715 '"__future__" is used, annotations are preserved as strings at '
3716 'runtime\n'
3717 'which enables postponed evaluation. Otherwise, they are '
3718 'evaluated\n'
3719 'when the function definition is executed. In this case '
3720 'annotations\n'
3721 'may be evaluated in a different order than they appear in the '
3722 'source\n'
3723 'code.\n'
3724 '\n'
3725 'It is also possible to create anonymous functions (functions not '
3726 'bound\n'
3727 'to a name), for immediate use in expressions. This uses lambda\n'
3728 'expressions, described in section Lambdas. Note that the '
3729 'lambda\n'
3730 'expression is merely a shorthand for a simplified function '
3731 'definition;\n'
3732 'a function defined in a “"def"” statement can be passed around '
3733 'or\n'
3734 'assigned to another name just like a function defined by a '
3735 'lambda\n'
3736 'expression. The “"def"” form is actually more powerful since '
3737 'it\n'
3738 'allows the execution of multiple statements and annotations.\n'
3739 '\n'
3740 '**Programmer’s note:** Functions are first-class objects. A '
3741 '“"def"”\n'
3742 'statement executed inside a function definition defines a local\n'
3743 'function that can be returned or passed around. Free variables '
3744 'used\n'
3745 'in the nested function can access the local variables of the '
3746 'function\n'
3747 'containing the def. See section Naming and binding for '
3748 'details.\n'
3749 '\n'
3750 'See also:\n'
3751 '\n'
3752 ' **PEP 3107** - Function Annotations\n'
3753 ' The original specification for function annotations.\n'
3754 '\n'
3755 ' **PEP 484** - Type Hints\n'
3756 ' Definition of a standard meaning for annotations: type '
3757 'hints.\n'
3758 '\n'
3759 ' **PEP 526** - Syntax for Variable Annotations\n'
3760 ' Ability to type hint variable declarations, including '
3761 'class\n'
3762 ' variables and instance variables.\n'
3763 '\n'
3764 ' **PEP 563** - Postponed Evaluation of Annotations\n'
3765 ' Support for forward references within annotations by '
3766 'preserving\n'
3767 ' annotations in a string form at runtime instead of eager\n'
3768 ' evaluation.\n'
3769 '\n'
3770 ' **PEP 318** - Decorators for Functions and Methods\n'
3771 ' Function and method decorators were introduced. Class '
3772 'decorators\n'
3773 ' were introduced in **PEP 3129**.\n'
3774 '\n'
3775 '\n'
3776 'Class definitions\n'
3777 '=================\n'
3778 '\n'
3779 'A class definition defines a class object (see section The '
3780 'standard\n'
3781 'type hierarchy):\n'
3782 '\n'
3783 ' classdef ::= [decorators] "class" classname [inheritance] '
3784 '":" suite\n'
3785 ' inheritance ::= "(" [argument_list] ")"\n'
3786 ' classname ::= identifier\n'
3787 '\n'
3788 'A class definition is an executable statement. The inheritance '
3789 'list\n'
3790 'usually gives a list of base classes (see Metaclasses for more\n'
3791 'advanced uses), so each item in the list should evaluate to a '
3792 'class\n'
3793 'object which allows subclassing. Classes without an inheritance '
3794 'list\n'
3795 'inherit, by default, from the base class "object"; hence,\n'
3796 '\n'
3797 ' class Foo:\n'
3798 ' pass\n'
3799 '\n'
3800 'is equivalent to\n'
3801 '\n'
3802 ' class Foo(object):\n'
3803 ' pass\n'
3804 '\n'
3805 'The class’s suite is then executed in a new execution frame '
3806 '(see\n'
3807 'Naming and binding), using a newly created local namespace and '
3808 'the\n'
3809 'original global namespace. (Usually, the suite contains mostly\n'
3810 'function definitions.) When the class’s suite finishes '
3811 'execution, its\n'
3812 'execution frame is discarded but its local namespace is saved. '
3813 '[5] A\n'
3814 'class object is then created using the inheritance list for the '
3815 'base\n'
3816 'classes and the saved local namespace for the attribute '
3817 'dictionary.\n'
3818 'The class name is bound to this class object in the original '
3819 'local\n'
3820 'namespace.\n'
3821 '\n'
3822 'The order in which attributes are defined in the class body is\n'
3823 'preserved in the new class’s "__dict__". Note that this is '
3824 'reliable\n'
3825 'only right after the class is created and only for classes that '
3826 'were\n'
3827 'defined using the definition syntax.\n'
3828 '\n'
3829 'Class creation can be customized heavily using metaclasses.\n'
3830 '\n'
3831 'Classes can also be decorated: just like when decorating '
3832 'functions,\n'
3833 '\n'
3834 ' @f1(arg)\n'
3835 ' @f2\n'
3836 ' class Foo: pass\n'
3837 '\n'
3838 'is roughly equivalent to\n'
3839 '\n'
3840 ' class Foo: pass\n'
3841 ' Foo = f1(arg)(f2(Foo))\n'
3842 '\n'
3843 'The evaluation rules for the decorator expressions are the same '
3844 'as for\n'
3845 'function decorators. The result is then bound to the class '
3846 'name.\n'
3847 '\n'
3848 'Changed in version 3.9: Classes may be decorated with any valid\n'
3849 '"assignment_expression". Previously, the grammar was much more\n'
3850 'restrictive; see **PEP 614** for details.\n'
3851 '\n'
3852 '**Programmer’s note:** Variables defined in the class definition '
3853 'are\n'
3854 'class attributes; they are shared by instances. Instance '
3855 'attributes\n'
3856 'can be set in a method with "self.name = value". Both class '
3857 'and\n'
3858 'instance attributes are accessible through the notation '
3859 '“"self.name"”,\n'
3860 'and an instance attribute hides a class attribute with the same '
3861 'name\n'
3862 'when accessed in this way. Class attributes can be used as '
3863 'defaults\n'
3864 'for instance attributes, but using mutable values there can lead '
3865 'to\n'
3866 'unexpected results. Descriptors can be used to create instance\n'
3867 'variables with different implementation details.\n'
3868 '\n'
3869 'See also:\n'
3870 '\n'
3871 ' **PEP 3115** - Metaclasses in Python 3000\n'
3872 ' The proposal that changed the declaration of metaclasses to '
3873 'the\n'
3874 ' current syntax, and the semantics for how classes with\n'
3875 ' metaclasses are constructed.\n'
3876 '\n'
3877 ' **PEP 3129** - Class Decorators\n'
3878 ' The proposal that added class decorators. Function and '
3879 'method\n'
3880 ' decorators were introduced in **PEP 318**.\n'
3881 '\n'
3882 '\n'
3883 'Coroutines\n'
3884 '==========\n'
3885 '\n'
3886 'New in version 3.5.\n'
3887 '\n'
3888 '\n'
3889 'Coroutine function definition\n'
3890 '-----------------------------\n'
3891 '\n'
3892 ' async_funcdef ::= [decorators] "async" "def" funcname "(" '
3893 '[parameter_list] ")"\n'
3894 ' ["->" expression] ":" suite\n'
3895 '\n'
3896 'Execution of Python coroutines can be suspended and resumed at '
3897 'many\n'
3898 'points (see *coroutine*). "await" expressions, "async for" and '
3899 '"async\n'
3900 'with" can only be used in the body of a coroutine function.\n'
3901 '\n'
3902 'Functions defined with "async def" syntax are always coroutine\n'
3903 'functions, even if they do not contain "await" or "async" '
3904 'keywords.\n'
3905 '\n'
3906 'It is a "SyntaxError" to use a "yield from" expression inside '
3907 'the body\n'
3908 'of a coroutine function.\n'
3909 '\n'
3910 'An example of a coroutine function:\n'
3911 '\n'
3912 ' async def func(param1, param2):\n'
3913 ' do_stuff()\n'
3914 ' await some_coroutine()\n'
3915 '\n'
3916 'Changed in version 3.7: "await" and "async" are now keywords;\n'
3917 'previously they were only treated as such inside the body of a\n'
3918 'coroutine function.\n'
3919 '\n'
3920 '\n'
3921 'The "async for" statement\n'
3922 '-------------------------\n'
3923 '\n'
3924 ' async_for_stmt ::= "async" for_stmt\n'
3925 '\n'
3926 'An *asynchronous iterable* provides an "__aiter__" method that\n'
3927 'directly returns an *asynchronous iterator*, which can call\n'
3928 'asynchronous code in its "__anext__" method.\n'
3929 '\n'
3930 'The "async for" statement allows convenient iteration over\n'
3931 'asynchronous iterables.\n'
3932 '\n'
3933 'The following code:\n'
3934 '\n'
3935 ' async for TARGET in ITER:\n'
3936 ' SUITE\n'
3937 ' else:\n'
3938 ' SUITE2\n'
3939 '\n'
3940 'Is semantically equivalent to:\n'
3941 '\n'
3942 ' iter = (ITER)\n'
3943 ' iter = type(iter).__aiter__(iter)\n'
3944 ' running = True\n'
3945 '\n'
3946 ' while running:\n'
3947 ' try:\n'
3948 ' TARGET = await type(iter).__anext__(iter)\n'
3949 ' except StopAsyncIteration:\n'
3950 ' running = False\n'
3951 ' else:\n'
3952 ' SUITE\n'
3953 ' else:\n'
3954 ' SUITE2\n'
3955 '\n'
3956 'See also "__aiter__()" and "__anext__()" for details.\n'
3957 '\n'
3958 'It is a "SyntaxError" to use an "async for" statement outside '
3959 'the body\n'
3960 'of a coroutine function.\n'
3961 '\n'
3962 '\n'
3963 'The "async with" statement\n'
3964 '--------------------------\n'
3965 '\n'
3966 ' async_with_stmt ::= "async" with_stmt\n'
3967 '\n'
3968 'An *asynchronous context manager* is a *context manager* that is '
3969 'able\n'
3970 'to suspend execution in its *enter* and *exit* methods.\n'
3971 '\n'
3972 'The following code:\n'
3973 '\n'
3974 ' async with EXPRESSION as TARGET:\n'
3975 ' SUITE\n'
3976 '\n'
3977 'is semantically equivalent to:\n'
3978 '\n'
3979 ' manager = (EXPRESSION)\n'
3980 ' aenter = type(manager).__aenter__\n'
3981 ' aexit = type(manager).__aexit__\n'
3982 ' value = await aenter(manager)\n'
3983 ' hit_except = False\n'
3984 '\n'
3985 ' try:\n'
3986 ' TARGET = value\n'
3987 ' SUITE\n'
3988 ' except:\n'
3989 ' hit_except = True\n'
3990 ' if not await aexit(manager, *sys.exc_info()):\n'
3991 ' raise\n'
3992 ' finally:\n'
3993 ' if not hit_except:\n'
3994 ' await aexit(manager, None, None, None)\n'
3995 '\n'
3996 'See also "__aenter__()" and "__aexit__()" for details.\n'
3997 '\n'
3998 'It is a "SyntaxError" to use an "async with" statement outside '
3999 'the\n'
4000 'body of a coroutine function.\n'
4001 '\n'
4002 'See also:\n'
4003 '\n'
4004 ' **PEP 492** - Coroutines with async and await syntax\n'
4005 ' The proposal that made coroutines a proper standalone '
4006 'concept in\n'
4007 ' Python, and added supporting syntax.\n'
4008 '\n'
4009 '-[ Footnotes ]-\n'
4010 '\n'

4012 'there\n'

4014 'exception.\n'

4016 '\n'

4074 '\n'
4075 '[5] A string literal appearing as the first statement in the '

4077 ' body is transformed into the namespace’s "__doc__" item and\n'
4078 ' therefore the class’s *docstring*.\n',

4111 'any.\n'

4118 'exited. If the\n'

4120 'arguments will\n'

  • E128 Continuation line under-indented for visual indent
4183 'customization': 'Basic customization\n'
4184 '*******************\n'
4185 '\n'
4186 'object.__new__(cls[, ...])\n'
4187 '\n'
4188 ' Called to create a new instance of class *cls*. '
4189 '"__new__()" is a\n'
4190 ' static method (special-cased so you need not declare it '
4191 'as such)\n'
4192 ' that takes the class of which an instance was requested '
4193 'as its\n'
4194 ' first argument. The remaining arguments are those '
4195 'passed to the\n'
4196 ' object constructor expression (the call to the class). '
4197 'The return\n'
4198 ' value of "__new__()" should be the new object instance '
4199 '(usually an\n'
4200 ' instance of *cls*).\n'
4201 '\n'
4202 ' Typical implementations create a new instance of the '
4203 'class by\n'
4204 ' invoking the superclass’s "__new__()" method using\n'
4205 ' "super().__new__(cls[, ...])" with appropriate arguments '
4206 'and then\n'
4207 ' modifying the newly created instance as necessary before '
4208 'returning\n'
4209 ' it.\n'
4210 '\n'
4211 ' If "__new__()" is invoked during object construction and '
4212 'it returns\n'
4213 ' an instance of *cls*, then the new instance’s '
4214 '"__init__()" method\n'
4215 ' will be invoked like "__init__(self[, ...])", where '
4216 '*self* is the\n'
4217 ' new instance and the remaining arguments are the same as '
4218 'were\n'
4219 ' passed to the object constructor.\n'
4220 '\n'
4221 ' If "__new__()" does not return an instance of *cls*, '
4222 'then the new\n'
4223 ' instance’s "__init__()" method will not be invoked.\n'
4224 '\n'
4225 ' "__new__()" is intended mainly to allow subclasses of '
4226 'immutable\n'
4227 ' types (like int, str, or tuple) to customize instance '
4228 'creation. It\n'
4229 ' is also commonly overridden in custom metaclasses in '
4230 'order to\n'
4231 ' customize class creation.\n'
4232 '\n'
4233 'object.__init__(self[, ...])\n'
4234 '\n'
4235 ' Called after the instance has been created (by '
4236 '"__new__()"), but\n'
4237 ' before it is returned to the caller. The arguments are '
4238 'those\n'
4239 ' passed to the class constructor expression. If a base '
4240 'class has an\n'
4241 ' "__init__()" method, the derived class’s "__init__()" '
4242 'method, if\n'
4243 ' any, must explicitly call it to ensure proper '
4244 'initialization of the\n'
4245 ' base class part of the instance; for example:\n'
4246 ' "super().__init__([args...])".\n'
4247 '\n'
4248 ' Because "__new__()" and "__init__()" work together in '
4249 'constructing\n'
4250 ' objects ("__new__()" to create it, and "__init__()" to '
4251 'customize\n'
4252 ' it), no non-"None" value may be returned by '
4253 '"__init__()"; doing so\n'
4254 ' will cause a "TypeError" to be raised at runtime.\n'
4255 '\n'
4256 'object.__del__(self)\n'
4257 '\n'
4258 ' Called when the instance is about to be destroyed. This '
4259 'is also\n'
4260 ' called a finalizer or (improperly) a destructor. If a '
4261 'base class\n'
4262 ' has a "__del__()" method, the derived class’s '
4263 '"__del__()" method,\n'
4264 ' if any, must explicitly call it to ensure proper '
4265 'deletion of the\n'
4266 ' base class part of the instance.\n'
4267 '\n'
4268 ' It is possible (though not recommended!) for the '
4269 '"__del__()" method\n'
4270 ' to postpone destruction of the instance by creating a '
4271 'new reference\n'
4272 ' to it. This is called object *resurrection*. It is\n'
4273 ' implementation-dependent whether "__del__()" is called a '
4274 'second\n'
4275 ' time when a resurrected object is about to be destroyed; '
4276 'the\n'
4277 ' current *CPython* implementation only calls it once.\n'
4278 '\n'
4279 ' It is not guaranteed that "__del__()" methods are called '
4280 'for\n'
4281 ' objects that still exist when the interpreter exits.\n'
4282 '\n'
4283 ' Note:\n'
4284 '\n'
4285 ' "del x" doesn’t directly call "x.__del__()" — the '
4286 'former\n'
4287 ' decrements the reference count for "x" by one, and the '
4288 'latter is\n'
4289 ' only called when "x"’s reference count reaches zero.\n'
4290 '\n'
4291 ' **CPython implementation detail:** It is possible for a '
4292 'reference\n'
4293 ' cycle to prevent the reference count of an object from '
4294 'going to\n'
4295 ' zero. In this case, the cycle will be later detected '
4296 'and deleted\n'
4297 ' by the *cyclic garbage collector*. A common cause of '
4298 'reference\n'
4299 ' cycles is when an exception has been caught in a local '
4300 'variable.\n'
4301 ' The frame’s locals then reference the exception, which '
4302 'references\n'
4303 ' its own traceback, which references the locals of all '
4304 'frames caught\n'
4305 ' in the traceback.\n'
4306 '\n'
4307 ' See also: Documentation for the "gc" module.\n'
4308 '\n'
4309 ' Warning:\n'
4310 '\n'
4311 ' Due to the precarious circumstances under which '
4312 '"__del__()"\n'
4313 ' methods are invoked, exceptions that occur during '
4314 'their execution\n'
4315 ' are ignored, and a warning is printed to "sys.stderr" '
4316 'instead.\n'
4317 ' In particular:\n'
4318 '\n'
4319 ' * "__del__()" can be invoked when arbitrary code is '
4320 'being\n'
4321 ' executed, including from any arbitrary thread. If '
4322 '"__del__()"\n'
4323 ' needs to take a lock or invoke any other blocking '
4324 'resource, it\n'
4325 ' may deadlock as the resource may already be taken by '
4326 'the code\n'
4327 ' that gets interrupted to execute "__del__()".\n'
4328 '\n'
4329 ' * "__del__()" can be executed during interpreter '
4330 'shutdown. As a\n'
4331 ' consequence, the global variables it needs to access '
4332 '(including\n'
4333 ' other modules) may already have been deleted or set '
4334 'to "None".\n'
4335 ' Python guarantees that globals whose name begins '
4336 'with a single\n'
4337 ' underscore are deleted from their module before '
4338 'other globals\n'
4339 ' are deleted; if no other references to such globals '
4340 'exist, this\n'
4341 ' may help in assuring that imported modules are still '
4342 'available\n'
4343 ' at the time when the "__del__()" method is called.\n'
4344 '\n'
4345 'object.__repr__(self)\n'
4346 '\n'
4347 ' Called by the "repr()" built-in function to compute the '
4348 '“official”\n'
4349 ' string representation of an object. If at all possible, '
4350 'this\n'
4351 ' should look like a valid Python expression that could be '
4352 'used to\n'
4353 ' recreate an object with the same value (given an '
4354 'appropriate\n'
4355 ' environment). If this is not possible, a string of the '
4356 'form\n'
4357 ' "<...some useful description...>" should be returned. '
4358 'The return\n'
4359 ' value must be a string object. If a class defines '
4360 '"__repr__()" but\n'
4361 ' not "__str__()", then "__repr__()" is also used when an '
4362 '“informal”\n'

4365 '\n'
4366 ' This is typically used for debugging, so it is important '
4367 'that the\n'
4368 ' representation is information-rich and unambiguous.\n'
4369 '\n'
4370 'object.__str__(self)\n'
4371 '\n'
4372 ' Called by "str(object)" and the built-in functions '
4373 '"format()" and\n'
4374 ' "print()" to compute the “informal” or nicely printable '
4375 'string\n'
4376 ' representation of an object. The return value must be a '

4380 ' This method differs from "object.__repr__()" in that '

4427 'now\n'

4429 '\'\')".\n'
4430 '\n'
4431 'object.__lt__(self, other)\n'
4432 'object.__le__(self, other)\n'
4433 'object.__eq__(self, other)\n'
4434 'object.__ne__(self, other)\n'
4435 'object.__gt__(self, other)\n'
4436 'object.__ge__(self, other)\n'
4437 '\n'
4438 ' These are the so-called “rich comparison” methods. The\n'
4439 ' correspondence between operator symbols and method names '
4440 'is as\n'
4441 ' follows: "x<y" calls "x.__lt__(y)", "x<=y" calls '
4442 '"x.__le__(y)",\n'
4443 ' "x==y" calls "x.__eq__(y)", "x!=y" calls "x.__ne__(y)", '
4444 '"x>y" calls\n'
4445 ' "x.__gt__(y)", and "x>=y" calls "x.__ge__(y)".\n'
4446 '\n'
4447 ' A rich comparison method may return the singleton '
4448 '"NotImplemented"\n'
4449 ' if it does not implement the operation for a given pair '
4450 'of\n'
4451 ' arguments. By convention, "False" and "True" are '
4452 'returned for a\n'
4453 ' successful comparison. However, these methods can return '
4454 'any value,\n'
4455 ' so if the comparison operator is used in a Boolean '
4456 'context (e.g.,\n'
4457 ' in the condition of an "if" statement), Python will call '
4458 '"bool()"\n'
4459 ' on the value to determine if the result is true or '
4460 'false.\n'
4461 '\n'
4462 ' By default, "object" implements "__eq__()" by using '
4463 '"is", returning\n'
4464 ' "NotImplemented" in the case of a false comparison: '
4465 '"True if x is y\n'
4466 ' else NotImplemented". For "__ne__()", by default it '
4467 'delegates to\n'
4468 ' "__eq__()" and inverts the result unless it is '
4469 '"NotImplemented".\n'
4470 ' There are no other implied relationships among the '
4471 'comparison\n'
4472 ' operators or default implementations; for example, the '
4473 'truth of\n'
4474 ' "(x<y or x==y)" does not imply "x<=y". To automatically '
4475 'generate\n'
4476 ' ordering operations from a single root operation, see\n'
4477 ' "functools.total_ordering()".\n'
4478 '\n'
4479 ' See the paragraph on "__hash__()" for some important '
4480 'notes on\n'
4481 ' creating *hashable* objects which support custom '
4482 'comparison\n'
4483 ' operations and are usable as dictionary keys.\n'
4484 '\n'
4485 ' There are no swapped-argument versions of these methods '
4486 '(to be used\n'
4487 ' when the left argument does not support the operation '
4488 'but the right\n'
4489 ' argument does); rather, "__lt__()" and "__gt__()" are '
4490 'each other’s\n'
4491 ' reflection, "__le__()" and "__ge__()" are each other’s '
4492 'reflection,\n'
4493 ' and "__eq__()" and "__ne__()" are their own reflection. '
4494 'If the\n'
4495 ' operands are of different types, and the right operand’s '
4496 'type is a\n'
4497 ' direct or indirect subclass of the left operand’s type, '
4498 'the\n'
4499 ' reflected method of the right operand has priority, '
4500 'otherwise the\n'
4501 ' left operand’s method has priority. Virtual subclassing '
4502 'is not\n'
4503 ' considered.\n'
4504 '\n'
4505 ' When no appropriate method returns any value other than\n'
4506 ' "NotImplemented", the "==" and "!=" operators will fall '
4507 'back to\n'
4508 ' "is" and "is not", respectively.\n'
4509 '\n'
4510 'object.__hash__(self)\n'
4511 '\n'
4512 ' Called by built-in function "hash()" and for operations '
4513 'on members\n'
4514 ' of hashed collections including "set", "frozenset", and '
4515 '"dict".\n'
4516 ' The "__hash__()" method should return an integer. The '
4517 'only required\n'
4518 ' property is that objects which compare equal have the '
4519 'same hash\n'
4520 ' value; it is advised to mix together the hash values of '
4521 'the\n'
4522 ' components of the object that also play a part in '
4523 'comparison of\n'
4524 ' objects by packing them into a tuple and hashing the '
4525 'tuple.\n'
4526 ' Example:\n'
4527 '\n'
4528 ' def __hash__(self):\n'
4529 ' return hash((self.name, self.nick, self.color))\n'
4530 '\n'
4531 ' Note:\n'
4532 '\n'
4533 ' "hash()" truncates the value returned from an object’s '
4534 'custom\n'
4535 ' "__hash__()" method to the size of a "Py_ssize_t". '
4536 'This is\n'
4537 ' typically 8 bytes on 64-bit builds and 4 bytes on '
4538 '32-bit builds.\n'
4539 ' If an object’s "__hash__()" must interoperate on '
4540 'builds of\n'
4541 ' different bit sizes, be sure to check the width on all '
4542 'supported\n'
4543 ' builds. An easy way to do this is with "python -c '
4544 '"import sys;\n'
4545 ' print(sys.hash_info.width)"".\n'
4546 '\n'
4547 ' If a class does not define an "__eq__()" method it '
4548 'should not\n'
4549 ' define a "__hash__()" operation either; if it defines '
4550 '"__eq__()"\n'
4551 ' but not "__hash__()", its instances will not be usable '
4552 'as items in\n'
4553 ' hashable collections. If a class defines mutable '
4554 'objects and\n'
4555 ' implements an "__eq__()" method, it should not '
4556 'implement\n'
4557 ' "__hash__()", since the implementation of *hashable* '
4558 'collections\n'
4559 ' requires that a key’s hash value is immutable (if the '
4560 'object’s hash\n'
4561 ' value changes, it will be in the wrong hash bucket).\n'
4562 '\n'
4563 ' User-defined classes have "__eq__()" and "__hash__()" '
4564 'methods by\n'
4565 ' default; with them, all objects compare unequal (except '
4566 'with\n'
4567 ' themselves) and "x.__hash__()" returns an appropriate '
4568 'value such\n'
4569 ' that "x == y" implies both that "x is y" and "hash(x) == '
4570 'hash(y)".\n'
4571 '\n'
4572 ' A class that overrides "__eq__()" and does not define '
4573 '"__hash__()"\n'
4574 ' will have its "__hash__()" implicitly set to "None". '
4575 'When the\n'
4576 ' "__hash__()" method of a class is "None", instances of '
4577 'the class\n'
4578 ' will raise an appropriate "TypeError" when a program '
4579 'attempts to\n'
4580 ' retrieve their hash value, and will also be correctly '
4581 'identified as\n'
4582 ' unhashable when checking "isinstance(obj,\n'
4583 ' collections.abc.Hashable)".\n'
4584 '\n'
4585 ' If a class that overrides "__eq__()" needs to retain '
4586 'the\n'
4587 ' implementation of "__hash__()" from a parent class, the '
4588 'interpreter\n'
4589 ' must be told this explicitly by setting "__hash__ =\n'
4590 ' <ParentClass>.__hash__".\n'
4591 '\n'
4592 ' If a class that does not override "__eq__()" wishes to '
4593 'suppress\n'
4594 ' hash support, it should include "__hash__ = None" in the '
4595 'class\n'
4596 ' definition. A class which defines its own "__hash__()" '
4597 'that\n'
4598 ' explicitly raises a "TypeError" would be incorrectly '
4599 'identified as\n'
4600 ' hashable by an "isinstance(obj, '
4601 'collections.abc.Hashable)" call.\n'
4602 '\n'
4603 ' Note:\n'
4604 '\n'
4605 ' By default, the "__hash__()" values of str and bytes '
4606 'objects are\n'
4607 ' “salted” with an unpredictable random value. Although '
4608 'they\n'
4609 ' remain constant within an individual Python process, '
4610 'they are not\n'
4611 ' predictable between repeated invocations of '
4612 'Python.This is\n'
4613 ' intended to provide protection against a '
4614 'denial-of-service caused\n'
4615 ' by carefully chosen inputs that exploit the worst '
4616 'case\n'
4617 ' performance of a dict insertion, *O*(*n*^2) '
4618 'complexity. See\n'

4620 ' details.Changing hash values affects the iteration '

5551 'Exceptions are a means of breaking out of the normal flow of '

5553 'of a code block in order to handle errors or other '

5579 'an outer\n'

5625 'execmodel': 'Execution model\n'
5626 '***************\n'
5627 '\n'
5628 '\n'
5629 'Structure of a program\n'
5630 '======================\n'
5631 '\n'
5632 'A Python program is constructed from code blocks. A *block* is '
5633 'a piece\n'
5634 'of Python program text that is executed as a unit. The '
5635 'following are\n'
5636 'blocks: a module, a function body, and a class definition. '
5637 'Each\n'
5638 'command typed interactively is a block. A script file (a file '
5639 'given\n'
5640 'as standard input to the interpreter or specified as a command '
5641 'line\n'
5642 'argument to the interpreter) is a code block. A script command '
5643 '(a\n'
5644 'command specified on the interpreter command line with the '
5645 '"-c"\n'
5646 'option) is a code block. A module run as a top level script (as '
5647 'module\n'
5648 '"__main__") from the command line using a "-m" argument is also '
5649 'a code\n'
5650 'block. The string argument passed to the built-in functions '
5651 '"eval()"\n'
5652 'and "exec()" is a code block.\n'
5653 '\n'
5654 'A code block is executed in an *execution frame*. A frame '
5655 'contains\n'
5656 'some administrative information (used for debugging) and '
5657 'determines\n'
5658 'where and how execution continues after the code block’s '
5659 'execution has\n'
5660 'completed.\n'
5661 '\n'
5662 '\n'
5663 'Naming and binding\n'
5664 '==================\n'
5665 '\n'
5666 '\n'
5667 'Binding of names\n'
5668 '----------------\n'
5669 '\n'
5670 '*Names* refer to objects. Names are introduced by name '
5671 'binding\n'
5672 'operations.\n'
5673 '\n'
5674 'The following constructs bind names:\n'
5675 '\n'
5676 '* formal parameters to functions,\n'
5677 '\n'
5678 '* class definitions,\n'
5679 '\n'
5680 '* function definitions,\n'
5681 '\n'
5682 '* assignment expressions,\n'
5683 '\n'
5684 '* targets that are identifiers if occurring in an assignment:\n'
5685 '\n'
5686 ' * "for" loop header,\n'
5687 '\n'
5688 ' * after "as" in a "with" statement, "except" clause, '
5689 '"except*"\n'
5690 ' clause, or in the as-pattern in structural pattern '
5691 'matching,\n'
5692 '\n'
5693 ' * in a capture pattern in structural pattern matching\n'
5694 '\n'
5695 '* "import" statements.\n'
5696 '\n'
5697 'The "import" statement of the form "from ... import *" binds '
5698 'all names\n'
5699 'defined in the imported module, except those beginning with an\n'
5700 'underscore. This form may only be used at the module level.\n'
5701 '\n'
5702 'A target occurring in a "del" statement is also considered '
5703 'bound for\n'
5704 'this purpose (though the actual semantics are to unbind the '
5705 'name).\n'
5706 '\n'
5707 'Each assignment or import statement occurs within a block '
5708 'defined by a\n'
5709 'class or function definition or at the module level (the '
5710 'top-level\n'
5711 'code block).\n'
5712 '\n'
5713 'If a name is bound in a block, it is a local variable of that '
5714 'block,\n'
5715 'unless declared as "nonlocal" or "global". If a name is bound '
5716 'at the\n'
5717 'module level, it is a global variable. (The variables of the '
5718 'module\n'
5719 'code block are local and global.) If a variable is used in a '
5720 'code\n'
5721 'block but not defined there, it is a *free variable*.\n'
5722 '\n'
5723 'Each occurrence of a name in the program text refers to the '
5724 '*binding*\n'
5725 'of that name established by the following name resolution '
5726 'rules.\n'
5727 '\n'
5728 '\n'
5729 'Resolution of names\n'
5730 '-------------------\n'
5731 '\n'
5732 'A *scope* defines the visibility of a name within a block. If '
5733 'a local\n'
5734 'variable is defined in a block, its scope includes that block. '
5735 'If the\n'
5736 'definition occurs in a function block, the scope extends to any '
5737 'blocks\n'
5738 'contained within the defining one, unless a contained block '
5739 'introduces\n'
5740 'a different binding for the name.\n'
5741 '\n'
5742 'When a name is used in a code block, it is resolved using the '
5743 'nearest\n'
5744 'enclosing scope. The set of all such scopes visible to a code '
5745 'block\n'
5746 'is called the block’s *environment*.\n'
5747 '\n'
5748 'When a name is not found at all, a "NameError" exception is '
5749 'raised. If\n'
5750 'the current scope is a function scope, and the name refers to a '
5751 'local\n'
5752 'variable that has not yet been bound to a value at the point '
5753 'where the\n'
5754 'name is used, an "UnboundLocalError" exception is raised.\n'
5755 '"UnboundLocalError" is a subclass of "NameError".\n'
5756 '\n'
5757 'If a name binding operation occurs anywhere within a code '
5758 'block, all\n'
5759 'uses of the name within the block are treated as references to '
5760 'the\n'
5761 'current block. This can lead to errors when a name is used '
5762 'within a\n'
5763 'block before it is bound. This rule is subtle. Python lacks\n'
5764 'declarations and allows name binding operations to occur '
5765 'anywhere\n'
5766 'within a code block. The local variables of a code block can '
5767 'be\n'
5768 'determined by scanning the entire text of the block for name '
5769 'binding\n'
5770 'operations. See the FAQ entry on UnboundLocalError for '
5771 'examples.\n'
5772 '\n'
5773 'If the "global" statement occurs within a block, all uses of '
5774 'the names\n'
5775 'specified in the statement refer to the bindings of those names '
5776 'in the\n'
5777 'top-level namespace. Names are resolved in the top-level '
5778 'namespace by\n'
5779 'searching the global namespace, i.e. the namespace of the '
5780 'module\n'
5781 'containing the code block, and the builtins namespace, the '
5782 'namespace\n'
5783 'of the module "builtins". The global namespace is searched '
5784 'first. If\n'
5785 'the names are not found there, the builtins namespace is '
5786 'searched.\n'
5787 'The "global" statement must precede all uses of the listed '
5788 'names.\n'
5789 '\n'
5790 'The "global" statement has the same scope as a name binding '
5791 'operation\n'
5792 'in the same block. If the nearest enclosing scope for a free '
5793 'variable\n'
5794 'contains a global statement, the free variable is treated as a '
5795 'global.\n'
5796 '\n'
5797 'The "nonlocal" statement causes corresponding names to refer '
5798 'to\n'
5799 'previously bound variables in the nearest enclosing function '
5800 'scope.\n'
5801 '"SyntaxError" is raised at compile time if the given name does '
5802 'not\n'
5803 'exist in any enclosing function scope.\n'
5804 '\n'
5805 'The namespace for a module is automatically created the first '
5806 'time a\n'
5807 'module is imported. The main module for a script is always '
5808 'called\n'
5809 '"__main__".\n'
5810 '\n'
5811 'Class definition blocks and arguments to "exec()" and "eval()" '
5812 'are\n'
5813 'special in the context of name resolution. A class definition '
5814 'is an\n'
5815 'executable statement that may use and define names. These '
5816 'references\n'
5817 'follow the normal rules for name resolution with an exception '
5818 'that\n'
5819 'unbound local variables are looked up in the global namespace. '
5820 'The\n'
5821 'namespace of the class definition becomes the attribute '
5822 'dictionary of\n'
5823 'the class. The scope of names defined in a class block is '
5824 'limited to\n'
5825 'the class block; it does not extend to the code blocks of '
5826 'methods –\n'
5827 'this includes comprehensions and generator expressions since '
5828 'they are\n'
5829 'implemented using a function scope. This means that the '
5830 'following\n'
5831 'will fail:\n'
5832 '\n'
5833 ' class A:\n'
5834 ' a = 42\n'
5835 ' b = list(a + i for i in range(10))\n'
5836 '\n'
5837 '\n'
5838 'Builtins and restricted execution\n'
5839 '---------------------------------\n'
5840 '\n'

5842 '"__builtins__"; it is strictly an implementation detail. '
5843 'Users\n'

5966 'exprlists': 'Expression lists\n'
5967 '****************\n'
5968 '\n'
5969 ' expression_list ::= expression ("," expression)* [","]\n'
5970 ' starred_list ::= starred_item ("," starred_item)* '

5987 'the\n'

6003 'floating': 'Floating point literals\n'

6010 ' pointfloat ::= [digitpart] fraction | digitpart "."\n'
6011 ' exponentfloat ::= (digitpart | pointfloat) exponent\n'
6012 ' digitpart ::= digit (["_"] digit)*\n'
6013 ' fraction ::= "." digitpart\n'
6014 ' exponent ::= ("e" | "E") ["+" | "-"] digitpart\n'
6015 '\n'

6017 'using\n'
6018 'radix 10. For example, "077e010" is legal, and denotes the same '
6019 'number\n'
6020 'as "77e10". The allowed range of floating point literals is\n'
6021 'implementation-dependent. As in integer literals, underscores '
6022 'are\n'
6023 'supported for digit grouping.\n'
6024 '\n'
6025 'Some examples of floating point literals:\n'
6026 '\n'
