  • E128 Continuation line under-indented for visual indent
6079 'formatstrings': 'Format String Syntax\n'
6080 '********************\n'
6081 '\n'
6082 'The "str.format()" method and the "Formatter" class share '
6083 'the same\n'
6084 'syntax for format strings (although in the case of '
6085 '"Formatter",\n'
6086 'subclasses can define their own format string syntax). The '
6087 'syntax is\n'
6088 'related to that of formatted string literals, but it is '
6089 'less\n'
6090 'sophisticated and, in particular, does not support '
6091 'arbitrary\n'
6092 'expressions.\n'
6093 '\n'
6094 'Format strings contain “replacement fields” surrounded by '
6095 'curly braces\n'
6096 '"{}". Anything that is not contained in braces is '
6097 'considered literal\n'
6098 'text, which is copied unchanged to the output. If you need '
6099 'to include\n'
6100 'a brace character in the literal text, it can be escaped by '
6101 'doubling:\n'
6102 '"{{" and "}}".\n'
6103 '\n'
6104 'The grammar for a replacement field is as follows:\n'
6105 '\n'
6106 ' replacement_field ::= "{" [field_name] ["!" conversion] '
6107 '[":" format_spec] "}"\n'
6108 ' field_name ::= arg_name ("." attribute_name | "[" '
6109 'element_index "]")*\n'
6110 ' arg_name ::= [identifier | digit+]\n'
6111 ' attribute_name ::= identifier\n'
6112 ' element_index ::= digit+ | index_string\n'
6113 ' index_string ::= <any source character except "]"> '
6114 '+\n'
6115 ' conversion ::= "r" | "s" | "a"\n'
6116 ' format_spec ::= format-spec:format_spec\n'
6117 '\n'
6118 'In less formal terms, the replacement field can start with '
6119 'a\n'
6120 '*field_name* that specifies the object whose value is to be '
6121 'formatted\n'
6122 'and inserted into the output instead of the replacement '
6123 'field. The\n'
6124 '*field_name* is optionally followed by a *conversion* '
6125 'field, which is\n'
6126 'preceded by an exclamation point "\'!\'", and a '
6127 '*format_spec*, which is\n'
6128 'preceded by a colon "\':\'". These specify a non-default '
6129 'format for the\n'
6130 'replacement value.\n'
6131 '\n'
6132 'See also the Format Specification Mini-Language section.\n'
6133 '\n'
6134 'The *field_name* itself begins with an *arg_name* that is '
6135 'either a\n'
6136 'number or a keyword. If it’s a number, it refers to a '
6137 'positional\n'
6138 'argument, and if it’s a keyword, it refers to a named '
6139 'keyword\n'
6140 'argument. An *arg_name* is treated as a number if a call '
6141 'to\n'
6142 '"str.isdecimal()" on the string would return true. If the '
6143 'numerical\n'
6144 'arg_names in a format string are 0, 1, 2, … in sequence, '
6145 'they can all\n'
6146 'be omitted (not just some) and the numbers 0, 1, 2, … will '
6147 'be\n'
6148 'automatically inserted in that order. Because *arg_name* is '
6149 'not quote-\n'
6150 'delimited, it is not possible to specify arbitrary '
6151 'dictionary keys\n'
6152 '(e.g., the strings "\'10\'" or "\':-]\'") within a format '
6153 'string. The\n'
6154 '*arg_name* can be followed by any number of index or '
6155 'attribute\n'
6156 'expressions. An expression of the form "\'.name\'" selects '
6157 'the named\n'
6158 'attribute using "getattr()", while an expression of the '
6159 'form\n'
6160 '"\'[index]\'" does an index lookup using "__getitem__()".\n'
6161 '\n'
6162 'Changed in version 3.1: The positional argument specifiers '
6163 'can be\n'
6164 'omitted for "str.format()", so "\'{} {}\'.format(a, b)" is '
6165 'equivalent to\n'
6166 '"\'{0} {1}\'.format(a, b)".\n'
6167 '\n'
6168 'Changed in version 3.4: The positional argument specifiers '
6169 'can be\n'
6170 'omitted for "Formatter".\n'
6171 '\n'
6172 'Some simple format string examples:\n'
6173 '\n'
6174 ' "First, thou shalt count to {0}" # References first '
6175 'positional argument\n'
6176 ' "Bring me a {}" # Implicitly '
6177 'references the first positional argument\n'
6178 ' "From {} to {}" # Same as "From {0} to '
6179 '{1}"\n'
6180 ' "My quest is {name}" # References keyword '
6181 "argument 'name'\n"
6182 ' "Weight in tons {0.weight}" # \'weight\' attribute '
6183 'of first positional arg\n'
6184 ' "Units destroyed: {players[0]}" # First element of '
6185 "keyword argument 'players'.\n"
6186 '\n'
6187 'The *conversion* field causes a type coercion before '
6188 'formatting.\n'
6189 'Normally, the job of formatting a value is done by the '
6190 '"__format__()"\n'
6191 'method of the value itself. However, in some cases it is '
6192 'desirable to\n'
6193 'force a type to be formatted as a string, overriding its '
6194 'own\n'
6195 'definition of formatting. By converting the value to a '
6196 'string before\n'
6197 'calling "__format__()", the normal formatting logic is '
6198 'bypassed.\n'
6199 '\n'
6200 'Three conversion flags are currently supported: "\'!s\'" '
6201 'which calls\n'
6202 '"str()" on the value, "\'!r\'" which calls "repr()" and '
6203 '"\'!a\'" which\n'
6204 'calls "ascii()".\n'
6205 '\n'
6206 'Some examples:\n'
6207 '\n'
6208 ' "Harold\'s a clever {0!s}" # Calls str() on the '
6209 'argument first\n'
6210 ' "Bring out the holy {name!r}" # Calls repr() on the '
6211 'argument first\n'
6212 ' "More {!a}" # Calls ascii() on the '
6213 'argument first\n'
6214 '\n'
6215 'The *format_spec* field contains a specification of how the '
6216 'value\n'
6217 'should be presented, including such details as field width, '
6218 'alignment,\n'
6219 'padding, decimal precision and so on. Each value type can '
6220 'define its\n'
6221 'own “formatting mini-language” or interpretation of the '
6222 '*format_spec*.\n'
6223 '\n'
6224 'Most built-in types support a common formatting '
6225 'mini-language, which\n'
6226 'is described in the next section.\n'
6227 '\n'
6228 'A *format_spec* field can also include nested replacement '
6229 'fields\n'
6230 'within it. These nested replacement fields may contain a '
6231 'field name,\n'
6232 'conversion flag and format specification, but deeper '
6233 'nesting is not\n'
6234 'allowed. The replacement fields within the format_spec '
6235 'are\n'
6236 'substituted before the *format_spec* string is interpreted. '
6237 'This\n'
6238 'allows the formatting of a value to be dynamically '
6239 'specified.\n'
6240 '\n'
6241 'See the Format examples section for some examples.\n'
6242 '\n'
6243 '\n'
6244 'Format Specification Mini-Language\n'
6245 '==================================\n'
6246 '\n'
6247 '“Format specifications” are used within replacement fields '
6248 'contained\n'
6249 'within a format string to define how individual values are '
6250 'presented\n'
6251 '(see Format String Syntax and f-strings). They can also be '
6252 'passed\n'
6253 'directly to the built-in "format()" function. Each '
6254 'formattable type\n'
6255 'may define how the format specification is to be '
6256 'interpreted.\n'
6257 '\n'
6258 'Most built-in types implement the following options for '
6259 'format\n'
6260 'specifications, although some of the formatting options are '
6261 'only\n'
6262 'supported by the numeric types.\n'
6263 '\n'
6264 'A general convention is that an empty format specification '
6265 'produces\n'
6266 'the same result as if you had called "str()" on the value. '
6267 'A non-empty\n'
6268 'format specification typically modifies the result.\n'
6269 '\n'
6270 'The general form of a *standard format specifier* is:\n'
6271 '\n'
6272 ' format_spec ::= '
6273 '[[fill]align][sign]["z"]["#"]["0"][width][grouping_option]["." '
6274 'precision][type]\n'
6275 ' fill ::= <any character>\n'
6276 ' align ::= "<" | ">" | "=" | "^"\n'
6277 ' sign ::= "+" | "-" | " "\n'
6278 ' width ::= digit+\n'
6279 ' grouping_option ::= "_" | ","\n'
6280 ' precision ::= digit+\n'
6281 ' type ::= "b" | "c" | "d" | "e" | "E" | "f" | '
6282 '"F" | "g" | "G" | "n" | "o" | "s" | "x" | "X" | "%"\n'
6283 '\n'
6284 'If a valid *align* value is specified, it can be preceded '
6285 'by a *fill*\n'
6286 'character that can be any character and defaults to a space '
6287 'if\n'
6288 'omitted. It is not possible to use a literal curly brace '
6289 '(”"{"” or\n'
6290 '“"}"”) as the *fill* character in a formatted string '
6291 'literal or when\n'
6292 'using the "str.format()" method. However, it is possible '
6293 'to insert a\n'
6294 'curly brace with a nested replacement field. This '
6295 'limitation doesn’t\n'
6296 'affect the "format()" function.\n'
6297 '\n'
6298 'The meaning of the various alignment options is as '
6299 'follows:\n'
6300 '\n'
6301 '+-----------+------------------------------------------------------------+\n'
6302 '| Option | '
6303 'Meaning '
6304 '|\n'
6305 '|===========|============================================================|\n'
6306 '| "\'<\'" | Forces the field to be left-aligned within '
6307 'the available |\n'
6308 '| | space (this is the default for most '
6309 'objects). |\n'
6310 '+-----------+------------------------------------------------------------+\n'
6311 '| "\'>\'" | Forces the field to be right-aligned within '
6312 'the available |\n'
6313 '| | space (this is the default for '
6314 'numbers). |\n'
6315 '+-----------+------------------------------------------------------------+\n'
6316 '| "\'=\'" | Forces the padding to be placed after the '
6317 'sign (if any) |\n'
6318 '| | but before the digits. This is used for '
6319 'printing fields |\n'
6320 '| | in the form ‘+000000120’. This alignment '
6321 'option is only |\n'
6322 '| | valid for numeric types. It becomes the '
6323 'default for |\n'
6324 '| | numbers when ‘0’ immediately precedes the '
6325 'field width. |\n'
6326 '+-----------+------------------------------------------------------------+\n'
6327 '| "\'^\'" | Forces the field to be centered within the '
6328 'available |\n'
6329 '| | '
6330 'space. '
6331 '|\n'
6332 '+-----------+------------------------------------------------------------+\n'
6333 '\n'
6334 'Note that unless a minimum field width is defined, the '
6335 'field width\n'
6336 'will always be the same size as the data to fill it, so '
6337 'that the\n'
6338 'alignment option has no meaning in this case.\n'
6339 '\n'
6340 'The *sign* option is only valid for number types, and can '
6341 'be one of\n'
6342 'the following:\n'
6343 '\n'
6344 '+-----------+------------------------------------------------------------+\n'
6345 '| Option | '
6346 'Meaning '
6347 '|\n'
6348 '|===========|============================================================|\n'
6349 '| "\'+\'" | indicates that a sign should be used for '
6350 'both positive as |\n'
6351 '| | well as negative '
6352 'numbers. |\n'
6353 '+-----------+------------------------------------------------------------+\n'
6354 '| "\'-\'" | indicates that a sign should be used only '
6355 'for negative |\n'
6356 '| | numbers (this is the default '
6357 'behavior). |\n'
6358 '+-----------+------------------------------------------------------------+\n'
6359 '| space | indicates that a leading space should be used '
6360 'on positive |\n'
6361 '| | numbers, and a minus sign on negative '
6362 'numbers. |\n'
6363 '+-----------+------------------------------------------------------------+\n'
6364 '\n'
6365 'The "\'z\'" option coerces negative zero floating-point '
6366 'values to\n'
6367 'positive zero after rounding to the format precision. This '
6368 'option is\n'
6369 'only valid for floating-point presentation types.\n'
6370 '\n'
6371 'Changed in version 3.11: Added the "\'z\'" option (see also '
6372 '**PEP\n'
6373 '682**).\n'
6374 '\n'
6375 'The "\'#\'" option causes the “alternate form” to be used '
6376 'for the\n'
6377 'conversion. The alternate form is defined differently for '
6378 'different\n'
6379 'types. This option is only valid for integer, float and '
6380 'complex\n'
6381 'types. For integers, when binary, octal, or hexadecimal '
6382 'output is\n'
6383 'used, this option adds the respective prefix "\'0b\'", '
6384 '"\'0o\'", "\'0x\'",\n'
6385 'or "\'0X\'" to the output value. For float and complex the '
6386 'alternate\n'
6387 'form causes the result of the conversion to always contain '
6388 'a decimal-\n'
6389 'point character, even if no digits follow it. Normally, a '
6390 'decimal-\n'
6391 'point character appears in the result of these conversions '
6392 'only if a\n'
6393 'digit follows it. In addition, for "\'g\'" and "\'G\'" '
6394 'conversions,\n'
6395 'trailing zeros are not removed from the result.\n'
6396 '\n'
6397 'The "\',\'" option signals the use of a comma for a '
6398 'thousands separator.\n'
6399 'For a locale aware separator, use the "\'n\'" integer '
6400 'presentation type\n'
6401 'instead.\n'
6402 '\n'
6403 'Changed in version 3.1: Added the "\',\'" option (see also '
6404 '**PEP 378**).\n'
6405 '\n'
6406 'The "\'_\'" option signals the use of an underscore for a '
6407 'thousands\n'
6408 'separator for floating point presentation types and for '
6409 'integer\n'
6410 'presentation type "\'d\'". For integer presentation types '
6411 '"\'b\'", "\'o\'",\n'
6412 '"\'x\'", and "\'X\'", underscores will be inserted every 4 '
6413 'digits. For\n'
6414 'other presentation types, specifying this option is an '
6415 'error.\n'
6416 '\n'
6417 'Changed in version 3.6: Added the "\'_\'" option (see also '
6418 '**PEP 515**).\n'
6419 '\n'
6420 '*width* is a decimal integer defining the minimum total '
6421 'field width,\n'
6422 'including any prefixes, separators, and other formatting '
6423 'characters.\n'
6424 'If not specified, then the field width will be determined '
6425 'by the\n'
6426 'content.\n'
6427 '\n'
6428 'When no explicit alignment is given, preceding the *width* '
6429 'field by a\n'
6430 'zero ("\'0\'") character enables sign-aware zero-padding '
6431 'for numeric\n'
6432 'types. This is equivalent to a *fill* character of "\'0\'" '
6433 'with an\n'
6434 '*alignment* type of "\'=\'".\n'
6435 '\n'
6436 'Changed in version 3.10: Preceding the *width* field by '
6437 '"\'0\'" no\n'
6438 'longer affects the default alignment for strings.\n'
6439 '\n'
6440 'The *precision* is a decimal integer indicating how many '
6441 'digits should\n'
6442 'be displayed after the decimal point for presentation types '
6443 '"\'f\'" and\n'
6444 '"\'F\'", or before and after the decimal point for '
6445 'presentation types\n'
6446 '"\'g\'" or "\'G\'". For string presentation types the '
6447 'field indicates the\n'
6448 'maximum field size - in other words, how many characters '
6449 'will be used\n'
6450 'from the field content. The *precision* is not allowed for '
6451 'integer\n'
6452 'presentation types.\n'
6453 '\n'
6454 'Finally, the *type* determines how the data should be '
6455 'presented.\n'
6456 '\n'
6457 'The available string presentation types are:\n'
6458 '\n'
6459 ' '
6460 '+-----------+------------------------------------------------------------+\n'
6461 ' | Type | '
6462 'Meaning '
6463 '|\n'
6464 ' '
6465 '|===========|============================================================|\n'
6466 ' | "\'s\'" | String format. This is the default type '
6467 'for strings and |\n'
6468 ' | | may be '
6469 'omitted. |\n'
6470 ' '
6471 '+-----------+------------------------------------------------------------+\n'
6472 ' | None | The same as '
6473 '"\'s\'". |\n'
6474 ' '
6475 '+-----------+------------------------------------------------------------+\n'
6476 '\n'
6477 'The available integer presentation types are:\n'
6478 '\n'
6479 ' '
6480 '+-----------+------------------------------------------------------------+\n'
6481 ' | Type | '
6482 'Meaning '
6483 '|\n'
6484 ' '

6486 ' | "\'b\'" | Binary format. Outputs the number in '
6487 'base 2. |\n'
6488 ' '
6489 '+-----------+------------------------------------------------------------+\n'
6490 ' | "\'c\'" | Character. Converts the integer to the '
6491 'corresponding |\n'
6492 ' | | unicode character before '
6493 'printing. |\n'
6494 ' '
6495 '+-----------+------------------------------------------------------------+\n'
6496 ' | "\'d\'" | Decimal Integer. Outputs the number in '
6497 'base 10. |\n'
6498 ' '
6499 '+-----------+------------------------------------------------------------+\n'
6500 ' | "\'o\'" | Octal format. Outputs the number in base '
6501 '8. |\n'
6502 ' '
6503 '+-----------+------------------------------------------------------------+\n'
6504 ' | "\'x\'" | Hex format. Outputs the number in base '
6505 '16, using lower- |\n'
6506 ' | | case letters for the digits above '
6507 '9. |\n'
6508 ' '
6509 '+-----------+------------------------------------------------------------+\n'
6510 ' | "\'X\'" | Hex format. Outputs the number in base '
6511 '16, using upper- |\n'
6512 ' | | case letters for the digits above 9. In '
6513 'case "\'#\'" is |\n'
6514 ' | | specified, the prefix "\'0x\'" will be '
6515 'upper-cased to "\'0X\'" |\n'
6516 ' | | as '
6517 'well. |\n'
6518 ' '
6519 '+-----------+------------------------------------------------------------+\n'
6520 ' | "\'n\'" | Number. This is the same as "\'d\'", '
6521 'except that it uses the |\n'
6522 ' | | current locale setting to insert the '
6523 'appropriate number |\n'
6524 ' | | separator '
6525 'characters. |\n'
6526 ' '
6527 '+-----------+------------------------------------------------------------+\n'
6528 ' | None | The same as '
6529 '"\'d\'". |\n'
6530 ' '
6531 '+-----------+------------------------------------------------------------+\n'
6532 '\n'
6533 'In addition to the above presentation types, integers can '
6534 'be formatted\n'
6535 'with the floating point presentation types listed below '
6536 '(except "\'n\'"\n'
6537 'and "None"). When doing so, "float()" is used to convert '
6538 'the integer\n'
6539 'to a floating point number before formatting.\n'
6540 '\n'
6541 'The available presentation types for "float" and "Decimal" '
6542 'values are:\n'
6543 '\n'
6544 ' '
6545 '+-----------+------------------------------------------------------------+\n'
6546 ' | Type | '
6547 'Meaning '
6548 '|\n'
6549 ' '
6550 '|===========|============================================================|\n'
6551 ' | "\'e\'" | Scientific notation. For a given '
6552 'precision "p", formats |\n'
6553 ' | | the number in scientific notation with the '
6554 'letter ‘e’ |\n'
6555 ' | | separating the coefficient from the '
6556 'exponent. The |\n'
6557 ' | | coefficient has one digit before and "p" '
6558 'digits after the |\n'
6559 ' | | decimal point, for a total of "p + 1" '
6560 'significant digits. |\n'
6561 ' | | With no precision given, uses a precision '
6562 'of "6" digits |\n'
6563 ' | | after the decimal point for "float", and '
6564 'shows all |\n'
6565 ' | | coefficient digits for "Decimal". If no '
6566 'digits follow the |\n'
6567 ' | | decimal point, the decimal point is also '
6568 'removed unless |\n'
6569 ' | | the "#" option is '
6570 'used. |\n'
6571 ' '
6572 '+-----------+------------------------------------------------------------+\n'
6573 ' | "\'E\'" | Scientific notation. Same as "\'e\'" '
6574 'except it uses an upper |\n'
6575 ' | | case ‘E’ as the separator '
6576 'character. |\n'
6577 ' '
6578 '+-----------+------------------------------------------------------------+\n'
6579 ' | "\'f\'" | Fixed-point notation. For a given '
6580 'precision "p", formats |\n'
6581 ' | | the number as a decimal number with '
6582 'exactly "p" digits |\n'
6583 ' | | following the decimal point. With no '
6584 'precision given, uses |\n'
6585 ' | | a precision of "6" digits after the '
6586 'decimal point for |\n'
6587 ' | | "float", and uses a precision large enough '
6588 'to show all |\n'
6589 ' | | coefficient digits for "Decimal". If no '
6590 'digits follow the |\n'
6591 ' | | decimal point, the decimal point is also '
6592 'removed unless |\n'
6593 ' | | the "#" option is '
6594 'used. |\n'
6595 ' '
6596 '+-----------+------------------------------------------------------------+\n'
6597 ' | "\'F\'" | Fixed-point notation. Same as "\'f\'", '
6598 'but converts "nan" to |\n'
6599 ' | | "NAN" and "inf" to '
6600 '"INF". |\n'
6601 ' '
6602 '+-----------+------------------------------------------------------------+\n'
6603 ' | "\'g\'" | General format. For a given precision '
6604 '"p >= 1", this |\n'
6605 ' | | rounds the number to "p" significant '
6606 'digits and then |\n'
6607 ' | | formats the result in either fixed-point '
6608 'format or in |\n'
6609 ' | | scientific notation, depending on its '
6610 'magnitude. A |\n'
6611 ' | | precision of "0" is treated as equivalent '
6612 'to a precision |\n'
6613 ' | | of "1". The precise rules are as follows: '
6614 'suppose that |\n'
6615 ' | | the result formatted with presentation '
6616 'type "\'e\'" and |\n'
6617 ' | | precision "p-1" would have exponent '
6618 '"exp". Then, if "m <= |\n'
6619 ' | | exp < p", where "m" is -4 for floats and '
6620 '-6 for |\n'
6621 ' | | "Decimals", the number is formatted with '
6622 'presentation type |\n'
6623 ' | | "\'f\'" and precision "p-1-exp". '
6624 'Otherwise, the number is |\n'
6625 ' | | formatted with presentation type "\'e\'" '
6626 'and precision |\n'
6627 ' | | "p-1". In both cases insignificant '
6628 'trailing zeros are |\n'
6629 ' | | removed from the significand, and the '
6630 'decimal point is |\n'
6631 ' | | also removed if there are no remaining '
6632 'digits following |\n'
6633 ' | | it, unless the "\'#\'" option is used. '
6634 'With no precision |\n'
6635 ' | | given, uses a precision of "6" significant '
6636 'digits for |\n'
6637 ' | | "float". For "Decimal", the coefficient of '
6638 'the result is |\n'
6639 ' | | formed from the coefficient digits of the '
6640 'value; |\n'
6641 ' | | scientific notation is used for values '
6642 'smaller than "1e-6" |\n'
6643 ' | | in absolute value and values where the '
6644 'place value of the |\n'
6645 ' | | least significant digit is larger than 1, '
6646 'and fixed-point |\n'
6647 ' | | notation is used otherwise. Positive and '
6648 'negative |\n'
6649 ' | | infinity, positive and negative zero, and '
6650 'nans, are |\n'
6651 ' | | formatted as "inf", "-inf", "0", "-0" and '
6652 '"nan" |\n'
6653 ' | | respectively, regardless of the '
6654 'precision. |\n'
6655 ' '
6656 '+-----------+------------------------------------------------------------+\n'
6657 ' | "\'G\'" | General format. Same as "\'g\'" except '
6658 'switches to "\'E\'" if |\n'
6659 ' | | the number gets too large. The '
6660 'representations of infinity |\n'
6661 ' | | and NaN are uppercased, '
6662 'too. |\n'
6663 ' '
6664 '+-----------+------------------------------------------------------------+\n'
6665 ' | "\'n\'" | Number. This is the same as "\'g\'", '
6666 'except that it uses the |\n'
6667 ' | | current locale setting to insert the '
6668 'appropriate number |\n'
6669 ' | | separator '
6670 'characters. |\n'
6671 ' '
6672 '+-----------+------------------------------------------------------------+\n'
6673 ' | "\'%\'" | Percentage. Multiplies the number by 100 '
6674 'and displays in |\n'
6675 ' | | fixed ("\'f\'") format, followed by a '
6676 'percent sign. |\n'
6677 ' '
6678 '+-----------+------------------------------------------------------------+\n'
6679 ' | None | For "float" this is the same as "\'g\'", '
6680 'except that when |\n'
6681 ' | | fixed-point notation is used to format the '
6682 'result, it |\n'
6683 ' | | always includes at least one digit past '
6684 'the decimal point. |\n'
6685 ' | | The precision used is as large as needed '
6686 'to represent the |\n'
6687 ' | | given value faithfully. For "Decimal", '
6688 'this is the same |\n'
6689 ' | | as either "\'g\'" or "\'G\'" depending on '
6690 'the value of |\n'
6691 ' | | "context.capitals" for the current decimal '
6692 'context. The |\n'
6693 ' | | overall effect is to match the output of '
6694 '"str()" as |\n'
6695 ' | | altered by the other format '
6696 'modifiers. |\n'
6697 ' '
6698 '+-----------+------------------------------------------------------------+\n'
6699 '\n'
6700 '\n'
6701 'Format examples\n'
6702 '===============\n'
6703 '\n'
6704 'This section contains examples of the "str.format()" syntax '
6705 'and\n'
6706 'comparison with the old "%"-formatting.\n'
6707 '\n'
6708 'In most of the cases the syntax is similar to the old '
6709 '"%"-formatting,\n'
6710 'with the addition of the "{}" and with ":" used instead of '
6711 '"%". For\n'
6712 'example, "\'%03.2f\'" can be translated to "\'{:03.2f}\'".\n'
6713 '\n'
6714 'The new format syntax also supports new and different '
6715 'options, shown\n'
6716 'in the following examples.\n'
6717 '\n'
6718 'Accessing arguments by position:\n'
6719 '\n'
6720 " >>> '{0}, {1}, {2}'.format('a', 'b', 'c')\n"
6721 " 'a, b, c'\n"
6722 " >>> '{}, {}, {}'.format('a', 'b', 'c') # 3.1+ only\n"
6723 " 'a, b, c'\n"
6724 " >>> '{2}, {1}, {0}'.format('a', 'b', 'c')\n"
6725 " 'c, b, a'\n"
6726 " >>> '{2}, {1}, {0}'.format(*'abc') # unpacking "
6727 'argument sequence\n'
6728 " 'c, b, a'\n"
6729 " >>> '{0}{1}{0}'.format('abra', 'cad') # arguments' "
6730 'indices can be repeated\n'
6731 " 'abracadabra'\n"
6732 '\n'
6733 'Accessing arguments by name:\n'
6734 '\n'
6735 " >>> 'Coordinates: {latitude}, "
6736 "{longitude}'.format(latitude='37.24N', "
6737 "longitude='-115.81W')\n"
6738 " 'Coordinates: 37.24N, -115.81W'\n"
6739 " >>> coord = {'latitude': '37.24N', 'longitude': "
6740 "'-115.81W'}\n"
6741 " >>> 'Coordinates: {latitude}, "
6742 "{longitude}'.format(**coord)\n"
6743 " 'Coordinates: 37.24N, -115.81W'\n"
6744 '\n'
6745 'Accessing arguments’ attributes:\n'
6746 '\n'
6747 ' >>> c = 3-5j\n'
6748 " >>> ('The complex number {0} is formed from the real "
6749 "part {0.real} '\n"
6750 " ... 'and the imaginary part {0.imag}.').format(c)\n"
6751 " 'The complex number (3-5j) is formed from the real part "
6752 "3.0 and the imaginary part -5.0.'\n"
6753 ' >>> class Point:\n'
6754 ' ... def __init__(self, x, y):\n'
6755 ' ... self.x, self.y = x, y\n'
6756 ' ... def __str__(self):\n'
6757 " ... return 'Point({self.x}, "
6758 "{self.y})'.format(self=self)\n"
6759 ' ...\n'
6760 ' >>> str(Point(4, 2))\n'
6761 " 'Point(4, 2)'\n"
6762 '\n'
6763 'Accessing arguments’ items:\n'
6764 '\n'
6765 ' >>> coord = (3, 5)\n'
6766 " >>> 'X: {0[0]}; Y: {0[1]}'.format(coord)\n"
6767 " 'X: 3; Y: 5'\n"
6768 '\n'
6769 'Replacing "%s" and "%r":\n'
6770 '\n'
6771 ' >>> "repr() shows quotes: {!r}; str() doesn\'t: '
6772 '{!s}".format(\'test1\', \'test2\')\n'
6773 ' "repr() shows quotes: \'test1\'; str() doesn\'t: test2"\n'
6774 '\n'
6775 'Aligning the text and specifying a width:\n'
6776 '\n'
6777 " >>> '{:<30}'.format('left aligned')\n"
6778 " 'left aligned '\n"
6779 " >>> '{:>30}'.format('right aligned')\n"
6780 " ' right aligned'\n"
6781 " >>> '{:^30}'.format('centered')\n"
6782 " ' centered '\n"
6783 " >>> '{:*^30}'.format('centered') # use '*' as a fill "
6784 'char\n'
6785 " '***********centered***********'\n"
6786 '\n'
6787 'Replacing "%+f", "%-f", and "% f" and specifying a sign:\n'
6788 '\n'
6789 " >>> '{:+f}; {:+f}'.format(3.14, -3.14) # show it "
6790 'always\n'
6791 " '+3.140000; -3.140000'\n"
6792 " >>> '{: f}; {: f}'.format(3.14, -3.14) # show a space "
6793 'for positive numbers\n'
6794 " ' 3.140000; -3.140000'\n"
6795 " >>> '{:-f}; {:-f}'.format(3.14, -3.14) # show only the "
6796 "minus -- same as '{:f}; {:f}'\n"
6797 " '3.140000; -3.140000'\n"
6798 '\n'
6799 'Replacing "%x" and "%o" and converting the value to '
6800 'different bases:\n'
6801 '\n'
6802 ' >>> # format also supports binary numbers\n'
6803 ' >>> "int: {0:d}; hex: {0:x}; oct: {0:o}; bin: '
6804 '{0:b}".format(42)\n'
6805 " 'int: 42; hex: 2a; oct: 52; bin: 101010'\n"
6806 ' >>> # with 0x, 0o, or 0b as prefix:\n'
6807 ' >>> "int: {0:d}; hex: {0:#x}; oct: {0:#o}; bin: '
6808 '{0:#b}".format(42)\n'
6809 " 'int: 42; hex: 0x2a; oct: 0o52; bin: 0b101010'\n"
6810 '\n'
6811 'Using the comma as a thousands separator:\n'
6812 '\n'
6813 " >>> '{:,}'.format(1234567890)\n"
6814 " '1,234,567,890'\n"
6815 '\n'
6816 'Expressing a percentage:\n'
6817 '\n'
6818 ' >>> points = 19\n'
6819 ' >>> total = 22\n'
6820 " >>> 'Correct answers: {:.2%}'.format(points/total)\n"
6821 " 'Correct answers: 86.36%'\n"
6822 '\n'
6823 'Using type-specific formatting:\n'
6824 '\n'
6825 ' >>> import datetime\n'
6826 ' >>> d = datetime.datetime(2010, 7, 4, 12, 15, 58)\n'
6827 " >>> '{:%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S}'.format(d)\n"
6828 " '2010-07-04 12:15:58'\n"
6829 '\n'
6830 'Nesting arguments and more complex examples:\n'
6831 '\n'
6832 " >>> for align, text in zip('<^>', ['left', 'center', "
6833 "'right']):\n"
6834 " ... '{0:{fill}{align}16}'.format(text, fill=align, "
6835 'align=align)\n'
6836 ' ...\n'
6837 " 'left<<<<<<<<<<<<'\n"
6838 " '^^^^^center^^^^^'\n"
6839 " '>>>>>>>>>>>right'\n"
6840 ' >>>\n'
6841 ' >>> octets = [192, 168, 0, 1]\n'
6842 " >>> '{:02X}{:02X}{:02X}{:02X}'.format(*octets)\n"
6843 " 'C0A80001'\n"
6844 ' >>> int(_, 16)\n'
6845 ' 3232235521\n'
6846 ' >>>\n'
6847 ' >>> width = 5\n'
6848 ' >>> for num in range(5,12): \n'
6849 " ... for base in 'dXob':\n"
6850 " ... print('{0:{width}{base}}'.format(num, "
6851 "base=base, width=width), end=' ')\n"
6852 ' ... print()\n'
6853 ' ...\n'
6854 ' 5 5 5 101\n'
6855 ' 6 6 6 110\n'
6856 ' 7 7 7 111\n'
6857 ' 8 8 10 1000\n'
6858 ' 9 9 11 1001\n'
6859 ' 10 A 12 1010\n'
6860 ' 11 B 13 1011\n',

6861 'function': 'Function definitions\n'
6862 '********************\n'
6863 '\n'
6864 'A function definition defines a user-defined function object '
6865 '(see\n'
6866 'section The standard type hierarchy):\n'
6867 '\n'
6868 ' funcdef ::= [decorators] "def" funcname "(" '
6869 '[parameter_list] ")"\n'
6870 ' ["->" expression] ":" suite\n'
6871 ' decorators ::= decorator+\n'
6872 ' decorator ::= "@" assignment_expression '
6873 'NEWLINE\n'
6874 ' parameter_list ::= defparameter ("," '
6875 'defparameter)* "," "/" ["," [parameter_list_no_posonly]]\n'
6876 ' | parameter_list_no_posonly\n'
6877 ' parameter_list_no_posonly ::= defparameter ("," '
6878 'defparameter)* ["," [parameter_list_starargs]]\n'
6879 ' | parameter_list_starargs\n'
6880 ' parameter_list_starargs ::= "*" [parameter] ("," '
6881 'defparameter)* ["," ["**" parameter [","]]]\n'
6882 ' | "**" parameter [","]\n'
6883 ' parameter ::= identifier [":" expression]\n'
6884 ' defparameter ::= parameter ["=" expression]\n'
6885 ' funcname ::= identifier\n'
6886 '\n'
6887 'A function definition is an executable statement. Its execution '
6888 'binds\n'
6889 'the function name in the current local namespace to a function '
6890 'object\n'
6891 '(a wrapper around the executable code for the function). This\n'
6892 'function object contains a reference to the current global '
6893 'namespace\n'
6894 'as the global namespace to be used when the function is called.\n'
6895 '\n'
6896 'The function definition does not execute the function body; this '
6897 'gets\n'
6898 'executed only when the function is called. [4]\n'
6899 '\n'
6900 'A function definition may be wrapped by one or more *decorator*\n'
6901 'expressions. Decorator expressions are evaluated when the '
6902 'function is\n'
6903 'defined, in the scope that contains the function definition. '
6904 'The\n'
6905 'result must be a callable, which is invoked with the function '
6906 'object\n'
6907 'as the only argument. The returned value is bound to the '
6908 'function name\n'
6909 'instead of the function object. Multiple decorators are applied '
6910 'in\n'
6911 'nested fashion. For example, the following code\n'
6912 '\n'
6913 ' @f1(arg)\n'
6914 ' @f2\n'
6915 ' def func(): pass\n'
6916 '\n'
6917 'is roughly equivalent to\n'
6918 '\n'
6919 ' def func(): pass\n'
6920 ' func = f1(arg)(f2(func))\n'
6921 '\n'
6922 'except that the original function is not temporarily bound to '
6923 'the name\n'
6924 '"func".\n'
6925 '\n'
6926 'Changed in version 3.9: Functions may be decorated with any '
6927 'valid\n'
6928 '"assignment_expression". Previously, the grammar was much more\n'
6929 'restrictive; see **PEP 614** for details.\n'
6930 '\n'
6931 'When one or more *parameters* have the form *parameter* "="\n'
6932 '*expression*, the function is said to have “default parameter '
6933 'values.”\n'
6934 'For a parameter with a default value, the corresponding '
6935 '*argument* may\n'
6936 'be omitted from a call, in which case the parameter’s default '
6937 'value is\n'
6938 'substituted. If a parameter has a default value, all following\n'
6939 'parameters up until the “"*"” must also have a default value — '
6940 'this is\n'
6941 'a syntactic restriction that is not expressed by the grammar.\n'
6942 '\n'
6943 '**Default parameter values are evaluated from left to right when '
6944 'the\n'
6945 'function definition is executed.** This means that the '
6946 'expression is\n'
6947 'evaluated once, when the function is defined, and that the same '
6948 '“pre-\n'
6949 'computed” value is used for each call. This is especially '
6950 'important\n'
6951 'to understand when a default parameter value is a mutable '
6952 'object, such\n'
6953 'as a list or a dictionary: if the function modifies the object '
6954 '(e.g.\n'
6955 'by appending an item to a list), the default parameter value is '
6956 'in\n'
6957 'effect modified. This is generally not what was intended. A '
6958 'way\n'
6959 'around this is to use "None" as the default, and explicitly test '
6960 'for\n'
6961 'it in the body of the function, e.g.:\n'
6962 '\n'
6963 ' def whats_on_the_telly(penguin=None):\n'
6964 ' if penguin is None:\n'
6965 ' penguin = []\n'
6966 ' penguin.append("property of the zoo")\n'
6967 ' return penguin\n'
6968 '\n'
6969 'Function call semantics are described in more detail in section '
6970 'Calls.\n'
6971 'A function call always assigns values to all parameters '
6972 'mentioned in\n'
6973 'the parameter list, either from positional arguments, from '
6974 'keyword\n'
6975 'arguments, or from default values. If the form “"*identifier"” '
6976 'is\n'
6977 'present, it is initialized to a tuple receiving any excess '
6978 'positional\n'
6979 'parameters, defaulting to the empty tuple. If the form\n'
6980 '“"**identifier"” is present, it is initialized to a new ordered\n'
6981 'mapping receiving any excess keyword arguments, defaulting to a '
6982 'new\n'
6983 'empty mapping of the same type. Parameters after “"*"” or\n'
6984 '“"*identifier"” are keyword-only parameters and may only be '
6985 'passed by\n'
6986 'keyword arguments. Parameters before “"/"” are positional-only\n'
6987 'parameters and may only be passed by positional arguments.\n'
6988 '\n'
6989 'Changed in version 3.8: The "/" function parameter syntax may be '
6990 'used\n'
6991 'to indicate positional-only parameters. See **PEP 570** for '
6992 'details.\n'
6993 '\n'
6994 'Parameters may have an *annotation* of the form “": '
6995 'expression"”\n'
6996 'following the parameter name. Any parameter may have an '
6997 'annotation,\n'
6998 'even those of the form "*identifier" or "**identifier". '
6999 'Functions may\n'
7000 'have “return” annotation of the form “"-> expression"” after '
7001 'the\n'
7002 'parameter list. These annotations can be any valid Python '
7003 'expression.\n'
7004 'The presence of annotations does not change the semantics of a\n'
7005 'function. The annotation values are available as values of a\n'
7006 'dictionary keyed by the parameters’ names in the '
7007 '"__annotations__"\n'
7008 'attribute of the function object. If the "annotations" import '
7009 'from\n'
7010 '"__future__" is used, annotations are preserved as strings at '
7011 'runtime\n'
7012 'which enables postponed evaluation. Otherwise, they are '
7013 'evaluated\n'
7014 'when the function definition is executed. In this case '
7015 'annotations\n'
7016 'may be evaluated in a different order than they appear in the '
7017 'source\n'
7018 'code.\n'
7019 '\n'
7020 'It is also possible to create anonymous functions (functions not '
7021 'bound\n'
7022 'to a name), for immediate use in expressions. This uses lambda\n'
7023 'expressions, described in section Lambdas. Note that the '
7024 'lambda\n'
7025 'expression is merely a shorthand for a simplified function '
7026 'definition;\n'
7027 'a function defined in a “"def"” statement can be passed around '
7028 'or\n'
7029 'assigned to another name just like a function defined by a '
7030 'lambda\n'
7031 'expression. The “"def"” form is actually more powerful since '
7032 'it\n'
7033 'allows the execution of multiple statements and annotations.\n'
7034 '\n'
7035 '**Programmer’s note:** Functions are first-class objects. A '
7036 '“"def"”\n'
7037 'statement executed inside a function definition defines a local\n'
7038 'function that can be returned or passed around. Free variables '
7039 'used\n'
7040 'in the nested function can access the local variables of the '
7041 'function\n'
7042 'containing the def. See section Naming and binding for '
7043 'details.\n'
7044 '\n'
7045 'See also:\n'
7046 '\n'
7047 ' **PEP 3107** - Function Annotations\n'
7048 ' The original specification for function annotations.\n'
7049 '\n'
7050 ' **PEP 484** - Type Hints\n'
7051 ' Definition of a standard meaning for annotations: type '
7052 'hints.\n'
7053 '\n'
7054 ' **PEP 526** - Syntax for Variable Annotations\n'
7055 ' Ability to type hint variable declarations, including '
7056 'class\n'
7057 ' variables and instance variables.\n'
7058 '\n'
7059 ' **PEP 563** - Postponed Evaluation of Annotations\n'
7060 ' Support for forward references within annotations by '
7061 'preserving\n'
7062 ' annotations in a string form at runtime instead of eager\n'
7063 ' evaluation.\n'
7064 '\n'
7065 ' **PEP 318** - Decorators for Functions and Methods\n'
7066 ' Function and method decorators were introduced. Class '
7067 'decorators\n'
7068 ' were introduced in **PEP 3129**.\n',

7069 'global': 'The "global" statement\n'
7070 '**********************\n'
7071 '\n'
7072 ' global_stmt ::= "global" identifier ("," identifier)*\n'
7073 '\n'
7074 'The "global" statement is a declaration which holds for the '
7075 'entire\n'
7076 'current code block. It means that the listed identifiers are to '
7077 'be\n'
7078 'interpreted as globals. It would be impossible to assign to a '
7079 'global\n'
7080 'variable without "global", although free variables may refer to\n'
7081 'globals without being declared global.\n'
7082 '\n'
7083 'Names listed in a "global" statement must not be used in the same '
7084 'code\n'
7085 'block textually preceding that "global" statement.\n'
7086 '\n'
7087 'Names listed in a "global" statement must not be defined as '
7088 'formal\n'
7089 'parameters, or as targets in "with" statements or "except" '
7090 'clauses, or\n'
7091 'in a "for" target list, "class" definition, function definition,\n'
7092 '"import" statement, or variable annotation.\n'
7093 '\n'
7094 '**CPython implementation detail:** The current implementation does '
7095 'not\n'
7096 'enforce some of these restrictions, but programs should not abuse '
7097 'this\n'
7098 'freedom, as future implementations may enforce them or silently '
7099 'change\n'
7100 'the meaning of the program.\n'
7101 '\n'
7102 '**Programmer’s note:** "global" is a directive to the parser. It\n'
7103 'applies only to code parsed at the same time as the "global"\n'
7104 'statement. In particular, a "global" statement contained in a '
7105 'string\n'
7106 'or code object supplied to the built-in "exec()" function does '
7107 'not\n'
7108 'affect the code block *containing* the function call, and code\n'
7109 'contained in such a string is unaffected by "global" statements in '
7110 'the\n'
7111 'code containing the function call. The same applies to the '
7112 '"eval()"\n'
7113 'and "compile()" functions.\n',
  • E128 Continuation line under-indented for visual indent
7114 'id-classes': 'Reserved classes of identifiers\n'
7115 '*******************************\n'
7116 '\n'
7117 'Certain classes of identifiers (besides keywords) have '
7118 'special\n'
7119 'meanings. These classes are identified by the patterns of '
7120 'leading and\n'
7121 'trailing underscore characters:\n'
7122 '\n'
7123 '"_*"\n'
7124 ' Not imported by "from module import *".\n'
7125 '\n'
7126 '"_"\n'
7127 ' In a "case" pattern within a "match" statement, "_" is a '
7128 'soft\n'
7129 ' keyword that denotes a wildcard.\n'
7130 '\n'
7131 ' Separately, the interactive interpreter makes the result of '
7132 'the\n'
7133 ' last evaluation available in the variable "_". (It is '
7134 'stored in the\n'
7135 ' "builtins" module, alongside built-in functions like '
7136 '"print".)\n'
7137 '\n'
7138 ' Elsewhere, "_" is a regular identifier. It is often used to '
7139 'name\n'
7140 ' “special” items, but it is not special to Python itself.\n'
7141 '\n'
7142 ' Note:\n'
7143 '\n'
7144 ' The name "_" is often used in conjunction with\n'
7145 ' internationalization; refer to the documentation for the\n'
7146 ' "gettext" module for more information on this '
7147 'convention.It is\n'
7148 ' also commonly used for unused variables.\n'
7149 '\n'
7150 '"__*__"\n'
7151 ' System-defined names, informally known as “dunder” names. '
7152 'These\n'
7153 ' names are defined by the interpreter and its '
7154 'implementation\n'
7155 ' (including the standard library). Current system names are\n'
7156 ' discussed in the Special method names section and '
7157 'elsewhere. More\n'
7158 ' will likely be defined in future versions of Python. *Any* '
7159 'use of\n'
7160 ' "__*__" names, in any context, that does not follow '
7161 'explicitly\n'
7162 ' documented use, is subject to breakage without warning.\n'
7163 '\n'
7164 '"__*"\n'
7165 ' Class-private names. Names in this category, when used '
7166 'within the\n'
7167 ' context of a class definition, are re-written to use a '
7168 'mangled form\n'
7169 ' to help avoid name clashes between “private” attributes of '
7170 'base and\n'
7171 ' derived classes. See section Identifiers (Names).\n',

7172 'identifiers': 'Identifiers and keywords\n'
7173 '************************\n'
7174 '\n'
7175 'Identifiers (also referred to as *names*) are described by '
7176 'the\n'
7177 'following lexical definitions.\n'
7178 '\n'
7179 'The syntax of identifiers in Python is based on the Unicode '
7180 'standard\n'
7181 'annex UAX-31, with elaboration and changes as defined below; '
7182 'see also\n'
7183 '**PEP 3131** for further details.\n'
7184 '\n'
7185 'Within the ASCII range (U+0001..U+007F), the valid characters '
7186 'for\n'
7187 'identifiers are the same as in Python 2.x: the uppercase and '
7188 'lowercase\n'
7189 'letters "A" through "Z", the underscore "_" and, except for '
7190 'the first\n'

7193 'Python 3.0 introduces additional characters from outside the '
7194 'ASCII\n'

7196 'classification\n'
7197 'uses the version of the Unicode Character Database as '
7198 'included in the\n'
7199 '"unicodedata" module.\n'
7200 '\n'
7201 'Identifiers are unlimited in length. Case is significant.\n'
7202 '\n'

7204 ' id_start ::= <all characters in general categories Lu, '

7211 'normalization is in "id_start xid_continue*">\n'
7212 ' xid_continue ::= <all characters in id_continue whose NFKC '
7213 'normalization is in "id_continue*">\n'

7221 '* *Lt* - titlecase letters\n'
7222 '\n'
7223 '* *Lm* - modifier letters\n'
7224 '\n'
7225 '* *Lo* - other letters\n'
7226 '\n'
7227 '* *Nl* - letter numbers\n'
7228 '\n'
7229 '* *Mn* - nonspacing marks\n'
7230 '\n'
7231 '* *Mc* - spacing combining marks\n'

7233 '* *Nd* - decimal numbers\n'

7271 'Soft Keywords\n'

7273 '\n'
7274 'New in version 3.10.\n'

7287 'while\n'

7289 '"match",\n'

7291 '\n'

7301 '\n'

7304 '\n'

7307 'soft\n'
7308 ' keyword that denotes a wildcard.\n'
7309 '\n'
7310 ' Separately, the interactive interpreter makes the result '

7313 'stored in the\n'

7316 '\n'

7318 'to name\n'
7319 ' “special” items, but it is not special to Python itself.\n'
7320 '\n'
7321 ' Note:\n'

7389 'import': 'The "import" statement\n'
7390 '**********************\n'
7391 '\n'
7392 ' import_stmt ::= "import" module ["as" identifier] ("," '
7393 'module ["as" identifier])*\n'
7394 ' | "from" relative_module "import" identifier '
7395 '["as" identifier]\n'
7396 ' ("," identifier ["as" identifier])*\n'
7397 ' | "from" relative_module "import" "(" '
7398 'identifier ["as" identifier]\n'
7399 ' ("," identifier ["as" identifier])* [","] ")"\n'
7400 ' | "from" relative_module "import" "*"\n'
7401 ' module ::= (identifier ".")* identifier\n'
7402 ' relative_module ::= "."* module | "."+\n'
7403 '\n'
7404 'The basic import statement (no "from" clause) is executed in two\n'
7405 'steps:\n'
7406 '\n'
7407 '1. find a module, loading and initializing it if necessary\n'
7408 '\n'
7409 '2. define a name or names in the local namespace for the scope '
7410 'where\n'
7411 ' the "import" statement occurs.\n'
7412 '\n'
7413 'When the statement contains multiple clauses (separated by commas) '
7414 'the\n'
7415 'two steps are carried out separately for each clause, just as '
7416 'though\n'
7417 'the clauses had been separated out into individual import '
7418 'statements.\n'
7419 '\n'
7420 'The details of the first step, finding and loading modules, are\n'
7421 'described in greater detail in the section on the import system, '
7422 'which\n'
7423 'also describes the various types of packages and modules that can '
7424 'be\n'
7425 'imported, as well as all the hooks that can be used to customize '
7426 'the\n'
7427 'import system. Note that failures in this step may indicate '
7428 'either\n'
7429 'that the module could not be located, *or* that an error occurred\n'
7430 'while initializing the module, which includes execution of the\n'
7431 'module’s code.\n'
7432 '\n'
7433 'If the requested module is retrieved successfully, it will be '
7434 'made\n'
7435 'available in the local namespace in one of three ways:\n'
7436 '\n'
7437 '* If the module name is followed by "as", then the name following '
7438 '"as"\n'
7439 ' is bound directly to the imported module.\n'
7440 '\n'
7441 '* If no other name is specified, and the module being imported is '
7442 'a\n'
7443 ' top level module, the module’s name is bound in the local '
7444 'namespace\n'
7445 ' as a reference to the imported module\n'
7446 '\n'
7447 '* If the module being imported is *not* a top level module, then '
7448 'the\n'
7449 ' name of the top level package that contains the module is bound '
7450 'in\n'
7451 ' the local namespace as a reference to the top level package. '
7452 'The\n'
7453 ' imported module must be accessed using its full qualified name\n'
7454 ' rather than directly\n'
7455 '\n'
7456 'The "from" form uses a slightly more complex process:\n'
7457 '\n'
7458 '1. find the module specified in the "from" clause, loading and\n'
7459 ' initializing it if necessary;\n'
7460 '\n'
7461 '2. for each of the identifiers specified in the "import" clauses:\n'
7462 '\n'
7463 ' 1. check if the imported module has an attribute by that name\n'
7464 '\n'
7465 ' 2. if not, attempt to import a submodule with that name and '
7466 'then\n'
7467 ' check the imported module again for that attribute\n'
7468 '\n'
7469 ' 3. if the attribute is not found, "ImportError" is raised.\n'
7470 '\n'
7471 ' 4. otherwise, a reference to that value is stored in the local\n'
7472 ' namespace, using the name in the "as" clause if it is '
7473 'present,\n'
7474 ' otherwise using the attribute name\n'
7475 '\n'
7476 'Examples:\n'
7477 '\n'
7478 ' import foo # foo imported and bound locally\n'
7479 ' import foo.bar.baz # foo, foo.bar, and foo.bar.baz '
7480 'imported, foo bound locally\n'
7481 ' import foo.bar.baz as fbb # foo, foo.bar, and foo.bar.baz '
7482 'imported, foo.bar.baz bound as fbb\n'
7483 ' from foo.bar import baz # foo, foo.bar, and foo.bar.baz '
7484 'imported, foo.bar.baz bound as baz\n'
7485 ' from foo import attr # foo imported and foo.attr bound as '
7486 'attr\n'
7487 '\n'
7488 'If the list of identifiers is replaced by a star ("\'*\'"), all '
7489 'public\n'
7490 'names defined in the module are bound in the local namespace for '
7491 'the\n'
7492 'scope where the "import" statement occurs.\n'
7493 '\n'
7494 'The *public names* defined by a module are determined by checking '
7495 'the\n'
7496 'module’s namespace for a variable named "__all__"; if defined, it '
7497 'must\n'
7498 'be a sequence of strings which are names defined or imported by '
7499 'that\n'
7500 'module. The names given in "__all__" are all considered public '
7501 'and\n'
7502 'are required to exist. If "__all__" is not defined, the set of '
7503 'public\n'
7504 'names includes all names found in the module’s namespace which do '
7505 'not\n'
7506 'begin with an underscore character ("\'_\'"). "__all__" should '
7507 'contain\n'
7508 'the entire public API. It is intended to avoid accidentally '

7510 'items that are not part of the API (such as library modules which '
7511 'were\n'
7512 'imported and used within the module).\n'
7513 '\n'
7514 'The wild card form of import — "from module import *" — is only\n'
7515 'allowed at the module level. Attempting to use it in class or\n'

7517 '\n'

7520 'absolute name of the module. When a module or package is '

7539 'specification for relative imports is contained in the Package\n'

7551 'Future statements\n'
7552 '=================\n'
7553 '\n'
7554 'A *future statement* is a directive to the compiler that a '
7555 'particular\n'
7556 'module should be compiled using syntax or semantics that will be\n'
7557 'available in a specified future release of Python where the '
7558 'feature\n'
7559 'becomes standard.\n'
7560 '\n'
7561 'The future statement is intended to ease migration to future '
7562 'versions\n'
7563 'of Python that introduce incompatible changes to the language. '
7564 'It\n'
7565 'allows use of the new features on a per-module basis before the\n'
7566 'release in which the feature becomes standard.\n'
7567 '\n'
7568 ' future_stmt ::= "from" "__future__" "import" feature ["as" '
7569 'identifier]\n'
7570 ' ("," feature ["as" identifier])*\n'
7571 ' | "from" "__future__" "import" "(" feature '
7572 '["as" identifier]\n'
7573 ' ("," feature ["as" identifier])* [","] ")"\n'
7574 ' feature ::= identifier\n'
7575 '\n'
7576 'A future statement must appear near the top of the module. The '
7577 'only\n'
7578 'lines that can appear before a future statement are:\n'
7579 '\n'
7580 '* the module docstring (if any),\n'
7581 '\n'
7582 '* comments,\n'
7583 '\n'
7584 '* blank lines, and\n'
7585 '\n'
7586 '* other future statements.\n'
7587 '\n'
7588 'The only feature that requires using the future statement is\n'
7589 '"annotations" (see **PEP 563**).\n'
7590 '\n'
7591 'All historical features enabled by the future statement are still\n'
7592 'recognized by Python 3. The list includes "absolute_import",\n'
7593 '"division", "generators", "generator_stop", "unicode_literals",\n'
7594 '"print_function", "nested_scopes" and "with_statement". They are '
7595 'all\n'
7596 'redundant because they are always enabled, and only kept for '
7597 'backwards\n'
7598 'compatibility.\n'
7599 '\n'
7600 'A future statement is recognized and treated specially at compile\n'
7601 'time: Changes to the semantics of core constructs are often\n'
7602 'implemented by generating different code. It may even be the '
7603 'case\n'
7604 'that a new feature introduces new incompatible syntax (such as a '
7605 'new\n'
7606 'reserved word), in which case the compiler may need to parse the\n'
7607 'module differently. Such decisions cannot be pushed off until\n'
7608 'runtime.\n'
7609 '\n'
7610 'For any given release, the compiler knows which feature names '
7611 'have\n'
7612 'been defined, and raises a compile-time error if a future '
7613 'statement\n'
7614 'contains a feature not known to it.\n'
7615 '\n'
7616 'The direct runtime semantics are the same as for any import '
7617 'statement:\n'
7618 'there is a standard module "__future__", described later, and it '
7619 'will\n'
7620 'be imported in the usual way at the time the future statement is\n'
7621 'executed.\n'
7622 '\n'
7623 'The interesting runtime semantics depend on the specific feature\n'
7624 'enabled by the future statement.\n'
7625 '\n'
7626 'Note that there is nothing special about the statement:\n'
7627 '\n'
7628 ' import __future__ [as name]\n'
7629 '\n'
7630 'That is not a future statement; it’s an ordinary import statement '
7631 'with\n'
7632 'no special semantics or syntax restrictions.\n'
7633 '\n'
7634 'Code compiled by calls to the built-in functions "exec()" and\n'
7635 '"compile()" that occur in a module "M" containing a future '
7636 'statement\n'
7637 'will, by default, use the new syntax or semantics associated with '
7638 'the\n'
7639 'future statement. This can be controlled by optional arguments '
7640 'to\n'
7641 '"compile()" — see the documentation of that function for details.\n'
7642 '\n'
7643 'A future statement typed at an interactive interpreter prompt '
7644 'will\n'
7645 'take effect for the rest of the interpreter session. If an\n'
7646 'interpreter is started with the "-i" option, is passed a script '
7647 'name\n'
7648 'to execute, and the script includes a future statement, it will be '
7649 'in\n'
7650 'effect in the interactive session started after the script is\n'
7651 'executed.\n'
7652 '\n'
7653 'See also:\n'
7654 '\n'
7655 ' **PEP 236** - Back to the __future__\n'
7656 ' The original proposal for the __future__ mechanism.\n',

7779 'naming': 'Naming and binding\n'
7780 '******************\n'
7781 '\n'
7782 '\n'
7783 'Binding of names\n'
7784 '================\n'
7785 '\n'
7786 '*Names* refer to objects. Names are introduced by name binding\n'
7787 'operations.\n'
7788 '\n'
7789 'The following constructs bind names:\n'
7790 '\n'
7791 '* formal parameters to functions,\n'
7792 '\n'
7793 '* class definitions,\n'
7794 '\n'
7795 '* function definitions,\n'
7796 '\n'
7797 '* assignment expressions,\n'
7798 '\n'
7799 '* targets that are identifiers if occurring in an assignment:\n'
7800 '\n'
7801 ' * "for" loop header,\n'
7802 '\n'
7803 ' * after "as" in a "with" statement, "except" clause, "except*"\n'
7804 ' clause, or in the as-pattern in structural pattern matching,\n'
7805 '\n'
7806 ' * in a capture pattern in structural pattern matching\n'
7807 '\n'
7808 '* "import" statements.\n'
7809 '\n'
7810 'The "import" statement of the form "from ... import *" binds all '
7811 'names\n'
7812 'defined in the imported module, except those beginning with an\n'
7813 'underscore. This form may only be used at the module level.\n'
7814 '\n'
7815 'A target occurring in a "del" statement is also considered bound '
7816 'for\n'
7817 'this purpose (though the actual semantics are to unbind the '
7818 'name).\n'
7819 '\n'
7820 'Each assignment or import statement occurs within a block defined '
7821 'by a\n'
7822 'class or function definition or at the module level (the '
7823 'top-level\n'
7824 'code block).\n'
7825 '\n'
7826 'If a name is bound in a block, it is a local variable of that '
7827 'block,\n'
7828 'unless declared as "nonlocal" or "global". If a name is bound at '
7829 'the\n'
7830 'module level, it is a global variable. (The variables of the '
7831 'module\n'
7832 'code block are local and global.) If a variable is used in a '
7833 'code\n'
7834 'block but not defined there, it is a *free variable*.\n'
7835 '\n'
7836 'Each occurrence of a name in the program text refers to the '
7837 '*binding*\n'
7838 'of that name established by the following name resolution rules.\n'
7839 '\n'
7840 '\n'
7841 'Resolution of names\n'
7842 '===================\n'
7843 '\n'
7844 'A *scope* defines the visibility of a name within a block. If a '
7845 'local\n'
7846 'variable is defined in a block, its scope includes that block. If '
7847 'the\n'
7848 'definition occurs in a function block, the scope extends to any '
7849 'blocks\n'
7850 'contained within the defining one, unless a contained block '
7851 'introduces\n'
7852 'a different binding for the name.\n'
7853 '\n'
7854 'When a name is used in a code block, it is resolved using the '
7855 'nearest\n'
7856 'enclosing scope. The set of all such scopes visible to a code '
7857 'block\n'
7858 'is called the block’s *environment*.\n'
7859 '\n'
7860 'When a name is not found at all, a "NameError" exception is '
7861 'raised. If\n'
7862 'the current scope is a function scope, and the name refers to a '
7863 'local\n'
7864 'variable that has not yet been bound to a value at the point where '
7865 'the\n'
7866 'name is used, an "UnboundLocalError" exception is raised.\n'
7867 '"UnboundLocalError" is a subclass of "NameError".\n'
7868 '\n'
7869 'If a name binding operation occurs anywhere within a code block, '
7870 'all\n'
7871 'uses of the name within the block are treated as references to '
7872 'the\n'
7873 'current block. This can lead to errors when a name is used within '
7874 'a\n'
7875 'block before it is bound. This rule is subtle. Python lacks\n'
7876 'declarations and allows name binding operations to occur anywhere\n'
7877 'within a code block. The local variables of a code block can be\n'
7878 'determined by scanning the entire text of the block for name '
7879 'binding\n'
7880 'operations. See the FAQ entry on UnboundLocalError for examples.\n'
7881 '\n'
7882 'If the "global" statement occurs within a block, all uses of the '
7883 'names\n'
7884 'specified in the statement refer to the bindings of those names in '
7885 'the\n'
7886 'top-level namespace. Names are resolved in the top-level '
7887 'namespace by\n'
7888 'searching the global namespace, i.e. the namespace of the module\n'
7889 'containing the code block, and the builtins namespace, the '
7890 'namespace\n'
7891 'of the module "builtins". The global namespace is searched '
7892 'first. If\n'
7893 'the names are not found there, the builtins namespace is '
7894 'searched.\n'
7895 'The "global" statement must precede all uses of the listed names.\n'
7896 '\n'
7897 'The "global" statement has the same scope as a name binding '
7898 'operation\n'
7899 'in the same block. If the nearest enclosing scope for a free '
7900 'variable\n'
7901 'contains a global statement, the free variable is treated as a '
7902 'global.\n'
7903 '\n'
7904 'The "nonlocal" statement causes corresponding names to refer to\n'
7905 'previously bound variables in the nearest enclosing function '
7906 'scope.\n'
7907 '"SyntaxError" is raised at compile time if the given name does '
7908 'not\n'
7909 'exist in any enclosing function scope.\n'
7910 '\n'
7911 'The namespace for a module is automatically created the first time '
7912 'a\n'
7913 'module is imported. The main module for a script is always '
7914 'called\n'
7915 '"__main__".\n'
7916 '\n'
7917 'Class definition blocks and arguments to "exec()" and "eval()" '
7918 'are\n'
7919 'special in the context of name resolution. A class definition is '
7920 'an\n'
7921 'executable statement that may use and define names. These '
7922 'references\n'
7923 'follow the normal rules for name resolution with an exception '
7924 'that\n'
7925 'unbound local variables are looked up in the global namespace. '
7926 'The\n'
7927 'namespace of the class definition becomes the attribute dictionary '
7928 'of\n'
7929 'the class. The scope of names defined in a class block is limited '
7930 'to\n'
7931 'the class block; it does not extend to the code blocks of methods '
7932 '–\n'
7933 'this includes comprehensions and generator expressions since they '
7934 'are\n'
7935 'implemented using a function scope. This means that the '
7936 'following\n'
7937 'will fail:\n'
7938 '\n'
7939 ' class A:\n'
7940 ' a = 42\n'
7941 ' b = list(a + i for i in range(10))\n'
7942 '\n'
7943 '\n'
7944 'Builtins and restricted execution\n'
7945 '=================================\n'
7946 '\n'
7947 '**CPython implementation detail:** Users should not touch\n'
7948 '"__builtins__"; it is strictly an implementation detail. Users\n'
7949 'wanting to override values in the builtins namespace should '
7950 '"import"\n'
7951 'the "builtins" module and modify its attributes appropriately.\n'
7952 '\n'
7953 'The builtins namespace associated with the execution of a code '
7954 'block\n'
7955 'is actually found by looking up the name "__builtins__" in its '
7956 'global\n'
7957 'namespace; this should be a dictionary or a module (in the latter '
7958 'case\n'
7959 'the module’s dictionary is used). By default, when in the '
7960 '"__main__"\n'
7961 'module, "__builtins__" is the built-in module "builtins"; when in '
7962 'any\n'
7963 'other module, "__builtins__" is an alias for the dictionary of '
7964 'the\n'
7965 '"builtins" module itself.\n'
7966 '\n'
7967 '\n'
7968 'Interaction with dynamic features\n'
7969 '=================================\n'
7970 '\n'
7971 'Name resolution of free variables occurs at runtime, not at '
7972 'compile\n'
7973 'time. This means that the following code will print 42:\n'
7974 '\n'
7975 ' i = 10\n'
7976 ' def f():\n'
7977 ' print(i)\n'
7978 ' i = 42\n'
7979 ' f()\n'
7980 '\n'
7981 'The "eval()" and "exec()" functions do not have access to the '
7982 'full\n'
7983 'environment for resolving names. Names may be resolved in the '
7984 'local\n'
7985 'and global namespaces of the caller. Free variables are not '
7986 'resolved\n'
7987 'in the nearest enclosing namespace, but in the global namespace. '
7988 '[1]\n'
7989 'The "exec()" and "eval()" functions have optional arguments to\n'
7990 'override the global and local namespace. If only one namespace '
7991 'is\n'
7992 'specified, it is used for both.\n',

7993 'nonlocal': 'The "nonlocal" statement\n'
7994 '************************\n'
7995 '\n'

8012 'enclosing scope (the scope in which a new binding should be '
8013 'created\n'
8014 'cannot be determined unambiguously).\n'
8015 '\n'

8017 'pre-\n'
8018 'existing bindings in the local scope.\n'
8019 '\n'

8241 'objects': 'Objects, values and types\n'
8242 '*************************\n'
8243 '\n'
8244 '*Objects* are Python’s abstraction for data. All data in a '
8245 'Python\n'
8246 'program is represented by objects or by relations between '
8247 'objects. (In\n'
8248 'a sense, and in conformance to Von Neumann’s model of a “stored\n'
8249 'program computer”, code is also represented by objects.)\n'
8250 '\n'
8251 'Every object has an identity, a type and a value. An object’s\n'
8252 '*identity* never changes once it has been created; you may think '
8253 'of it\n'
8254 'as the object’s address in memory. The "is" operator compares '
8255 'the\n'
8256 'identity of two objects; the "id()" function returns an integer\n'
8257 'representing its identity.\n'
8258 '\n'
8259 '**CPython implementation detail:** For CPython, "id(x)" is the '
8260 'memory\n'
8261 'address where "x" is stored.\n'
8262 '\n'
8263 'An object’s type determines the operations that the object '
8264 'supports\n'
8265 '(e.g., “does it have a length?”) and also defines the possible '
8266 'values\n'
8267 'for objects of that type. The "type()" function returns an '
8268 'object’s\n'
8269 'type (which is an object itself). Like its identity, an '
8270 'object’s\n'
8271 '*type* is also unchangeable. [1]\n'
8272 '\n'
8273 'The *value* of some objects can change. Objects whose value can\n'
8274 'change are said to be *mutable*; objects whose value is '
8275 'unchangeable\n'
8276 'once they are created are called *immutable*. (The value of an\n'
8277 'immutable container object that contains a reference to a '
8278 'mutable\n'
8279 'object can change when the latter’s value is changed; however '
8280 'the\n'
8281 'container is still considered immutable, because the collection '
8282 'of\n'
8283 'objects it contains cannot be changed. So, immutability is not\n'
8284 'strictly the same as having an unchangeable value, it is more '
8285 'subtle.)\n'
8286 'An object’s mutability is determined by its type; for instance,\n'
8287 'numbers, strings and tuples are immutable, while dictionaries '
8288 'and\n'
8289 'lists are mutable.\n'
8290 '\n'
8291 'Objects are never explicitly destroyed; however, when they '
8292 'become\n'
8293 'unreachable they may be garbage-collected. An implementation is\n'
8294 'allowed to postpone garbage collection or omit it altogether — it '
8295 'is a\n'
8296 'matter of implementation quality how garbage collection is\n'
8297 'implemented, as long as no objects are collected that are still\n'
8298 'reachable.\n'
8299 '\n'
8300 '**CPython implementation detail:** CPython currently uses a '
8301 'reference-\n'
8302 'counting scheme with (optional) delayed detection of cyclically '
8303 'linked\n'
8304 'garbage, which collects most objects as soon as they become\n'
8305 'unreachable, but is not guaranteed to collect garbage containing\n'
8306 'circular references. See the documentation of the "gc" module '
8307 'for\n'
8308 'information on controlling the collection of cyclic garbage. '
8309 'Other\n'
8310 'implementations act differently and CPython may change. Do not '
8311 'depend\n'
8312 'on immediate finalization of objects when they become unreachable '
8313 '(so\n'
8314 'you should always close files explicitly).\n'
8315 '\n'
8316 'Note that the use of the implementation’s tracing or debugging\n'
8317 'facilities may keep objects alive that would normally be '
8318 'collectable.\n'
8319 'Also note that catching an exception with a "try"…"except" '
8320 'statement\n'
8321 'may keep objects alive.\n'
8322 '\n'
8323 'Some objects contain references to “external” resources such as '
8324 'open\n'
8325 'files or windows. It is understood that these resources are '
8326 'freed\n'
8327 'when the object is garbage-collected, but since garbage '
8328 'collection is\n'
8329 'not guaranteed to happen, such objects also provide an explicit '
8330 'way to\n'
8331 'release the external resource, usually a "close()" method. '
8332 'Programs\n'
8333 'are strongly recommended to explicitly close such objects. The\n'
8334 '"try"…"finally" statement and the "with" statement provide '
8335 'convenient\n'
8336 'ways to do this.\n'
8337 '\n'
8338 'Some objects contain references to other objects; these are '
8339 'called\n'
8340 '*containers*. Examples of containers are tuples, lists and\n'
8341 'dictionaries. The references are part of a container’s value. '
8342 'In\n'
8343 'most cases, when we talk about the value of a container, we imply '
8344 'the\n'
8345 'values, not the identities of the contained objects; however, '
8346 'when we\n'
8347 'talk about the mutability of a container, only the identities of '
8348 'the\n'
8349 'immediately contained objects are implied. So, if an immutable\n'
8350 'container (like a tuple) contains a reference to a mutable '
8351 'object, its\n'
8352 'value changes if that mutable object is changed.\n'
8353 '\n'
8354 'Types affect almost all aspects of object behavior. Even the\n'
8355 'importance of object identity is affected in some sense: for '
8356 'immutable\n'
8357 'types, operations that compute new values may actually return a\n'
8358 'reference to any existing object with the same type and value, '
8359 'while\n'
8360 'for mutable objects this is not allowed. E.g., after "a = 1; b = '
8361 '1",\n'
8362 '"a" and "b" may or may not refer to the same object with the '
8363 'value\n'
8364 'one, depending on the implementation, but after "c = []; d = []", '
8365 '"c"\n'
8366 'and "d" are guaranteed to refer to two different, unique, newly\n'
8367 'created empty lists. (Note that "c = d = []" assigns the same '
8368 'object\n'
8369 'to both "c" and "d".)\n',

8465 '[1] While "abs(x%y) < abs(y)" is true mathematically, '
8466 'for floats it\n'
8467 ' may not be true numerically due to roundoff. For '
8468 'example, and\n'
8469 ' assuming a platform on which a Python float is an '
8470 'IEEE 754 double-\n'
8471 ' precision number, in order that "-1e-100 % 1e100" '
8472 'have the same\n'
8473 ' sign as "1e100", the computed result is "-1e-100 + '
8474 '1e100", which\n'
8475 ' is numerically exactly equal to "1e100". The '
8476 'function\n'
8477 ' "math.fmod()" returns a result whose sign matches '
8478 'the sign of the\n'
8479 ' first argument instead, and so returns "-1e-100" in '
8480 'this case.\n'
8481 ' Which approach is more appropriate depends on the '
8482 'application.\n'
8483 '\n'
8484 '[2] If x is very close to an exact integer multiple of '
8485 'y, it’s\n'
8486 ' possible for "x//y" to be one larger than '
8487 '"(x-x%y)//y" due to\n'
8488 ' rounding. In such cases, Python returns the latter '
8489 'result, in\n'
8490 ' order to preserve that "divmod(x,y)[0] * y + x % y" '
8491 'be very close\n'
8492 ' to "x".\n'
8493 '\n'
8494 '[3] The Unicode standard distinguishes between *code '
8495 'points* (e.g.\n'
8496 ' U+0041) and *abstract characters* (e.g. “LATIN '
8497 'CAPITAL LETTER A”).\n'
8498 ' While most abstract characters in Unicode are only '
8499 'represented\n'
8500 ' using one code point, there is a number of abstract '
8501 'characters\n'
8502 ' that can in addition be represented using a sequence '
8503 'of more than\n'
8504 ' one code point. For example, the abstract character '
8505 '“LATIN\n'
8506 ' CAPITAL LETTER C WITH CEDILLA” can be represented as '
8507 'a single\n'
8508 ' *precomposed character* at code position U+00C7, or '
8509 'as a sequence\n'
8510 ' of a *base character* at code position U+0043 (LATIN '
8511 'CAPITAL\n'
8512 ' LETTER C), followed by a *combining character* at '
8513 'code position\n'
8514 ' U+0327 (COMBINING CEDILLA).\n'
8515 '\n'
8516 ' The comparison operators on strings compare at the '
8517 'level of\n'
8518 ' Unicode code points. This may be counter-intuitive '
8519 'to humans. For\n'
8520 ' example, ""\\u00C7" == "\\u0043\\u0327"" is "False", '
8521 'even though both\n'
8522 ' strings represent the same abstract character “LATIN '
8523 'CAPITAL\n'
8524 ' LETTER C WITH CEDILLA”.\n'
8525 '\n'
8526 ' To compare strings at the level of abstract '
8527 'characters (that is,\n'
8528 ' in a way intuitive to humans), use '
8529 '"unicodedata.normalize()".\n'
8530 '\n'
8531 '[4] Due to automatic garbage-collection, free lists, and '
8532 'the dynamic\n'
8533 ' nature of descriptors, you may notice seemingly '
8534 'unusual behaviour\n'
8535 ' in certain uses of the "is" operator, like those '
8536 'involving\n'
8537 ' comparisons between instance methods, or constants. '
8538 'Check their\n'
8539 ' documentation for more info.\n'
8540 '\n'

8542 'arithmetic or\n'
8543 ' bitwise unary operator on its right, that is, '
8544 '"2**-1" is "0.5".\n'

8563 'power': 'The power operator\n'
8564 '******************\n'
8565 '\n'
8566 'The power operator binds more tightly than unary operators on its\n'
8567 'left; it binds less tightly than unary operators on its right. '
8568 'The\n'
8569 'syntax is:\n'
8570 '\n'
8571 ' power ::= (await_expr | primary) ["**" u_expr]\n'
8572 '\n'
8573 'Thus, in an unparenthesized sequence of power and unary operators, '
8574 'the\n'
8575 'operators are evaluated from right to left (this does not '
8576 'constrain\n'
8577 'the evaluation order for the operands): "-1**2" results in "-1".\n'
8578 '\n'
8579 'The power operator has the same semantics as the built-in "pow()"\n'
8580 'function, when called with two arguments: it yields its left '
8581 'argument\n'
8582 'raised to the power of its right argument. The numeric arguments '
8583 'are\n'
8584 'first converted to a common type, and the result is of that type.\n'
8585 '\n'
8586 'For int operands, the result has the same type as the operands '
8587 'unless\n'
8588 'the second argument is negative; in that case, all arguments are\n'
8589 'converted to float and a float result is delivered. For example,\n'
8590 '"10**2" returns "100", but "10**-2" returns "0.01".\n'
8591 '\n'
8592 'Raising "0.0" to a negative power results in a '
8593 '"ZeroDivisionError".\n'
8594 'Raising a negative number to a fractional power results in a '
8595 '"complex"\n'
8596 'number. (In earlier versions it raised a "ValueError".)\n'
8597 '\n'
8598 'This operation can be customized using the special "__pow__()" '
8599 'method.\n',

8601 '*********************\n'
8602 '\n'
8603 ' raise_stmt ::= "raise" [expression ["from" expression]]\n'
8604 '\n'
8605 'If no expressions are present, "raise" re-raises the exception that '
8606 'is\n'
8607 'currently being handled, which is also known as the *active\n'
8608 'exception*. If there isn’t currently an active exception, a\n'

8611 '\n'

8614 '"BaseException". If it is a class, the exception instance will be\n'
8615 'obtained when needed by instantiating the class with no arguments.\n'

8618 '*value* is the instance itself.\n'

8621 'exception\n'

8623 'can\n'

8627 'exception\n'

8631 '\n'

8633 'second\n'
8634 '*expression* must be another exception class or instance. If the\n'
8635 'second expression is an exception instance, it will be attached to '
8636 'the\n'

8638 'If\n'

8757 'sequence-types': 'Emulating container types\n'
8758 '*************************\n'
8759 '\n'
8760 'The following methods can be defined to implement '
8761 'container objects.\n'
8762 'Containers usually are *sequences* (such as "lists" or '
8763 '"tuples") or\n'
8764 '*mappings* (like "dictionaries"), but can represent other '
8765 'containers\n'
8766 'as well. The first set of methods is used either to '
8767 'emulate a\n'
8768 'sequence or to emulate a mapping; the difference is that '
8769 'for a\n'
8770 'sequence, the allowable keys should be the integers *k* '
8771 'for which "0\n'
8772 '<= k < N" where *N* is the length of the sequence, or '
8773 '"slice" objects,\n'
8774 'which define a range of items. It is also recommended '
8775 'that mappings\n'
8776 'provide the methods "keys()", "values()", "items()", '
8777 '"get()",\n'
8778 '"clear()", "setdefault()", "pop()", "popitem()", "copy()", '
8779 'and\n'
8780 '"update()" behaving similar to those for Python’s '
8781 'standard\n'
8782 '"dictionary" objects. The "collections.abc" module '
8783 'provides a\n'
8784 '"MutableMapping" *abstract base class* to help create '
8785 'those methods\n'
8786 'from a base set of "__getitem__()", "__setitem__()", '
8787 '"__delitem__()",\n'
8788 'and "keys()". Mutable sequences should provide methods '
8789 '"append()",\n'
8790 '"count()", "index()", "extend()", "insert()", "pop()", '
8791 '"remove()",\n'
8792 '"reverse()" and "sort()", like Python standard "list" '
8793 'objects.\n'
8794 'Finally, sequence types should implement addition '
8795 '(meaning\n'
8796 'concatenation) and multiplication (meaning repetition) by '
8797 'defining the\n'
8798 'methods "__add__()", "__radd__()", "__iadd__()", '
8799 '"__mul__()",\n'
8800 '"__rmul__()" and "__imul__()" described below; they should '
8801 'not define\n'
8802 'other numerical operators. It is recommended that both '
8803 'mappings and\n'
8804 'sequences implement the "__contains__()" method to allow '
8805 'efficient use\n'
8806 'of the "in" operator; for mappings, "in" should search the '
8807 'mapping’s\n'
8808 'keys; for sequences, it should search through the values. '
8809 'It is\n'
8810 'further recommended that both mappings and sequences '
8811 'implement the\n'
8812 '"__iter__()" method to allow efficient iteration through '
8813 'the\n'
8814 'container; for mappings, "__iter__()" should iterate '
8815 'through the\n'
8816 'object’s keys; for sequences, it should iterate through '
8817 'the values.\n'
8818 '\n'
8819 'object.__len__(self)\n'
8820 '\n'
8821 ' Called to implement the built-in function "len()". '
8822 'Should return\n'
8823 ' the length of the object, an integer ">=" 0. Also, an '
8824 'object that\n'
8825 ' doesn’t define a "__bool__()" method and whose '
8826 '"__len__()" method\n'
8827 ' returns zero is considered to be false in a Boolean '
8828 'context.\n'
8829 '\n'
8830 ' **CPython implementation detail:** In CPython, the '
8831 'length is\n'
8832 ' required to be at most "sys.maxsize". If the length is '
8833 'larger than\n'
8834 ' "sys.maxsize" some features (such as "len()") may '
8835 'raise\n'
8836 ' "OverflowError". To prevent raising "OverflowError" by '
8837 'truth value\n'
8838 ' testing, an object must define a "__bool__()" method.\n'
8839 '\n'
8840 'object.__length_hint__(self)\n'
8841 '\n'
8842 ' Called to implement "operator.length_hint()". Should '
8843 'return an\n'
8844 ' estimated length for the object (which may be greater '
8845 'or less than\n'
8846 ' the actual length). The length must be an integer ">=" '
8847 '0. The\n'
8848 ' return value may also be "NotImplemented", which is '

8855 '\n'

8875 ' Called to implement evaluation of "self[key]". For '

8877 ' types, the accepted keys should be integers. '

9021 'slicings': 'Slicings\n'
9022 '********\n'
9023 '\n'
9024 'A slicing selects a range of items in a sequence object (e.g., '
9025 'a\n'
9026 'string, tuple or list). Slicings may be used as expressions or '
9027 'as\n'
9028 'targets in assignment or "del" statements. The syntax for a '
9029 'slicing:\n'
9030 '\n'
9031 ' slicing ::= primary "[" slice_list "]"\n'
9032 ' slice_list ::= slice_item ("," slice_item)* [","]\n'
9033 ' slice_item ::= expression | proper_slice\n'
9034 ' proper_slice ::= [lower_bound] ":" [upper_bound] [ ":" '
9035 '[stride] ]\n'
9036 ' lower_bound ::= expression\n'
9037 ' upper_bound ::= expression\n'
9038 ' stride ::= expression\n'
9039 '\n'
9040 'There is ambiguity in the formal syntax here: anything that '
9041 'looks like\n'
9042 'an expression list also looks like a slice list, so any '
9043 'subscription\n'
9044 'can be interpreted as a slicing. Rather than further '
9045 'complicating the\n'
9046 'syntax, this is disambiguated by defining that in this case the\n'
9047 'interpretation as a subscription takes priority over the\n'
9048 'interpretation as a slicing (this is the case if the slice list\n'
9049 'contains no proper slice).\n'
9050 '\n'
9051 'The semantics for a slicing are as follows. The primary is '
9052 'indexed\n'
9053 '(using the same "__getitem__()" method as normal subscription) '
9054 'with a\n'
9055 'key that is constructed from the slice list, as follows. If the '
9056 'slice\n'
9057 'list contains at least one comma, the key is a tuple containing '
9058 'the\n'
9059 'conversion of the slice items; otherwise, the conversion of the '
9060 'lone\n'
9061 'slice item is the key. The conversion of a slice item that is '
9062 'an\n'
9063 'expression is that expression. The conversion of a proper slice '
9064 'is a\n'
9065 'slice object (see section The standard type hierarchy) whose '
9066 '"start",\n'
9067 '"stop" and "step" attributes are the values of the expressions '
9068 'given\n'
9069 'as lower bound, upper bound and stride, respectively, '
9070 'substituting\n'
9071 '"None" for missing expressions.\n',
