9134 'specialnames': 'Special method names\n'
9135 '********************\n'
9136 '\n'
9137 'A class can implement certain operations that are invoked by '
9138 'special\n'
9139 'syntax (such as arithmetic operations or subscripting and '
9140 'slicing) by\n'
9141 'defining methods with special names. This is Python’s '
9142 'approach to\n'
9143 '*operator overloading*, allowing classes to define their own '
9144 'behavior\n'
9145 'with respect to language operators. For instance, if a '
9146 'class defines\n'
9147 'a method named "__getitem__()", and "x" is an instance of '
9148 'this class,\n'
9149 'then "x[i]" is roughly equivalent to "type(x).__getitem__(x, '
9150 'i)".\n'
9151 'Except where mentioned, attempts to execute an operation '
9152 'raise an\n'
9153 'exception when no appropriate method is defined (typically\n'
9154 '"AttributeError" or "TypeError").\n'
9155 '\n'
9156 'Setting a special method to "None" indicates that the '
9157 'corresponding\n'
9158 'operation is not available. For example, if a class sets '
9159 '"__iter__()"\n'
9160 'to "None", the class is not iterable, so calling "iter()" on '
9161 'its\n'
9162 'instances will raise a "TypeError" (without falling back to\n'
9163 '"__getitem__()"). [2]\n'
9164 '\n'
9165 'When implementing a class that emulates any built-in type, '
9166 'it is\n'
9167 'important that the emulation only be implemented to the '
9168 'degree that it\n'
9169 'makes sense for the object being modelled. For example, '
9170 'some\n'
9171 'sequences may work well with retrieval of individual '
9172 'elements, but\n'
9173 'extracting a slice may not make sense. (One example of this '
9174 'is the\n'
9175 '"NodeList" interface in the W3C’s Document Object Model.)\n'
9176 '\n'
9177 '\n'
9178 'Basic customization\n'
9179 '===================\n'
9180 '\n'
9181 'object.__new__(cls[, ...])\n'
9182 '\n'
9183 ' Called to create a new instance of class *cls*. '
9184 '"__new__()" is a\n'
9185 ' static method (special-cased so you need not declare it '
9186 'as such)\n'
9187 ' that takes the class of which an instance was requested '
9188 'as its\n'
9189 ' first argument. The remaining arguments are those passed '
9190 'to the\n'
9191 ' object constructor expression (the call to the class). '
9192 'The return\n'
9193 ' value of "__new__()" should be the new object instance '
9194 '(usually an\n'
9195 ' instance of *cls*).\n'
9196 '\n'
9197 ' Typical implementations create a new instance of the '
9198 'class by\n'
9199 ' invoking the superclass’s "__new__()" method using\n'
9200 ' "super().__new__(cls[, ...])" with appropriate arguments '
9201 'and then\n'
9202 ' modifying the newly created instance as necessary before '
9203 'returning\n'
9204 ' it.\n'
9205 '\n'
9206 ' If "__new__()" is invoked during object construction and '
9207 'it returns\n'
9208 ' an instance of *cls*, then the new instance’s '
9209 '"__init__()" method\n'
9210 ' will be invoked like "__init__(self[, ...])", where '
9211 '*self* is the\n'
9212 ' new instance and the remaining arguments are the same as '
9213 'were\n'
9214 ' passed to the object constructor.\n'
9215 '\n'
9216 ' If "__new__()" does not return an instance of *cls*, then '
9217 'the new\n'
9218 ' instance’s "__init__()" method will not be invoked.\n'
9219 '\n'
9220 ' "__new__()" is intended mainly to allow subclasses of '
9221 'immutable\n'
9222 ' types (like int, str, or tuple) to customize instance '
9223 'creation. It\n'
9224 ' is also commonly overridden in custom metaclasses in '
9225 'order to\n'
9226 ' customize class creation.\n'
9227 '\n'
9228 'object.__init__(self[, ...])\n'
9229 '\n'
9230 ' Called after the instance has been created (by '
9231 '"__new__()"), but\n'
9232 ' before it is returned to the caller. The arguments are '
9233 'those\n'
9234 ' passed to the class constructor expression. If a base '
9235 'class has an\n'
9236 ' "__init__()" method, the derived class’s "__init__()" '
9237 'method, if\n'
9238 ' any, must explicitly call it to ensure proper '
9239 'initialization of the\n'
9240 ' base class part of the instance; for example:\n'
9241 ' "super().__init__([args...])".\n'
9242 '\n'
9243 ' Because "__new__()" and "__init__()" work together in '
9244 'constructing\n'
9245 ' objects ("__new__()" to create it, and "__init__()" to '
9246 'customize\n'
9247 ' it), no non-"None" value may be returned by "__init__()"; '
9248 'doing so\n'
9249 ' will cause a "TypeError" to be raised at runtime.\n'
9250 '\n'
9251 'object.__del__(self)\n'
9252 '\n'
9253 ' Called when the instance is about to be destroyed. This '
9254 'is also\n'
9255 ' called a finalizer or (improperly) a destructor. If a '
9256 'base class\n'
9257 ' has a "__del__()" method, the derived class’s "__del__()" '
9258 'method,\n'
9259 ' if any, must explicitly call it to ensure proper deletion '
9260 'of the\n'
9261 ' base class part of the instance.\n'
9262 '\n'
9263 ' It is possible (though not recommended!) for the '
9264 '"__del__()" method\n'
9265 ' to postpone destruction of the instance by creating a new '
9266 'reference\n'
9267 ' to it. This is called object *resurrection*. It is\n'
9268 ' implementation-dependent whether "__del__()" is called a '
9269 'second\n'
9270 ' time when a resurrected object is about to be destroyed; '
9271 'the\n'
9272 ' current *CPython* implementation only calls it once.\n'
9273 '\n'
9274 ' It is not guaranteed that "__del__()" methods are called '
9275 'for\n'
9276 ' objects that still exist when the interpreter exits.\n'
9277 '\n'
9278 ' Note:\n'
9279 '\n'
9280 ' "del x" doesn’t directly call "x.__del__()" — the '
9281 'former\n'
9282 ' decrements the reference count for "x" by one, and the '
9283 'latter is\n'
9284 ' only called when "x"’s reference count reaches zero.\n'
9285 '\n'
9286 ' **CPython implementation detail:** It is possible for a '
9287 'reference\n'
9288 ' cycle to prevent the reference count of an object from '
9289 'going to\n'
9290 ' zero. In this case, the cycle will be later detected and '
9291 'deleted\n'
9292 ' by the *cyclic garbage collector*. A common cause of '
9293 'reference\n'
9294 ' cycles is when an exception has been caught in a local '
9295 'variable.\n'
9296 ' The frame’s locals then reference the exception, which '
9297 'references\n'
9298 ' its own traceback, which references the locals of all '
9299 'frames caught\n'
9300 ' in the traceback.\n'
9301 '\n'
9302 ' See also: Documentation for the "gc" module.\n'
9303 '\n'
9304 ' Warning:\n'
9305 '\n'
9306 ' Due to the precarious circumstances under which '
9307 '"__del__()"\n'
9308 ' methods are invoked, exceptions that occur during their '
9309 'execution\n'
9310 ' are ignored, and a warning is printed to "sys.stderr" '
9311 'instead.\n'
9312 ' In particular:\n'
9313 '\n'
9314 ' * "__del__()" can be invoked when arbitrary code is '
9315 'being\n'
9316 ' executed, including from any arbitrary thread. If '
9317 '"__del__()"\n'
9318 ' needs to take a lock or invoke any other blocking '
9319 'resource, it\n'
9320 ' may deadlock as the resource may already be taken by '
9321 'the code\n'
9322 ' that gets interrupted to execute "__del__()".\n'
9323 '\n'
9324 ' * "__del__()" can be executed during interpreter '
9325 'shutdown. As a\n'
9326 ' consequence, the global variables it needs to access '
9327 '(including\n'
9328 ' other modules) may already have been deleted or set '
9329 'to "None".\n'
9330 ' Python guarantees that globals whose name begins with '
9331 'a single\n'
9332 ' underscore are deleted from their module before other '
9333 'globals\n'
9334 ' are deleted; if no other references to such globals '
9335 'exist, this\n'
9336 ' may help in assuring that imported modules are still '
9337 'available\n'
9338 ' at the time when the "__del__()" method is called.\n'
9339 '\n'
9340 'object.__repr__(self)\n'
9341 '\n'
9342 ' Called by the "repr()" built-in function to compute the '
9343 '“official”\n'
9344 ' string representation of an object. If at all possible, '
9345 'this\n'
9346 ' should look like a valid Python expression that could be '

9392 '\n'

9425 '\n'
9426 'object.__lt__(self, other)\n'
9427 'object.__le__(self, other)\n'
9428 'object.__eq__(self, other)\n'
9429 'object.__ne__(self, other)\n'
9430 'object.__gt__(self, other)\n'
9431 'object.__ge__(self, other)\n'
9432 '\n'
9433 ' These are the so-called “rich comparison” methods. The\n'
9434 ' correspondence between operator symbols and method names '
9435 'is as\n'
9436 ' follows: "x<y" calls "x.__lt__(y)", "x<=y" calls '
9437 '"x.__le__(y)",\n'
9438 ' "x==y" calls "x.__eq__(y)", "x!=y" calls "x.__ne__(y)", '
9439 '"x>y" calls\n'
9440 ' "x.__gt__(y)", and "x>=y" calls "x.__ge__(y)".\n'
9441 '\n'
9442 ' A rich comparison method may return the singleton '
9443 '"NotImplemented"\n'
9444 ' if it does not implement the operation for a given pair '
9445 'of\n'
9446 ' arguments. By convention, "False" and "True" are returned '
9447 'for a\n'
9448 ' successful comparison. However, these methods can return '
9449 'any value,\n'
9450 ' so if the comparison operator is used in a Boolean '
9451 'context (e.g.,\n'
9452 ' in the condition of an "if" statement), Python will call '
9453 '"bool()"\n'
9454 ' on the value to determine if the result is true or '
9455 'false.\n'
9456 '\n'
9457 ' By default, "object" implements "__eq__()" by using "is", '
9458 'returning\n'
9459 ' "NotImplemented" in the case of a false comparison: "True '
9460 'if x is y\n'
9461 ' else NotImplemented". For "__ne__()", by default it '
9462 'delegates to\n'
9463 ' "__eq__()" and inverts the result unless it is '
9464 '"NotImplemented".\n'
9465 ' There are no other implied relationships among the '
9466 'comparison\n'
9467 ' operators or default implementations; for example, the '
9468 'truth of\n'
9469 ' "(x<y or x==y)" does not imply "x<=y". To automatically '
9470 'generate\n'
9471 ' ordering operations from a single root operation, see\n'
9472 ' "functools.total_ordering()".\n'
9473 '\n'
9474 ' See the paragraph on "__hash__()" for some important '
9475 'notes on\n'
9476 ' creating *hashable* objects which support custom '
9477 'comparison\n'
9478 ' operations and are usable as dictionary keys.\n'
9479 '\n'
9480 ' There are no swapped-argument versions of these methods '
9481 '(to be used\n'
9482 ' when the left argument does not support the operation but '
9483 'the right\n'
9484 ' argument does); rather, "__lt__()" and "__gt__()" are '
9485 'each other’s\n'
9486 ' reflection, "__le__()" and "__ge__()" are each other’s '
9487 'reflection,\n'
9488 ' and "__eq__()" and "__ne__()" are their own reflection. '
9489 'If the\n'
9490 ' operands are of different types, and the right operand’s '
9491 'type is a\n'
9492 ' direct or indirect subclass of the left operand’s type, '
9493 'the\n'
9494 ' reflected method of the right operand has priority, '
9495 'otherwise the\n'
9496 ' left operand’s method has priority. Virtual subclassing '
9497 'is not\n'
9498 ' considered.\n'
9499 '\n'
9500 ' When no appropriate method returns any value other than\n'
9501 ' "NotImplemented", the "==" and "!=" operators will fall '
9502 'back to\n'
9503 ' "is" and "is not", respectively.\n'
9504 '\n'
9505 'object.__hash__(self)\n'
9506 '\n'
9507 ' Called by built-in function "hash()" and for operations '
9508 'on members\n'
9509 ' of hashed collections including "set", "frozenset", and '
9510 '"dict".\n'
9511 ' The "__hash__()" method should return an integer. The '
9512 'only required\n'
9513 ' property is that objects which compare equal have the '
9514 'same hash\n'
9515 ' value; it is advised to mix together the hash values of '
9516 'the\n'
9517 ' components of the object that also play a part in '
9518 'comparison of\n'
9519 ' objects by packing them into a tuple and hashing the '
9520 'tuple.\n'
9521 ' Example:\n'
9522 '\n'
9523 ' def __hash__(self):\n'
9524 ' return hash((self.name, self.nick, self.color))\n'
9525 '\n'
9526 ' Note:\n'
9527 '\n'
9528 ' "hash()" truncates the value returned from an object’s '
9529 'custom\n'
9530 ' "__hash__()" method to the size of a "Py_ssize_t". '
9531 'This is\n'
9532 ' typically 8 bytes on 64-bit builds and 4 bytes on '
9533 '32-bit builds.\n'
9534 ' If an object’s "__hash__()" must interoperate on '
9535 'builds of\n'
9536 ' different bit sizes, be sure to check the width on all '
9537 'supported\n'
9538 ' builds. An easy way to do this is with "python -c '
9539 '"import sys;\n'
9540 ' print(sys.hash_info.width)"".\n'
9541 '\n'
9542 ' If a class does not define an "__eq__()" method it should '
9543 'not\n'
9544 ' define a "__hash__()" operation either; if it defines '
9545 '"__eq__()"\n'
9546 ' but not "__hash__()", its instances will not be usable as '
9547 'items in\n'
9548 ' hashable collections. If a class defines mutable objects '
9549 'and\n'
9550 ' implements an "__eq__()" method, it should not implement\n'
9551 ' "__hash__()", since the implementation of *hashable* '
9552 'collections\n'
9553 ' requires that a key’s hash value is immutable (if the '
9554 'object’s hash\n'
9555 ' value changes, it will be in the wrong hash bucket).\n'
9556 '\n'
9557 ' User-defined classes have "__eq__()" and "__hash__()" '
9558 'methods by\n'
9559 ' default; with them, all objects compare unequal (except '
9560 'with\n'
9561 ' themselves) and "x.__hash__()" returns an appropriate '
9562 'value such\n'
9563 ' that "x == y" implies both that "x is y" and "hash(x) == '
9564 'hash(y)".\n'
9565 '\n'
9566 ' A class that overrides "__eq__()" and does not define '
9567 '"__hash__()"\n'
9568 ' will have its "__hash__()" implicitly set to "None". '
9569 'When the\n'
9570 ' "__hash__()" method of a class is "None", instances of '
9571 'the class\n'
9572 ' will raise an appropriate "TypeError" when a program '
9573 'attempts to\n'
9574 ' retrieve their hash value, and will also be correctly '
9575 'identified as\n'
9576 ' unhashable when checking "isinstance(obj,\n'
9577 ' collections.abc.Hashable)".\n'
9578 '\n'
9579 ' If a class that overrides "__eq__()" needs to retain the\n'
9580 ' implementation of "__hash__()" from a parent class, the '
9581 'interpreter\n'
9582 ' must be told this explicitly by setting "__hash__ =\n'
9583 ' <ParentClass>.__hash__".\n'
9584 '\n'
9585 ' If a class that does not override "__eq__()" wishes to '
9586 'suppress\n'
9587 ' hash support, it should include "__hash__ = None" in the '
9588 'class\n'
9589 ' definition. A class which defines its own "__hash__()" '
9590 'that\n'
9591 ' explicitly raises a "TypeError" would be incorrectly '
9592 'identified as\n'
9593 ' hashable by an "isinstance(obj, '
9594 'collections.abc.Hashable)" call.\n'
9595 '\n'
9596 ' Note:\n'
9597 '\n'
9598 ' By default, the "__hash__()" values of str and bytes '
9599 'objects are\n'
9600 ' “salted” with an unpredictable random value. Although '
9601 'they\n'
9602 ' remain constant within an individual Python process, '
9603 'they are not\n'
9604 ' predictable between repeated invocations of Python.This '
9605 'is\n'
9606 ' intended to provide protection against a '
9607 'denial-of-service caused\n'
9608 ' by carefully chosen inputs that exploit the worst case\n'
9609 ' performance of a dict insertion, *O*(*n*^2) '
9610 'complexity. See\n'
9611 ' http://ocert.org/advisories/ocert-2011-003.html for\n'
9612 ' details.Changing hash values affects the iteration '
9613 'order of sets.\n'
9614 ' Python has never made guarantees about this ordering '
9615 '(and it\n'
9616 ' typically varies between 32-bit and 64-bit builds).See '
9617 'also\n'
9618 ' "PYTHONHASHSEED".\n'
9619 '\n'
9620 ' Changed in version 3.3: Hash randomization is enabled by '
9621 'default.\n'
9622 '\n'
9623 'object.__bool__(self)\n'
9624 '\n'
9625 ' Called to implement truth value testing and the built-in '
9626 'operation\n'
9627 ' "bool()"; should return "False" or "True". When this '
9628 'method is not\n'
9629 ' defined, "__len__()" is called, if it is defined, and the '
9630 'object is\n'
9631 ' considered true if its result is nonzero. If a class '
9632 'defines\n'
9633 ' neither "__len__()" nor "__bool__()", all its instances '
9634 'are\n'
9635 ' considered true.\n'
9636 '\n'
9637 '\n'
9638 'Customizing attribute access\n'
9639 '============================\n'
9640 '\n'
9641 'The following methods can be defined to customize the '
9642 'meaning of\n'
9643 'attribute access (use of, assignment to, or deletion of '
9644 '"x.name") for\n'
9645 'class instances.\n'
9646 '\n'
9647 'object.__getattr__(self, name)\n'
9648 '\n'
9649 ' Called when the default attribute access fails with an\n'
9650 ' "AttributeError" (either "__getattribute__()" raises an\n'
9651 ' "AttributeError" because *name* is not an instance '
9652 'attribute or an\n'
9653 ' attribute in the class tree for "self"; or "__get__()" of '
9654 'a *name*\n'
9655 ' property raises "AttributeError"). This method should '
9656 'either\n'
9657 ' return the (computed) attribute value or raise an '
9658 '"AttributeError"\n'
9659 ' exception.\n'
9660 '\n'
9661 ' Note that if the attribute is found through the normal '
9662 'mechanism,\n'
9663 ' "__getattr__()" is not called. (This is an intentional '
9664 'asymmetry\n'
9665 ' between "__getattr__()" and "__setattr__()".) This is '
9666 'done both for\n'
9667 ' efficiency reasons and because otherwise "__getattr__()" '
9668 'would have\n'
9669 ' no way to access other attributes of the instance. Note '
9670 'that at\n'
9671 ' least for instance variables, you can fake total control '
9672 'by not\n'
9673 ' inserting any values in the instance attribute dictionary '
9674 '(but\n'
9675 ' instead inserting them in another object). See the\n'
9676 ' "__getattribute__()" method below for a way to actually '
9677 'get total\n'
9678 ' control over attribute access.\n'
9679 '\n'
9680 'object.__getattribute__(self, name)\n'
9681 '\n'
9682 ' Called unconditionally to implement attribute accesses '
9683 'for\n'
9684 ' instances of the class. If the class also defines '
9685 '"__getattr__()",\n'
9686 ' the latter will not be called unless "__getattribute__()" '
9687 'either\n'
9688 ' calls it explicitly or raises an "AttributeError". This '
9689 'method\n'
9690 ' should return the (computed) attribute value or raise an\n'
9691 ' "AttributeError" exception. In order to avoid infinite '
9692 'recursion in\n'
9693 ' this method, its implementation should always call the '
9694 'base class\n'
9695 ' method with the same name to access any attributes it '
9696 'needs, for\n'
9697 ' example, "object.__getattribute__(self, name)".\n'
9698 '\n'
9699 ' Note:\n'
9700 '\n'
9701 ' This method may still be bypassed when looking up '
9702 'special methods\n'
9703 ' as the result of implicit invocation via language '
9704 'syntax or\n'
9705 ' built-in functions. See Special method lookup.\n'
9706 '\n'
9707 ' For certain sensitive attribute accesses, raises an '
9708 'auditing event\n'
9709 ' "object.__getattr__" with arguments "obj" and "name".\n'
9710 '\n'
9711 'object.__setattr__(self, name, value)\n'
9712 '\n'
9713 ' Called when an attribute assignment is attempted. This '
9714 'is called\n'
9715 ' instead of the normal mechanism (i.e. store the value in '
9716 'the\n'
9717 ' instance dictionary). *name* is the attribute name, '
9718 '*value* is the\n'
9719 ' value to be assigned to it.\n'
9720 '\n'
9721 ' If "__setattr__()" wants to assign to an instance '
9722 'attribute, it\n'
9723 ' should call the base class method with the same name, for '
9724 'example,\n'
9725 ' "object.__setattr__(self, name, value)".\n'
9726 '\n'
9727 ' For certain sensitive attribute assignments, raises an '
9728 'auditing\n'
9729 ' event "object.__setattr__" with arguments "obj", "name", '
9730 '"value".\n'
9731 '\n'
9732 'object.__delattr__(self, name)\n'
9733 '\n'
9734 ' Like "__setattr__()" but for attribute deletion instead '
9735 'of\n'
9736 ' assignment. This should only be implemented if "del '
9737 'obj.name" is\n'
9738 ' meaningful for the object.\n'
9739 '\n'
9740 ' For certain sensitive attribute deletions, raises an '
9741 'auditing event\n'
9742 ' "object.__delattr__" with arguments "obj" and "name".\n'
9743 '\n'
9744 'object.__dir__(self)\n'
9745 '\n'
9746 ' Called when "dir()" is called on the object. An iterable '
9747 'must be\n'
9748 ' returned. "dir()" converts the returned iterable to a '
9749 'list and\n'
9750 ' sorts it.\n'
9751 '\n'
9752 '\n'
9753 'Customizing module attribute access\n'
9754 '-----------------------------------\n'
9755 '\n'
9756 'Special names "__getattr__" and "__dir__" can be also used '
9757 'to\n'
9758 'customize access to module attributes. The "__getattr__" '
9759 'function at\n'
9760 'the module level should accept one argument which is the '
9761 'name of an\n'
9762 'attribute and return the computed value or raise an '
9763 '"AttributeError".\n'
9764 'If an attribute is not found on a module object through the '
9765 'normal\n'
9766 'lookup, i.e. "object.__getattribute__()", then "__getattr__" '
9767 'is\n'
9768 'searched in the module "__dict__" before raising an '
9769 '"AttributeError".\n'
9770 'If found, it is called with the attribute name and the '
9771 'result is\n'
9772 'returned.\n'
9773 '\n'
9774 'The "__dir__" function should accept no arguments, and '
9775 'return an\n'
9776 'iterable of strings that represents the names accessible on '
9777 'module. If\n'
9778 'present, this function overrides the standard "dir()" search '
9779 'on a\n'
9780 'module.\n'
9781 '\n'
9782 'For a more fine grained customization of the module behavior '
9783 '(setting\n'
9784 'attributes, properties, etc.), one can set the "__class__" '
9785 'attribute\n'
9786 'of a module object to a subclass of "types.ModuleType". For '
9787 'example:\n'
9788 '\n'
9789 ' import sys\n'
9790 ' from types import ModuleType\n'
9791 '\n'
9792 ' class VerboseModule(ModuleType):\n'
9793 ' def __repr__(self):\n'
9794 " return f'Verbose {self.__name__}'\n"
9795 '\n'
9796 ' def __setattr__(self, attr, value):\n'
9797 " print(f'Setting {attr}...')\n"
9798 ' super().__setattr__(attr, value)\n'
9799 '\n'
9800 ' sys.modules[__name__].__class__ = VerboseModule\n'
9801 '\n'
9802 'Note:\n'
9803 '\n'
9804 ' Defining module "__getattr__" and setting module '
9805 '"__class__" only\n'
9806 ' affect lookups made using the attribute access syntax – '
9807 'directly\n'
9808 ' accessing the module globals (whether by code within the '
9809 'module, or\n'
9810 ' via a reference to the module’s globals dictionary) is '
9811 'unaffected.\n'
9812 '\n'
9813 'Changed in version 3.5: "__class__" module attribute is now '
9814 'writable.\n'
9815 '\n'
9816 'New in version 3.7: "__getattr__" and "__dir__" module '
9817 'attributes.\n'
9818 '\n'
9819 'See also:\n'
9820 '\n'
9821 ' **PEP 562** - Module __getattr__ and __dir__\n'
9822 ' Describes the "__getattr__" and "__dir__" functions on '
9823 'modules.\n'
9824 '\n'
9825 '\n'
9826 'Implementing Descriptors\n'
9827 '------------------------\n'
9828 '\n'
9829 'The following methods only apply when an instance of the '
9830 'class\n'
9831 'containing the method (a so-called *descriptor* class) '
9832 'appears in an\n'
9833 '*owner* class (the descriptor must be in either the owner’s '
9834 'class\n'
9835 'dictionary or in the class dictionary for one of its '
9836 'parents). In the\n'
9837 'examples below, “the attribute” refers to the attribute '
9838 'whose name is\n'
9839 'the key of the property in the owner class’ "__dict__".\n'
9840 '\n'
9841 'object.__get__(self, instance, owner=None)\n'
9842 '\n'
9843 ' Called to get the attribute of the owner class (class '
9844 'attribute\n'
9845 ' access) or of an instance of that class (instance '
9846 'attribute\n'
9847 ' access). The optional *owner* argument is the owner '
9848 'class, while\n'
9849 ' *instance* is the instance that the attribute was '
9850 'accessed through,\n'
9851 ' or "None" when the attribute is accessed through the '
9852 '*owner*.\n'
9853 '\n'
9854 ' This method should return the computed attribute value or '
9855 'raise an\n'
9856 ' "AttributeError" exception.\n'
9857 '\n'
9858 ' **PEP 252** specifies that "__get__()" is callable with '
9859 'one or two\n'
9860 ' arguments. Python’s own built-in descriptors support '
9861 'this\n'
9862 ' specification; however, it is likely that some '
9863 'third-party tools\n'
9864 ' have descriptors that require both arguments. Python’s '
9865 'own\n'
9866 ' "__getattribute__()" implementation always passes in both '
9867 'arguments\n'
9868 ' whether they are required or not.\n'
9869 '\n'
9870 'object.__set__(self, instance, value)\n'
9871 '\n'
9872 ' Called to set the attribute on an instance *instance* of '
9873 'the owner\n'
9874 ' class to a new value, *value*.\n'
9875 '\n'
9876 ' Note, adding "__set__()" or "__delete__()" changes the '
9877 'kind of\n'
9878 ' descriptor to a “data descriptor”. See Invoking '
9879 'Descriptors for\n'
9880 ' more details.\n'
9881 '\n'
9882 'object.__delete__(self, instance)\n'
9883 '\n'
9884 ' Called to delete the attribute on an instance *instance* '
9885 'of the\n'
9886 ' owner class.\n'
9887 '\n'
9888 'Instances of descriptors may also have the "__objclass__" '
9889 'attribute\n'
9890 'present:\n'
9891 '\n'
9892 'object.__objclass__\n'
9893 '\n'
9894 ' The attribute "__objclass__" is interpreted by the '
9895 '"inspect" module\n'
9896 ' as specifying the class where this object was defined '
9897 '(setting this\n'
9898 ' appropriately can assist in runtime introspection of '
9899 'dynamic class\n'
9900 ' attributes). For callables, it may indicate that an '
9901 'instance of the\n'
9902 ' given type (or a subclass) is expected or required as the '
9903 'first\n'
9904 ' positional argument (for example, CPython sets this '
9905 'attribute for\n'
9906 ' unbound methods that are implemented in C).\n'
9907 '\n'
9908 '\n'
9909 'Invoking Descriptors\n'
9910 '--------------------\n'
9911 '\n'
9912 'In general, a descriptor is an object attribute with '
9913 '“binding\n'
9914 'behavior”, one whose attribute access has been overridden by '
9915 'methods\n'
9916 'in the descriptor protocol: "__get__()", "__set__()", and\n'
9917 '"__delete__()". If any of those methods are defined for an '
9918 'object, it\n'
9919 'is said to be a descriptor.\n'
9920 '\n'
9921 'The default behavior for attribute access is to get, set, or '
9922 'delete\n'
9923 'the attribute from an object’s dictionary. For instance, '
9924 '"a.x" has a\n'
9925 'lookup chain starting with "a.__dict__[\'x\']", then\n'
9926 '"type(a).__dict__[\'x\']", and continuing through the base '
9927 'classes of\n'
9928 '"type(a)" excluding metaclasses.\n'
9929 '\n'
9930 'However, if the looked-up value is an object defining one of '
9931 'the\n'
9932 'descriptor methods, then Python may override the default '
9933 'behavior and\n'
9934 'invoke the descriptor method instead. Where this occurs in '
9935 'the\n'
9936 'precedence chain depends on which descriptor methods were '
9937 'defined and\n'
9938 'how they were called.\n'
9939 '\n'
9940 'The starting point for descriptor invocation is a binding, '
9941 '"a.x". How\n'
9942 'the arguments are assembled depends on "a":\n'
9943 '\n'
9944 'Direct Call\n'
9945 ' The simplest and least common call is when user code '
9946 'directly\n'
9947 ' invokes a descriptor method: "x.__get__(a)".\n'
9948 '\n'
9949 'Instance Binding\n'
9950 ' If binding to an object instance, "a.x" is transformed '
9951 'into the\n'
9952 ' call: "type(a).__dict__[\'x\'].__get__(a, type(a))".\n'
9953 '\n'
9954 'Class Binding\n'
9955 ' If binding to a class, "A.x" is transformed into the '
9956 'call:\n'
9957 ' "A.__dict__[\'x\'].__get__(None, A)".\n'
9958 '\n'
9959 'Super Binding\n'
9960 ' A dotted lookup such as "super(A, a).x" searches\n'
9961 ' "a.__class__.__mro__" for a base class "B" following "A" '
9962 'and then\n'
9963 ' returns "B.__dict__[\'x\'].__get__(a, A)". If not a '
9964 'descriptor, "x"\n'
9965 ' is returned unchanged.\n'
9966 '\n'
9967 'For instance bindings, the precedence of descriptor '
9968 'invocation depends\n'
9969 'on which descriptor methods are defined. A descriptor can '
9970 'define any\n'
9971 'combination of "__get__()", "__set__()" and "__delete__()". '
9972 'If it\n'
9973 'does not define "__get__()", then accessing the attribute '
9974 'will return\n'
9975 'the descriptor object itself unless there is a value in the '
9976 'object’s\n'
9977 'instance dictionary. If the descriptor defines "__set__()" '
9978 'and/or\n'
9979 '"__delete__()", it is a data descriptor; if it defines '
9980 'neither, it is\n'
9981 'a non-data descriptor. Normally, data descriptors define '
9982 'both\n'
9983 '"__get__()" and "__set__()", while non-data descriptors have '
9984 'just the\n'
9985 '"__get__()" method. Data descriptors with "__get__()" and '
9986 '"__set__()"\n'
9987 '(and/or "__delete__()") defined always override a '
9988 'redefinition in an\n'
9989 'instance dictionary. In contrast, non-data descriptors can '
9990 'be\n'
9991 'overridden by instances.\n'
9992 '\n'
9993 'Python methods (including those decorated with '
9994 '"@staticmethod" and\n'
9995 '"@classmethod") are implemented as non-data descriptors. '
9996 'Accordingly,\n'
9997 'instances can redefine and override methods. This allows '
9998 'individual\n'
9999 'instances to acquire behaviors that differ from other '
10000 'instances of the\n'
10001 'same class.\n'
10002 '\n'
10003 'The "property()" function is implemented as a data '
10004 'descriptor.\n'
10005 'Accordingly, instances cannot override the behavior of a '
10006 'property.\n'
10007 '\n'
10008 '\n'
10009 '__slots__\n'
10010 '---------\n'
10011 '\n'
10012 '*__slots__* allow us to explicitly declare data members '
10013 '(like\n'
10014 'properties) and deny the creation of "__dict__" and '
10015 '*__weakref__*\n'
10016 '(unless explicitly declared in *__slots__* or available in a '
10017 'parent.)\n'
10018 '\n'
10019 'The space saved over using "__dict__" can be significant. '
10020 'Attribute\n'
10021 'lookup speed can be significantly improved as well.\n'
10022 '\n'
10023 'object.__slots__\n'
10024 '\n'
10025 ' This class variable can be assigned a string, iterable, '
10026 'or sequence\n'
10027 ' of strings with variable names used by instances. '
10028 '*__slots__*\n'
10029 ' reserves space for the declared variables and prevents '
10030 'the\n'
10031 ' automatic creation of "__dict__" and *__weakref__* for '
10032 'each\n'
10033 ' instance.\n'
10034 '\n'
10035 'Notes on using *__slots__*:\n'
10036 '\n'
10037 '* When inheriting from a class without *__slots__*, the '
10038 '"__dict__" and\n'
10039 ' *__weakref__* attribute of the instances will always be '
10040 'accessible.\n'
10041 '\n'
10042 '* Without a "__dict__" variable, instances cannot be '
10043 'assigned new\n'
10044 ' variables not listed in the *__slots__* definition. '
10045 'Attempts to\n'
10046 ' assign to an unlisted variable name raises '
10047 '"AttributeError". If\n'
10048 ' dynamic assignment of new variables is desired, then add\n'
10049 ' "\'__dict__\'" to the sequence of strings in the '
10050 '*__slots__*\n'
10051 ' declaration.\n'
10052 '\n'
10053 '* Without a *__weakref__* variable for each instance, '
10054 'classes defining\n'
10055 ' *__slots__* do not support "weak references" to its '
10056 'instances. If\n'
10057 ' weak reference support is needed, then add '
10058 '"\'__weakref__\'" to the\n'
10059 ' sequence of strings in the *__slots__* declaration.\n'
10060 '\n'
10061 '* *__slots__* are implemented at the class level by '
10062 'creating\n'
10063 ' descriptors for each variable name. As a result, class '
10064 'attributes\n'
10065 ' cannot be used to set default values for instance '
10066 'variables defined\n'
10067 ' by *__slots__*; otherwise, the class attribute would '
10068 'overwrite the\n'
10069 ' descriptor assignment.\n'
10070 '\n'
10071 '* The action of a *__slots__* declaration is not limited to '
10072 'the class\n'
10073 ' where it is defined. *__slots__* declared in parents are '
10074 'available\n'
10075 ' in child classes. However, child subclasses will get a '
10076 '"__dict__"\n'
10077 ' and *__weakref__* unless they also define *__slots__* '
10078 '(which should\n'
10079 ' only contain names of any *additional* slots).\n'
10080 '\n'
10081 '* If a class defines a slot also defined in a base class, '
10082 'the instance\n'
10083 ' variable defined by the base class slot is inaccessible '
10084 '(except by\n'
10085 ' retrieving its descriptor directly from the base class). '
10086 'This\n'
10087 ' renders the meaning of the program undefined. In the '
10088 'future, a\n'
10089 ' check may be added to prevent this.\n'
10090 '\n'
10091 '* "TypeError" will be raised if nonempty *__slots__* are '
10092 'defined for a\n'
10093 ' class derived from a ""variable-length" built-in type" '
10094 'such as\n'
10095 ' "int", "bytes", and "tuple".\n'
10096 '\n'
10097 '* Any non-string *iterable* may be assigned to *__slots__*.\n'
10098 '\n'
10099 '* If a "dictionary" is used to assign *__slots__*, the '
10100 'dictionary keys\n'
10101 ' will be used as the slot names. The values of the '
10102 'dictionary can be\n'
10103 ' used to provide per-attribute docstrings that will be '
10104 'recognised by\n'
10105 ' "inspect.getdoc()" and displayed in the output of '
10106 '"help()".\n'
10107 '\n'
10108 '* "__class__" assignment works only if both classes have the '
10109 'same\n'
10110 ' *__slots__*.\n'
10111 '\n'
10112 '* Multiple inheritance with multiple slotted parent classes '
10113 'can be\n'
10114 ' used, but only one parent is allowed to have attributes '
10115 'created by\n'
10116 ' slots (the other bases must have empty slot layouts) - '
10117 'violations\n'
10118 ' raise "TypeError".\n'
10119 '\n'
10120 '* If an *iterator* is used for *__slots__* then a '
10121 '*descriptor* is\n'
10122 ' created for each of the iterator’s values. However, the '
10123 '*__slots__*\n'
10124 ' attribute will be an empty iterator.\n'
10125 '\n'
10126 '\n'
10127 'Customizing class creation\n'
10128 '==========================\n'
10129 '\n'
10130 'Whenever a class inherits from another class, '
10131 '"__init_subclass__()" is\n'
10132 'called on the parent class. This way, it is possible to '
10133 'write classes\n'
10134 'which change the behavior of subclasses. This is closely '
10135 'related to\n'
10136 'class decorators, but where class decorators only affect the '
10137 'specific\n'
10138 'class they’re applied to, "__init_subclass__" solely applies '
10139 'to future\n'
10140 'subclasses of the class defining the method.\n'
10141 '\n'
10142 'classmethod object.__init_subclass__(cls)\n'
10143 '\n'
10144 ' This method is called whenever the containing class is '
10145 'subclassed.\n'
10146 ' *cls* is then the new subclass. If defined as a normal '
10147 'instance\n'
10148 ' method, this method is implicitly converted to a class '
10149 'method.\n'
10150 '\n'
10151 ' Keyword arguments which are given to a new class are '
10152 'passed to the\n'
10153 ' parent class’s "__init_subclass__". For compatibility '
10154 'with other\n'
10155 ' classes using "__init_subclass__", one should take out '
10156 'the needed\n'
10157 ' keyword arguments and pass the others over to the base '
10158 'class, as\n'
10159 ' in:\n'
10160 '\n'
10161 ' class Philosopher:\n'
10162 ' def __init_subclass__(cls, /, default_name, '
10163 '**kwargs):\n'
10164 ' super().__init_subclass__(**kwargs)\n'
10165 ' cls.default_name = default_name\n'
10166 '\n'
10167 ' class AustralianPhilosopher(Philosopher, '
10168 'default_name="Bruce"):\n'
10169 ' pass\n'
10170 '\n'
10171 ' The default implementation "object.__init_subclass__" '
10172 'does nothing,\n'
10173 ' but raises an error if it is called with any arguments.\n'
10174 '\n'
10175 ' Note:\n'
10176 '\n'
10177 ' The metaclass hint "metaclass" is consumed by the rest '
10178 'of the\n'
10179 ' type machinery, and is never passed to '
10180 '"__init_subclass__"\n'
10181 ' implementations. The actual metaclass (rather than the '
10182 'explicit\n'
10183 ' hint) can be accessed as "type(cls)".\n'
10184 '\n'
10185 ' New in version 3.6.\n'
10186 '\n'
10187 'When a class is created, "type.__new__()" scans the class '
10188 'variables\n'
10189 'and makes callbacks to those with a "__set_name__()" hook.\n'
10190 '\n'
10191 'object.__set_name__(self, owner, name)\n'
10192 '\n'
10193 ' Automatically called at the time the owning class *owner* '
10194 'is\n'
10195 ' created. The object has been assigned to *name* in that '
10196 'class:\n'
10197 '\n'
10198 ' class A:\n'
10199 ' x = C() # Automatically calls: x.__set_name__(A, '
10200 "'x')\n"
10201 '\n'
10202 ' If the class variable is assigned after the class is '
10203 'created,\n'
10204 ' "__set_name__()" will not be called automatically. If '
10205 'needed,\n'
10206 ' "__set_name__()" can be called directly:\n'
10207 '\n'
10208 ' class A:\n'
10209 ' pass\n'
10210 '\n'
10211 ' c = C()\n'
10212 ' A.x = c # The hook is not called\n'
10213 " c.__set_name__(A, 'x') # Manually invoke the hook\n"
10214 '\n'
10215 ' See Creating the class object for more details.\n'
10216 '\n'
10217 ' New in version 3.6.\n'
10218 '\n'
10219 '\n'
10220 'Metaclasses\n'
10221 '-----------\n'
10222 '\n'
10223 'By default, classes are constructed using "type()". The '
10224 'class body is\n'
10225 'executed in a new namespace and the class name is bound '
10226 'locally to the\n'
10227 'result of "type(name, bases, namespace)".\n'
10228 '\n'
10229 'The class creation process can be customized by passing the\n'
10230 '"metaclass" keyword argument in the class definition line, '
10231 'or by\n'
10232 'inheriting from an existing class that included such an '
10233 'argument. In\n'
10234 'the following example, both "MyClass" and "MySubclass" are '
10235 'instances\n'
10236 'of "Meta":\n'
10237 '\n'
10238 ' class Meta(type):\n'
10239 ' pass\n'
10240 '\n'
10241 ' class MyClass(metaclass=Meta):\n'
10242 ' pass\n'
10243 '\n'
10244 ' class MySubclass(MyClass):\n'
10245 ' pass\n'
10246 '\n'
10247 'Any other keyword arguments that are specified in the class '
10248 'definition\n'
10249 'are passed through to all metaclass operations described '
10250 'below.\n'
10251 '\n'
10252 'When a class definition is executed, the following steps '
10253 'occur:\n'
10254 '\n'
10255 '* MRO entries are resolved;\n'
10256 '\n'
10257 '* the appropriate metaclass is determined;\n'
10258 '\n'
10259 '* the class namespace is prepared;\n'
10260 '\n'
10261 '* the class body is executed;\n'
10262 '\n'
10263 '* the class object is created.\n'
10264 '\n'
10265 '\n'
10266 'Resolving MRO entries\n'
10267 '---------------------\n'
10268 '\n'
10269 'object.__mro_entries__(self, bases)\n'
10270 '\n'
10271 ' If a base that appears in a class definition is not an '
10272 'instance of\n'
10273 ' "type", then an "__mro_entries__()" method is searched on '
10274 'the base.\n'
10275 ' If an "__mro_entries__()" method is found, the base is '
10276 'substituted\n'
10277 ' with the result of a call to "__mro_entries__()" when '
10278 'creating the\n'
10279 ' class. The method is called with the original bases tuple '
10280 'passed to\n'
10281 ' the *bases* parameter, and must return a tuple of classes '
10282 'that will\n'
10283 ' be used instead of the base. The returned tuple may be '
10284 'empty: in\n'
10285 ' these cases, the original base is ignored.\n'
10286 '\n'
10287 'See also:\n'
10288 '\n'
10289 ' "types.resolve_bases()"\n'
10290 ' Dynamically resolve bases that are not instances of '
10291 '"type".\n'
10292 '\n'
10293 ' **PEP 560**\n'
10294 ' Core support for typing module and generic types.\n'
10295 '\n'
10296 '\n'
10297 'Determining the appropriate metaclass\n'
10298 '-------------------------------------\n'
10299 '\n'
10300 'The appropriate metaclass for a class definition is '
10301 'determined as\n'
10302 'follows:\n'
10303 '\n'
10304 '* if no bases and no explicit metaclass are given, then '
10305 '"type()" is\n'
10306 ' used;\n'
10307 '\n'
10308 '* if an explicit metaclass is given and it is *not* an '
10309 'instance of\n'
10310 ' "type()", then it is used directly as the metaclass;\n'
10311 '\n'
10312 '* if an instance of "type()" is given as the explicit '
10313 'metaclass, or\n'
10314 ' bases are defined, then the most derived metaclass is '
10315 'used.\n'
10316 '\n'
10317 'The most derived metaclass is selected from the explicitly '
10318 'specified\n'
10319 'metaclass (if any) and the metaclasses (i.e. "type(cls)") of '
10320 'all\n'
10321 'specified base classes. The most derived metaclass is one '
10322 'which is a\n'
10323 'subtype of *all* of these candidate metaclasses. If none of '
10324 'the\n'
10325 'candidate metaclasses meets that criterion, then the class '
10326 'definition\n'
10327 'will fail with "TypeError".\n'
10328 '\n'
10329 '\n'
10330 'Preparing the class namespace\n'
10331 '-----------------------------\n'
10332 '\n'
10333 'Once the appropriate metaclass has been identified, then the '
10334 'class\n'
10335 'namespace is prepared. If the metaclass has a "__prepare__" '
10336 'attribute,\n'
10337 'it is called as "namespace = metaclass.__prepare__(name, '
10338 'bases,\n'
10339 '**kwds)" (where the additional keyword arguments, if any, '
10340 'come from\n'
10341 'the class definition). The "__prepare__" method should be '
10342 'implemented\n'
10343 'as a "classmethod". The namespace returned by "__prepare__" '
10344 'is passed\n'
10345 'in to "__new__", but when the final class object is created '
10346 'the\n'
10347 'namespace is copied into a new "dict".\n'
10348 '\n'
10349 'If the metaclass has no "__prepare__" attribute, then the '
10350 'class\n'
10351 'namespace is initialised as an empty ordered mapping.\n'
10352 '\n'
10353 'See also:\n'
10354 '\n'
10355 ' **PEP 3115** - Metaclasses in Python 3000\n'
10356 ' Introduced the "__prepare__" namespace hook\n'
10357 '\n'
10358 '\n'
10359 'Executing the class body\n'
10360 '------------------------\n'
10361 '\n'
10362 'The class body is executed (approximately) as "exec(body, '
10363 'globals(),\n'
10364 'namespace)". The key difference from a normal call to '
10365 '"exec()" is that\n'
10366 'lexical scoping allows the class body (including any '
10367 'methods) to\n'
10368 'reference names from the current and outer scopes when the '
10369 'class\n'
10370 'definition occurs inside a function.\n'
10371 '\n'
10372 'However, even when the class definition occurs inside the '
10373 'function,\n'
10374 'methods defined inside the class still cannot see names '
10375 'defined at the\n'
10376 'class scope. Class variables must be accessed through the '
10377 'first\n'
10378 'parameter of instance or class methods, or through the '
10379 'implicit\n'
10380 'lexically scoped "__class__" reference described in the next '
10381 'section.\n'
10382 '\n'
10383 '\n'
10384 'Creating the class object\n'
10385 '-------------------------\n'
10386 '\n'
10387 'Once the class namespace has been populated by executing the '
10388 'class\n'
10389 'body, the class object is created by calling '
10390 '"metaclass(name, bases,\n'
10391 'namespace, **kwds)" (the additional keywords passed here are '
10392 'the same\n'
10393 'as those passed to "__prepare__").\n'
10394 '\n'
10395 'This class object is the one that will be referenced by the '
10396 'zero-\n'
10397 'argument form of "super()". "__class__" is an implicit '
10398 'closure\n'
10399 'reference created by the compiler if any methods in a class '
10400 'body refer\n'
10401 'to either "__class__" or "super". This allows the zero '
10402 'argument form\n'
10403 'of "super()" to correctly identify the class being defined '
10404 'based on\n'
10405 'lexical scoping, while the class or instance that was used '
10406 'to make the\n'
10407 'current call is identified based on the first argument '
10408 'passed to the\n'
10409 'method.\n'
10410 '\n'
10411 '**CPython implementation detail:** In CPython 3.6 and later, '
10412 'the\n'
10413 '"__class__" cell is passed to the metaclass as a '
10414 '"__classcell__" entry\n'
10415 'in the class namespace. If present, this must be propagated '
10416 'up to the\n'
10417 '"type.__new__" call in order for the class to be '
10418 'initialised\n'
10419 'correctly. Failing to do so will result in a "RuntimeError" '
10420 'in Python\n'
10421 '3.8.\n'
10422 '\n'
10423 'When using the default metaclass "type", or any metaclass '
10424 'that\n'
10425 'ultimately calls "type.__new__", the following additional\n'
10426 'customization steps are invoked after creating the class '
10427 'object:\n'
10428 '\n'
10429 '1. The "type.__new__" method collects all of the attributes '
10430 'in the\n'
10431 ' class namespace that define a "__set_name__()" method;\n'
10432 '\n'
10433 '2. Those "__set_name__" methods are called with the class '
10434 'being\n'
10435 ' defined and the assigned name of that particular '
10436 'attribute;\n'
10437 '\n'
10438 '3. The "__init_subclass__()" hook is called on the immediate '
10439 'parent of\n'
10440 ' the new class in its method resolution order.\n'
10441 '\n'
10442 'After the class object is created, it is passed to the '
10443 'class\n'
10444 'decorators included in the class definition (if any) and the '
10445 'resulting\n'
10446 'object is bound in the local namespace as the defined '
10447 'class.\n'
10448 '\n'
10449 'When a new class is created by "type.__new__", the object '
10450 'provided as\n'
10451 'the namespace parameter is copied to a new ordered mapping '
10452 'and the\n'
10453 'original object is discarded. The new copy is wrapped in a '
10454 'read-only\n'
10455 'proxy, which becomes the "__dict__" attribute of the class '
10456 'object.\n'
10457 '\n'
10458 'See also:\n'
10459 '\n'
10460 ' **PEP 3135** - New super\n'
10461 ' Describes the implicit "__class__" closure reference\n'
10462 '\n'
10463 '\n'
10464 'Uses for metaclasses\n'
10465 '--------------------\n'
10466 '\n'
10467 'The potential uses for metaclasses are boundless. Some ideas '
10468 'that have\n'
10469 'been explored include enum, logging, interface checking, '
10470 'automatic\n'
10471 'delegation, automatic property creation, proxies, '
10472 'frameworks, and\n'
10473 'automatic resource locking/synchronization.\n'
10474 '\n'
10475 '\n'
10476 'Customizing instance and subclass checks\n'
10477 '========================================\n'
10478 '\n'
10479 'The following methods are used to override the default '
10480 'behavior of the\n'
10481 '"isinstance()" and "issubclass()" built-in functions.\n'
10482 '\n'
10483 'In particular, the metaclass "abc.ABCMeta" implements these '
10484 'methods in\n'
10485 'order to allow the addition of Abstract Base Classes (ABCs) '
10486 'as\n'
10487 '“virtual base classes” to any class or type (including '
10488 'built-in\n'
10489 'types), including other ABCs.\n'
10490 '\n'
10491 'class.__instancecheck__(self, instance)\n'
10492 '\n'
10493 ' Return true if *instance* should be considered a (direct '
10494 'or\n'
10495 ' indirect) instance of *class*. If defined, called to '
10496 'implement\n'
10497 ' "isinstance(instance, class)".\n'
10498 '\n'
10499 'class.__subclasscheck__(self, subclass)\n'
10500 '\n'
10501 ' Return true if *subclass* should be considered a (direct '
10502 'or\n'
10503 ' indirect) subclass of *class*. If defined, called to '
10504 'implement\n'
10505 ' "issubclass(subclass, class)".\n'
10506 '\n'
10507 'Note that these methods are looked up on the type '
10508 '(metaclass) of a\n'
10509 'class. They cannot be defined as class methods in the '
10510 'actual class.\n'
10511 'This is consistent with the lookup of special methods that '
10512 'are called\n'
10513 'on instances, only in this case the instance is itself a '
10514 'class.\n'
10515 '\n'
10516 'See also:\n'
10517 '\n'
10518 ' **PEP 3119** - Introducing Abstract Base Classes\n'
10519 ' Includes the specification for customizing '
10520 '"isinstance()" and\n'
10521 ' "issubclass()" behavior through "__instancecheck__()" '
10522 'and\n'
10523 ' "__subclasscheck__()", with motivation for this '
10524 'functionality in\n'
10525 ' the context of adding Abstract Base Classes (see the '
10526 '"abc"\n'
10527 ' module) to the language.\n'
10528 '\n'
10529 '\n'
10530 'Emulating generic types\n'
10531 '=======================\n'
10532 '\n'
10533 'When using *type annotations*, it is often useful to '
10534 '*parameterize* a\n'
10535 '*generic type* using Python’s square-brackets notation. For '
10536 'example,\n'
10537 'the annotation "list[int]" might be used to signify a "list" '
10538 'in which\n'
10539 'all the elements are of type "int".\n'
10540 '\n'
10541 'See also:\n'
10542 '\n'
10543 ' **PEP 484** - Type Hints\n'
10544 ' Introducing Python’s framework for type annotations\n'
10545 '\n'
10546 ' Generic Alias Types\n'
10547 ' Documentation for objects representing parameterized '
10548 'generic\n'
10549 ' classes\n'
10550 '\n'
10551 ' Generics, user-defined generics and "typing.Generic"\n'
10552 ' Documentation on how to implement generic classes that '
10553 'can be\n'
10554 ' parameterized at runtime and understood by static '
10555 'type-checkers.\n'
10556 '\n'
10557 'A class can *generally* only be parameterized if it defines '
10558 'the\n'
10559 'special class method "__class_getitem__()".\n'
10560 '\n'
10561 'classmethod object.__class_getitem__(cls, key)\n'
10562 '\n'
10563 ' Return an object representing the specialization of a '
10564 'generic class\n'
10565 ' by type arguments found in *key*.\n'
10566 '\n'
10567 ' When defined on a class, "__class_getitem__()" is '
10568 'automatically a\n'
10569 ' class method. As such, there is no need for it to be '
10570 'decorated with\n'
10571 ' "@classmethod" when it is defined.\n'
10572 '\n'
10573 '\n'
10574 'The purpose of *__class_getitem__*\n'
10575 '----------------------------------\n'
10576 '\n'
10577 'The purpose of "__class_getitem__()" is to allow runtime\n'
10578 'parameterization of standard-library generic classes in '
10579 'order to more\n'
10580 'easily apply *type hints* to these classes.\n'
10581 '\n'
10582 'To implement custom generic classes that can be '
10583 'parameterized at\n'
10584 'runtime and understood by static type-checkers, users should '
10585 'either\n'
10586 'inherit from a standard library class that already '
10587 'implements\n'
10588 '"__class_getitem__()", or inherit from "typing.Generic", '
10589 'which has its\n'
10590 'own implementation of "__class_getitem__()".\n'
10591 '\n'
10592 'Custom implementations of "__class_getitem__()" on classes '
10593 'defined\n'
10594 'outside of the standard library may not be understood by '
10595 'third-party\n'
10596 'type-checkers such as mypy. Using "__class_getitem__()" on '
10597 'any class\n'
10598 'for purposes other than type hinting is discouraged.\n'
10599 '\n'
10600 '\n'
10601 '*__class_getitem__* versus *__getitem__*\n'
10602 '----------------------------------------\n'
10603 '\n'
10604 'Usually, the subscription of an object using square brackets '
10605 'will call\n'
10606 'the "__getitem__()" instance method defined on the object’s '
10607 'class.\n'
10608 'However, if the object being subscribed is itself a class, '
10609 'the class\n'
10610 'method "__class_getitem__()" may be called instead.\n'
10611 '"__class_getitem__()" should return a GenericAlias object if '
10612 'it is\n'
10613 'properly defined.\n'
10614 '\n'
10615 'Presented with the *expression* "obj[x]", the Python '
10616 'interpreter\n'
10617 'follows something like the following process to decide '
10618 'whether\n'
10619 '"__getitem__()" or "__class_getitem__()" should be called:\n'
10620 '\n'
10621 ' from inspect import isclass\n'
10622 '\n'
10623 ' def subscribe(obj, x):\n'
10624 ' """Return the result of the expression \'obj[x]\'"""\n'
10625 '\n'
10626 ' class_of_obj = type(obj)\n'
10627 '\n'
10628 ' # If the class of obj defines __getitem__,\n'
10629 ' # call class_of_obj.__getitem__(obj, x)\n'
10630 " if hasattr(class_of_obj, '__getitem__'):\n"
10631 ' return class_of_obj.__getitem__(obj, x)\n'
10632 '\n'
10633 ' # Else, if obj is a class and defines '
10634 '__class_getitem__,\n'
10635 ' # call obj.__class_getitem__(x)\n'
10636 ' elif isclass(obj) and hasattr(obj, '
10637 "'__class_getitem__'):\n"
10638 ' return obj.__class_getitem__(x)\n'
10639 '\n'
10640 ' # Else, raise an exception\n'
10641 ' else:\n'
10642 ' raise TypeError(\n'
10643 ' f"\'{class_of_obj.__name__}\' object is not '
10644 'subscriptable"\n'
10645 ' )\n'
10646 '\n'
10647 'In Python, all classes are themselves instances of other '
10648 'classes. The\n'
10649 'class of a class is known as that class’s *metaclass*, and '
10650 'most\n'
10651 'classes have the "type" class as their metaclass. "type" '
10652 'does not\n'
10653 'define "__getitem__()", meaning that expressions such as '
10654 '"list[int]",\n'
10655 '"dict[str, float]" and "tuple[str, bytes]" all result in\n'
10656 '"__class_getitem__()" being called:\n'
10657 '\n'
10658 ' >>> # list has class "type" as its metaclass, like most '
10659 'classes:\n'
10660 ' >>> type(list)\n'
10661 " <class 'type'>\n"
10662 ' >>> type(dict) == type(list) == type(tuple) == type(str) '
10663 '== type(bytes)\n'
10664 ' True\n'
10665 ' >>> # "list[int]" calls "list.__class_getitem__(int)"\n'
10666 ' >>> list[int]\n'
10667 ' list[int]\n'
10668 ' >>> # list.__class_getitem__ returns a GenericAlias '
10669 'object:\n'
10670 ' >>> type(list[int])\n'
10671 " <class 'types.GenericAlias'>\n"
10672 '\n'
10673 'However, if a class has a custom metaclass that defines\n'
10674 '"__getitem__()", subscribing the class may result in '
10675 'different\n'
10676 'behaviour. An example of this can be found in the "enum" '
10677 'module:\n'
10678 '\n'
10679 ' >>> from enum import Enum\n'
10680 ' >>> class Menu(Enum):\n'
10681 ' ... """A breakfast menu"""\n'
10682 " ... SPAM = 'spam'\n"
10683 " ... BACON = 'bacon'\n"
10684 ' ...\n'
10685 ' >>> # Enum classes have a custom metaclass:\n'
10686 ' >>> type(Menu)\n'
10687 " <class 'enum.EnumMeta'>\n"
10688 ' >>> # EnumMeta defines __getitem__,\n'
10689 ' >>> # so __class_getitem__ is not called,\n'
10690 ' >>> # and the result is not a GenericAlias object:\n'
10691 " >>> Menu['SPAM']\n"
10692 " <Menu.SPAM: 'spam'>\n"
10693 " >>> type(Menu['SPAM'])\n"
10694 " <enum 'Menu'>\n"
10695 '\n'
10696 'See also:\n'
10697 '\n'
10698 ' **PEP 560** - Core Support for typing module and generic '
10699 'types\n'
10700 ' Introducing "__class_getitem__()", and outlining when '
10701 'a\n'
10702 ' subscription results in "__class_getitem__()" being '
10703 'called\n'
10704 ' instead of "__getitem__()"\n'
10705 '\n'
10706 '\n'
10707 'Emulating callable objects\n'
10708 '==========================\n'
10709 '\n'
10710 'object.__call__(self[, args...])\n'
10711 '\n'
10712 ' Called when the instance is “called” as a function; if '
10713 'this method\n'
10714 ' is defined, "x(arg1, arg2, ...)" roughly translates to\n'
10715 ' "type(x).__call__(x, arg1, ...)".\n'
10716 '\n'
10717 '\n'
10718 'Emulating container types\n'
10719 '=========================\n'
10720 '\n'
10721 'The following methods can be defined to implement container '
10722 'objects.\n'
10723 'Containers usually are *sequences* (such as "lists" or '
10724 '"tuples") or\n'
10725 '*mappings* (like "dictionaries"), but can represent other '
10726 'containers\n'
10727 'as well. The first set of methods is used either to emulate '
10728 'a\n'
10729 'sequence or to emulate a mapping; the difference is that for '
10730 'a\n'
10731 'sequence, the allowable keys should be the integers *k* for '
10732 'which "0\n'
10733 '<= k < N" where *N* is the length of the sequence, or '
10734 '"slice" objects,\n'
10735 'which define a range of items. It is also recommended that '
10736 'mappings\n'
10737 'provide the methods "keys()", "values()", "items()", '
10738 '"get()",\n'
10739 '"clear()", "setdefault()", "pop()", "popitem()", "copy()", '
10740 'and\n'
10741 '"update()" behaving similar to those for Python’s standard\n'
10742 '"dictionary" objects. The "collections.abc" module provides '
10743 'a\n'
10744 '"MutableMapping" *abstract base class* to help create those '
10745 'methods\n'
10746 'from a base set of "__getitem__()", "__setitem__()", '
10747 '"__delitem__()",\n'
10748 'and "keys()". Mutable sequences should provide methods '
10749 '"append()",\n'
10750 '"count()", "index()", "extend()", "insert()", "pop()", '
10751 '"remove()",\n'
10752 '"reverse()" and "sort()", like Python standard "list" '
10753 'objects.\n'
10754 'Finally, sequence types should implement addition (meaning\n'
10755 'concatenation) and multiplication (meaning repetition) by '
10756 'defining the\n'
10757 'methods "__add__()", "__radd__()", "__iadd__()", '
10758 '"__mul__()",\n'
10759 '"__rmul__()" and "__imul__()" described below; they should '
10760 'not define\n'
10761 'other numerical operators. It is recommended that both '
10762 'mappings and\n'
10763 'sequences implement the "__contains__()" method to allow '
10764 'efficient use\n'
10765 'of the "in" operator; for mappings, "in" should search the '
10766 'mapping’s\n'
10767 'keys; for sequences, it should search through the values. '
10768 'It is\n'
10769 'further recommended that both mappings and sequences '
10770 'implement the\n'
10771 '"__iter__()" method to allow efficient iteration through '
10772 'the\n'
10773 'container; for mappings, "__iter__()" should iterate through '
10774 'the\n'
10775 'object’s keys; for sequences, it should iterate through the '
10776 'values.\n'
10777 '\n'
10778 'object.__len__(self)\n'
10779 '\n'
10780 ' Called to implement the built-in function "len()". '
10781 'Should return\n'
10782 ' the length of the object, an integer ">=" 0. Also, an '
10783 'object that\n'
10784 ' doesn’t define a "__bool__()" method and whose '
10785 '"__len__()" method\n'
10786 ' returns zero is considered to be false in a Boolean '
10787 'context.\n'
10788 '\n'
10789 ' **CPython implementation detail:** In CPython, the length '
10790 'is\n'
10791 ' required to be at most "sys.maxsize". If the length is '
10792 'larger than\n'
10793 ' "sys.maxsize" some features (such as "len()") may raise\n'
10794 ' "OverflowError". To prevent raising "OverflowError" by '
10795 'truth value\n'
10796 ' testing, an object must define a "__bool__()" method.\n'
10797 '\n'
10798 'object.__length_hint__(self)\n'
10799 '\n'
10800 ' Called to implement "operator.length_hint()". Should '
10801 'return an\n'
10802 ' estimated length for the object (which may be greater or '
10803 'less than\n'
10804 ' the actual length). The length must be an integer ">=" 0. '
10805 'The\n'
10806 ' return value may also be "NotImplemented", which is '
10807 'treated the\n'
10808 ' same as if the "__length_hint__" method didn’t exist at '
10809 'all. This\n'
10810 ' method is purely an optimization and is never required '
10811 'for\n'
10812 ' correctness.\n'
10813 '\n'
10814 ' New in version 3.4.\n'
10815 '\n'
10816 'Note:\n'
10817 '\n'
10818 ' Slicing is done exclusively with the following three '
10819 'methods. A\n'
10820 ' call like\n'
10821 '\n'
10822 ' a[1:2] = b\n'
10823 '\n'
10824 ' is translated to\n'
10825 '\n'
10826 ' a[slice(1, 2, None)] = b\n'
10827 '\n'
10828 ' and so forth. Missing slice items are always filled in '
10829 'with "None".\n'
10830 '\n'
10831 'object.__getitem__(self, key)\n'
10832 '\n'
10833 ' Called to implement evaluation of "self[key]". For '
10834 '*sequence*\n'
10835 ' types, the accepted keys should be integers. Optionally, '
10836 'they may\n'
10837 ' support "slice" objects as well. Negative index support '
10838 'is also\n'
10839 ' optional. If *key* is of an inappropriate type, '
10840 '"TypeError" may be\n'
10841 ' raised; if *key* is a value outside the set of indexes '
10842 'for the\n'
10843 ' sequence (after any special interpretation of negative '
10844 'values),\n'
10845 ' "IndexError" should be raised. For *mapping* types, if '
10846 '*key* is\n'
10847 ' missing (not in the container), "KeyError" should be '
10848 'raised.\n'
10849 '\n'
10850 ' Note:\n'
10851 '\n'
10852 ' "for" loops expect that an "IndexError" will be raised '
10853 'for\n'
10854 ' illegal indexes to allow proper detection of the end of '
10855 'the\n'
10856 ' sequence.\n'
10857 '\n'
10858 ' Note:\n'
10859 '\n'
10860 ' When subscripting a *class*, the special class method\n'
10861 ' "__class_getitem__()" may be called instead of '
10862 '"__getitem__()".\n'
10863 ' See __class_getitem__ versus __getitem__ for more '
10864 'details.\n'
10865 '\n'
10866 'object.__setitem__(self, key, value)\n'
10867 '\n'
10868 ' Called to implement assignment to "self[key]". Same note '
10869 'as for\n'
10870 ' "__getitem__()". This should only be implemented for '
10871 'mappings if\n'
10872 ' the objects support changes to the values for keys, or if '
10873 'new keys\n'
10874 ' can be added, or for sequences if elements can be '
10875 'replaced. The\n'
10876 ' same exceptions should be raised for improper *key* '
10877 'values as for\n'
10878 ' the "__getitem__()" method.\n'
10879 '\n'
10880 'object.__delitem__(self, key)\n'
10881 '\n'
10882 ' Called to implement deletion of "self[key]". Same note '
10883 'as for\n'
10884 ' "__getitem__()". This should only be implemented for '
10885 'mappings if\n'
10886 ' the objects support removal of keys, or for sequences if '
10887 'elements\n'
10888 ' can be removed from the sequence. The same exceptions '
10889 'should be\n'
10890 ' raised for improper *key* values as for the '
10891 '"__getitem__()" method.\n'
10892 '\n'
10893 'object.__missing__(self, key)\n'
10894 '\n'
10895 ' Called by "dict"."__getitem__()" to implement "self[key]" '
10896 'for dict\n'
10897 ' subclasses when key is not in the dictionary.\n'
10898 '\n'
10899 'object.__iter__(self)\n'
10900 '\n'
10901 ' This method is called when an *iterator* is required for '
10902 'a\n'
10903 ' container. This method should return a new iterator '
10904 'object that can\n'
10905 ' iterate over all the objects in the container. For '
10906 'mappings, it\n'
10907 ' should iterate over the keys of the container.\n'
10908 '\n'
10909 'object.__reversed__(self)\n'
10910 '\n'
10911 ' Called (if present) by the "reversed()" built-in to '
10912 'implement\n'
10913 ' reverse iteration. It should return a new iterator '
10914 'object that\n'
10915 ' iterates over all the objects in the container in reverse '
10916 'order.\n'
10917 '\n'
10918 ' If the "__reversed__()" method is not provided, the '
10919 '"reversed()"\n'
10920 ' built-in will fall back to using the sequence protocol '
10921 '("__len__()"\n'
10922 ' and "__getitem__()"). Objects that support the sequence '
10923 'protocol\n'
10924 ' should only provide "__reversed__()" if they can provide '
10925 'an\n'
10926 ' implementation that is more efficient than the one '
10927 'provided by\n'
10928 ' "reversed()".\n'
10929 '\n'
10930 'The membership test operators ("in" and "not in") are '
10931 'normally\n'
10932 'implemented as an iteration through a container. However, '
10933 'container\n'
10934 'objects can supply the following special method with a more '
10935 'efficient\n'
10936 'implementation, which also does not require the object be '
10937 'iterable.\n'
10938 '\n'
10939 'object.__contains__(self, item)\n'
10940 '\n'
10941 ' Called to implement membership test operators. Should '
10942 'return true\n'
10943 ' if *item* is in *self*, false otherwise. For mapping '
10944 'objects, this\n'
10945 ' should consider the keys of the mapping rather than the '
10946 'values or\n'
10947 ' the key-item pairs.\n'
10948 '\n'
10949 ' For objects that don’t define "__contains__()", the '
10950 'membership test\n'
10951 ' first tries iteration via "__iter__()", then the old '
10952 'sequence\n'
10953 ' iteration protocol via "__getitem__()", see this section '
10954 'in the\n'
10955 ' language reference.\n'
10956 '\n'
10957 '\n'
10958 'Emulating numeric types\n'
10959 '=======================\n'
10960 '\n'
10961 'The following methods can be defined to emulate numeric '
10962 'objects.\n'
10963 'Methods corresponding to operations that are not supported '
10964 'by the\n'
10965 'particular kind of number implemented (e.g., bitwise '
10966 'operations for\n'
10967 'non-integral numbers) should be left undefined.\n'
10968 '\n'
10969 'object.__add__(self, other)\n'
10970 'object.__sub__(self, other)\n'
10971 'object.__mul__(self, other)\n'
10972 'object.__matmul__(self, other)\n'
10973 'object.__truediv__(self, other)\n'
10974 'object.__floordiv__(self, other)\n'
10975 'object.__mod__(self, other)\n'
10976 'object.__divmod__(self, other)\n'
10977 'object.__pow__(self, other[, modulo])\n'
10978 'object.__lshift__(self, other)\n'
10979 'object.__rshift__(self, other)\n'
10980 'object.__and__(self, other)\n'
10981 'object.__xor__(self, other)\n'
10982 'object.__or__(self, other)\n'
10983 '\n'
10984 ' These methods are called to implement the binary '
10985 'arithmetic\n'
10986 ' operations ("+", "-", "*", "@", "/", "//", "%", '
10987 '"divmod()",\n'
10988 ' "pow()", "**", "<<", ">>", "&", "^", "|"). For instance, '
10989 'to\n'
10990 ' evaluate the expression "x + y", where *x* is an instance '
10991 'of a\n'
10992 ' class that has an "__add__()" method, "type(x).__add__(x, '
10993 'y)" is\n'
10994 ' called. The "__divmod__()" method should be the '
10995 'equivalent to\n'
10996 ' using "__floordiv__()" and "__mod__()"; it should not be '
10997 'related to\n'
10998 ' "__truediv__()". Note that "__pow__()" should be defined '
10999 'to accept\n'
11000 ' an optional third argument if the ternary version of the '
11001 'built-in\n'
11002 ' "pow()" function is to be supported.\n'
11003 '\n'
11004 ' If one of those methods does not support the operation '
11005 'with the\n'
11006 ' supplied arguments, it should return "NotImplemented".\n'
11007 '\n'
11008 'object.__radd__(self, other)\n'
11009 'object.__rsub__(self, other)\n'
11010 'object.__rmul__(self, other)\n'
11011 'object.__rmatmul__(self, other)\n'
11012 'object.__rtruediv__(self, other)\n'
11013 'object.__rfloordiv__(self, other)\n'
11014 'object.__rmod__(self, other)\n'
11015 'object.__rdivmod__(self, other)\n'
11016 'object.__rpow__(self, other[, modulo])\n'
11017 'object.__rlshift__(self, other)\n'
11018 'object.__rrshift__(self, other)\n'
11019 'object.__rand__(self, other)\n'
11020 'object.__rxor__(self, other)\n'
11021 'object.__ror__(self, other)\n'
11022 '\n'
11023 ' These methods are called to implement the binary '
11024 'arithmetic\n'
11025 ' operations ("+", "-", "*", "@", "/", "//", "%", '
11026 '"divmod()",\n'
11027 ' "pow()", "**", "<<", ">>", "&", "^", "|") with reflected '
11028 '(swapped)\n'
11029 ' operands. These functions are only called if the left '
11030 'operand does\n'
11031 ' not support the corresponding operation [3] and the '
11032 'operands are of\n'
11033 ' different types. [4] For instance, to evaluate the '
11034 'expression "x -\n'
11035 ' y", where *y* is an instance of a class that has an '
11036 '"__rsub__()"\n'
11037 ' method, "type(y).__rsub__(y, x)" is called if '
11038 '"type(x).__sub__(x,\n'
11039 ' y)" returns "NotImplemented".\n'
11040 '\n'
11041 ' Note that ternary "pow()" will not try calling '
11042 '"__rpow__()" (the\n'
11043 ' coercion rules would become too complicated).\n'
11044 '\n'
11045 ' Note:\n'
11046 '\n'
11047 ' If the right operand’s type is a subclass of the left '
11048 'operand’s\n'
11049 ' type and that subclass provides a different '
11050 'implementation of the\n'
11051 ' reflected method for the operation, this method will be '
11052 'called\n'
11053 ' before the left operand’s non-reflected method. This '
11054 'behavior\n'
11055 ' allows subclasses to override their ancestors’ '
11056 'operations.\n'
11057 '\n'
11058 'object.__iadd__(self, other)\n'
11059 'object.__isub__(self, other)\n'
11060 'object.__imul__(self, other)\n'
11061 'object.__imatmul__(self, other)\n'
11062 'object.__itruediv__(self, other)\n'
11063 'object.__ifloordiv__(self, other)\n'
11064 'object.__imod__(self, other)\n'
11065 'object.__ipow__(self, other[, modulo])\n'
11066 'object.__ilshift__(self, other)\n'
11067 'object.__irshift__(self, other)\n'
11068 'object.__iand__(self, other)\n'
11069 'object.__ixor__(self, other)\n'
11070 'object.__ior__(self, other)\n'
11071 '\n'
11072 ' These methods are called to implement the augmented '
11073 'arithmetic\n'
11074 ' assignments ("+=", "-=", "*=", "@=", "/=", "//=", "%=", '
11075 '"**=",\n'
11076 ' "<<=", ">>=", "&=", "^=", "|="). These methods should '
11077 'attempt to\n'
11078 ' do the operation in-place (modifying *self*) and return '
11079 'the result\n'
11080 ' (which could be, but does not have to be, *self*). If a '
11081 'specific\n'
11082 ' method is not defined, or if that method returns '
11083 '"NotImplemented",\n'
11084 ' the augmented assignment falls back to the normal '
11085 'methods. For\n'
11086 ' instance, if *x* is an instance of a class with an '
11087 '"__iadd__()"\n'
11088 ' method, "x += y" is equivalent to "x = x.__iadd__(y)" . '
11089 'If\n'
11090 ' "__iadd__()" does not exist, or if "x.__iadd__(y)" '
11091 'returns\n'
11092 ' "NotImplemented", "x.__add__(y)" and "y.__radd__(x)" are\n'
11093 ' considered, as with the evaluation of "x + y". In '
11094 'certain\n'
11095 ' situations, augmented assignment can result in unexpected '
11096 'errors\n'
11097 ' (see Why does a_tuple[i] += [‘item’] raise an exception '
11098 'when the\n'
11099 ' addition works?), but this behavior is in fact part of '
11100 'the data\n'
11101 ' model.\n'
11102 '\n'
11103 'object.__neg__(self)\n'
11104 'object.__pos__(self)\n'
11105 'object.__abs__(self)\n'
11106 'object.__invert__(self)\n'
11107 '\n'
11108 ' Called to implement the unary arithmetic operations ("-", '
11109 '"+",\n'
11110 ' "abs()" and "~").\n'
11111 '\n'
11112 'object.__complex__(self)\n'
11113 'object.__int__(self)\n'
11114 'object.__float__(self)\n'
11115 '\n'
11116 ' Called to implement the built-in functions "complex()", '
11117 '"int()" and\n'
11118 ' "float()". Should return a value of the appropriate '
11119 'type.\n'
11120 '\n'
11121 'object.__index__(self)\n'
11122 '\n'
11123 ' Called to implement "operator.index()", and whenever '
11124 'Python needs\n'
11125 ' to losslessly convert the numeric object to an integer '
11126 'object (such\n'
11127 ' as in slicing, or in the built-in "bin()", "hex()" and '
11128 '"oct()"\n'
11129 ' functions). Presence of this method indicates that the '
11130 'numeric\n'
11131 ' object is an integer type. Must return an integer.\n'
11132 '\n'
11133 ' If "__int__()", "__float__()" and "__complex__()" are not '
11134 'defined\n'
11135 ' then corresponding built-in functions "int()", "float()" '
11136 'and\n'
11137 ' "complex()" fall back to "__index__()".\n'
11138 '\n'
11139 'object.__round__(self[, ndigits])\n'
11140 'object.__trunc__(self)\n'
11141 'object.__floor__(self)\n'
11142 'object.__ceil__(self)\n'
11143 '\n'
11144 ' Called to implement the built-in function "round()" and '
11145 '"math"\n'
11146 ' functions "trunc()", "floor()" and "ceil()". Unless '
11147 '*ndigits* is\n'
11148 ' passed to "__round__()" all these methods should return '
11149 'the value\n'
11150 ' of the object truncated to an "Integral" (typically an '
11151 '"int").\n'
11152 '\n'
11153 ' The built-in function "int()" falls back to "__trunc__()" '
11154 'if\n'
11155 ' neither "__int__()" nor "__index__()" is defined.\n'
11156 '\n'
11157 ' Changed in version 3.11: The delegation of "int()" to '
11158 '"__trunc__()"\n'
11159 ' is deprecated.\n'
11160 '\n'
11161 '\n'
11162 'With Statement Context Managers\n'
11163 '===============================\n'
11164 '\n'
11165 'A *context manager* is an object that defines the runtime '
11166 'context to\n'
11167 'be established when executing a "with" statement. The '
11168 'context manager\n'
11169 'handles the entry into, and the exit from, the desired '
11170 'runtime context\n'
11171 'for the execution of the block of code. Context managers '
11172 'are normally\n'
11173 'invoked using the "with" statement (described in section The '
11174 'with\n'
11175 'statement), but can also be used by directly invoking their '
11176 'methods.\n'
11177 '\n'
11178 'Typical uses of context managers include saving and '
11179 'restoring various\n'
11180 'kinds of global state, locking and unlocking resources, '
11181 'closing opened\n'
11182 'files, etc.\n'
11183 '\n'
11184 'For more information on context managers, see Context '
11185 'Manager Types.\n'
11186 '\n'
11187 'object.__enter__(self)\n'
11188 '\n'
11189 ' Enter the runtime context related to this object. The '
11190 '"with"\n'
11191 ' statement will bind this method’s return value to the '
11192 'target(s)\n'
11193 ' specified in the "as" clause of the statement, if any.\n'
11194 '\n'
11195 'object.__exit__(self, exc_type, exc_value, traceback)\n'
11196 '\n'
11197 ' Exit the runtime context related to this object. The '
11198 'parameters\n'
11199 ' describe the exception that caused the context to be '
11200 'exited. If the\n'
11201 ' context was exited without an exception, all three '
11202 'arguments will\n'
11203 ' be "None".\n'
11204 '\n'
11205 ' If an exception is supplied, and the method wishes to '
11206 'suppress the\n'
11207 ' exception (i.e., prevent it from being propagated), it '
11208 'should\n'
11209 ' return a true value. Otherwise, the exception will be '
11210 'processed\n'
11211 ' normally upon exit from this method.\n'
11212 '\n'
11213 ' Note that "__exit__()" methods should not reraise the '
11214 'passed-in\n'
11215 ' exception; this is the caller’s responsibility.\n'
11216 '\n'
11217 'See also:\n'
11218 '\n'
11219 ' **PEP 343** - The “with” statement\n'
11220 ' The specification, background, and examples for the '
11221 'Python "with"\n'
11222 ' statement.\n'
11223 '\n'
11224 '\n'
11225 'Customizing positional arguments in class pattern matching\n'
11226 '==========================================================\n'
11227 '\n'
11228 'When using a class name in a pattern, positional arguments '
11229 'in the\n'
11230 'pattern are not allowed by default, i.e. "case MyClass(x, '
11231 'y)" is\n'
11232 'typically invalid without special support in "MyClass". To '
11233 'be able to\n'
11234 'use that kind of pattern, the class needs to define a '
11235 '*__match_args__*\n'
11236 'attribute.\n'
11237 '\n'
11238 'object.__match_args__\n'
11239 '\n'
11240 ' This class variable can be assigned a tuple of strings. '
11241 'When this\n'
11242 ' class is used in a class pattern with positional '
11243 'arguments, each\n'
11244 ' positional argument will be converted into a keyword '
11245 'argument,\n'
11246 ' using the corresponding value in *__match_args__* as the '
11247 'keyword.\n'
11248 ' The absence of this attribute is equivalent to setting it '
11249 'to "()".\n'
11250 '\n'
11251 'For example, if "MyClass.__match_args__" is "("left", '
11252 '"center",\n'
11253 '"right")" that means that "case MyClass(x, y)" is equivalent '
11254 'to "case\n'
11255 'MyClass(left=x, center=y)". Note that the number of '
11256 'arguments in the\n'
11257 'pattern must be smaller than or equal to the number of '
11258 'elements in\n'
11259 '*__match_args__*; if it is larger, the pattern match attempt '
11260 'will\n'
11261 'raise a "TypeError".\n'
11262 '\n'
11263 'New in version 3.10.\n'
11264 '\n'
11265 'See also:\n'
11266 '\n'
11267 ' **PEP 634** - Structural Pattern Matching\n'
11268 ' The specification for the Python "match" statement.\n'
11269 '\n'
11270 '\n'
11271 'Special method lookup\n'
11272 '=====================\n'
11273 '\n'
11274 'For custom classes, implicit invocations of special methods '
11275 'are only\n'
11276 'guaranteed to work correctly if defined on an object’s type, '
11277 'not in\n'
11278 'the object’s instance dictionary. That behaviour is the '
11279 'reason why\n'
11280 'the following code raises an exception:\n'
11281 '\n'
11282 ' >>> class C:\n'
11283 ' ... pass\n'
11284 ' ...\n'
11285 ' >>> c = C()\n'
11286 ' >>> c.__len__ = lambda: 5\n'
11287 ' >>> len(c)\n'
11288 ' Traceback (most recent call last):\n'
11289 ' File "<stdin>", line 1, in <module>\n'
11290 " TypeError: object of type 'C' has no len()\n"
11291 '\n'
11292 'The rationale behind this behaviour lies with a number of '
11293 'special\n'
11294 'methods such as "__hash__()" and "__repr__()" that are '
11295 'implemented by\n'
11296 'all objects, including type objects. If the implicit lookup '
11297 'of these\n'
11298 'methods used the conventional lookup process, they would '
11299 'fail when\n'
11300 'invoked on the type object itself:\n'
11301 '\n'
11302 ' >>> 1 .__hash__() == hash(1)\n'
11303 ' True\n'
11304 ' >>> int.__hash__() == hash(int)\n'
11305 ' Traceback (most recent call last):\n'
11306 ' File "<stdin>", line 1, in <module>\n'
11307 " TypeError: descriptor '__hash__' of 'int' object needs an "
11308 'argument\n'
11309 '\n'
11310 'Incorrectly attempting to invoke an unbound method of a '
11311 'class in this\n'
11312 'way is sometimes referred to as ‘metaclass confusion’, and '
11313 'is avoided\n'
11314 'by bypassing the instance when looking up special methods:\n'
11315 '\n'
11316 ' >>> type(1).__hash__(1) == hash(1)\n'
11317 ' True\n'
11318 ' >>> type(int).__hash__(int) == hash(int)\n'
11319 ' True\n'
11320 '\n'
11321 'In addition to bypassing any instance attributes in the '
11322 'interest of\n'
11323 'correctness, implicit special method lookup generally also '
11324 'bypasses\n'
11325 'the "__getattribute__()" method even of the object’s '
11326 'metaclass:\n'
11327 '\n'
11328 ' >>> class Meta(type):\n'
11329 ' ... def __getattribute__(*args):\n'
11330 ' ... print("Metaclass getattribute invoked")\n'
11331 ' ... return type.__getattribute__(*args)\n'
11332 ' ...\n'
11333 ' >>> class C(object, metaclass=Meta):\n'
11334 ' ... def __len__(self):\n'
11335 ' ... return 10\n'
11336 ' ... def __getattribute__(*args):\n'
11337 ' ... print("Class getattribute invoked")\n'
11338 ' ... return object.__getattribute__(*args)\n'
11339 ' ...\n'
11340 ' >>> c = C()\n'
11341 ' >>> c.__len__() # Explicit lookup via '
11342 'instance\n'
11343 ' Class getattribute invoked\n'
11344 ' 10\n'
11345 ' >>> type(c).__len__(c) # Explicit lookup via '
11346 'type\n'
11347 ' Metaclass getattribute invoked\n'
11348 ' 10\n'
11349 ' >>> len(c) # Implicit lookup\n'
11350 ' 10\n'
11351 '\n'
11352 'Bypassing the "__getattribute__()" machinery in this fashion '
11353 'provides\n'
11354 'significant scope for speed optimisations within the '
11355 'interpreter, at\n'
11356 'the cost of some flexibility in the handling of special '
11357 'methods (the\n'
11358 'special method *must* be set on the class object itself in '
11359 'order to be\n'
11360 'consistently invoked by the interpreter).\n',

12022 " >>> '1,2,,3,'.split(',')\n"
12023 " ['1', '2', '', '3', '']\n"

12026 'splitting\n'

12030 'empty strings\n'
